<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0802 04-08 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0802,0852</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Conrad and Weatherby; AMs separates moved as a0613 on
Hamilton, a0615 on Firouz, a0616 on Polak and a0741 on Bray. A
separate on Hamilton also moved on the business wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Denis Hamilton</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denis Hamilton, 69, a leading figure in the
British newspaper industry for more than four decades and a former
chairman of the Reuters news agency, died Thursday.
   Hamilton began his career as a cub reporter on the Middlesbrough
Evening Gazette in northern England in 1936. At age 28, he became
personal assistant to newspaper proprietor Lord Kemsley.
   Hamilton became editor of the London Sunday Times, weekly
companion of the Times of London, when Canadian Lord Thomson bought
the newspapers in 1959, as well as editorial director of the group.
He was also editor-in-chief of Times Newspapers Ltd.
   Hamilton served as chairman of Reuters from 1979 to 1985 during
the British-based agency's expansion of its financial news
services. He was also the first president from 1978 until 1983 of
the International Press Institute, an organization of more than 200
editors and publishers.
   Hamilton introduced the color magazine supplement, now a feature
of all the big national weekly newpapers, into British journalism.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Mozaffar Firouz</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozaffar Firouz, a former Iranian vice premier who
was known as the ``Red Prince'' for his close ties with the Tudeh
Communist party, died at age 83. Members of his family did not say
when he died.
   Firouz took part in negotations in 1946 on the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from the Iranian part of Azerbaijan in the aftermath
of World War II. He also held the labor ministry portfolio and
helped draw up Iran's first labor code.
   Firouz eventually was named ambassador to the Soviet Union but
resigned the post in 1947 to protest what he called undemocratic
policies of Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi. He moved to Paris and
published articles and books attacking the shah.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Andre Polak</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andre Polak, a architect who helped
design the Brussels Atomium momument for the 1958 World Fair, died
Saturday of a heart attack. He was 74.
   Polak created the structure along with his brother, Jean. The
structure resembles an iron molecule to symbolize the power of
science, the atomic age and Belgian industrial acumen of the 1950s.
The nine huge spheres of the 335-foot-tall Atomium still dominate
the cityscape of suburban Laken.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jeanne Bray</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeanne Bray, a five-time national women's
police revolver champion and a 28-year veteran of the Columbus
police force, died Wednesday at the age of 56.
   Ms. Bray won the National Women's Police Combat Pistol
Championship, sponsored by the National Rifle Association, in 1962,
1963, 1964, 1965 and 1967.
   In 1984, Ms. Bray was a nominee for the Outstanding American
Handgunner Award. Considered an authority on personal protection,
she traveled widely to lecture on the subject. Ms. Bray filmed a
self-defense program for Dutch television and developed a slide
show for baby sitters.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Allen Kingman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allen Frederick Kingman, a brigadier
general who served in both World Wars and was awarded military
honors from a half-dozen foreign countries, died Monday at age 94.
   Kingman was commissioned as a second lieutenant of infantry and
served on the Mexican border during the United States' 1916-1917
effort to capture Pancho Villa. In World War I, he went to France
with the 16th Infantry of the First Division, the first company to
land in France. In World War II, Kingman served with the Second
Armored Division. He retired in 1953.
   During his 36 years in the Army, Kingman received the Legion of
Merit, the Bronze Star, the Commendation Medal and the Purple
Heart. France honored him with the Croix De Guerre with Palm for
bravery in combat, and he received the Brazilian War Medal.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Francis Conrad</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Francis E. Conrad, a high-level Veterans
Administration official, was stabbed to death Thursday at the age
of 51.
   Conrad had private practices in Philadelphia and Stony Brook
before joining the VA in 1973 as a staff psychiatrist. He was a
former associate professor of clinical psychiatry and associate
dean of veterans affairs at State University of New York, Stony
Brook.
   In 1985, Conrad became director of the office of quality
assurance, responsible for all quality-assurance programs in VA
health systems, which include 172 hospitals and 229 clinics
nationwide.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Roy Weatherby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy E. Weatherby Sr., creator of the
famed Weatherby rifle favored by big game hunters and a leading
authority on firearms and ballistics, died Tuesday after heart
surgery. He was 77.
   It was Weatherby's perfection of his theory on high velocity and
the resulting Weatherby Magnum cartiridges that led to the
development of the Weatherby rifle.
   The Weatherby Big Game Trophy, created in 1956, is prized in the
hunting world. Weatherby retired from active participation in the
company's affairs in December 1986.
</TEXT>
