<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:Oscars-SupportingActor     04-08 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Oscars-Supporting Actor,0952</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Supporting Actor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supporting Actor Nominees Are Diverse and None Has Won Before</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race for best supporting actor of 1987
provides Academy voters a choice among a perspiring TV reporter, a
steely Chicago cop, a philandering Brooklyn husband, a wily New
York City pimp and a South African martyr.
   The nominees are a diverse lot, ranging from the first James
Bond to a stand-up comedian. None has ever won an Oscar.
   Sean Connery is generally considered the quintessential 007, a
role that seemed impossible for him to escape. But after 30 years
in films, he has finally been recognized for his performance as
another enforcer, the Irish beat cop Jimmy Malone in ``The
Untouchables.''
   ``I thought it was a very clever concept to take the old cop and
use him as a kind of old dog who teaches a new dog tricks,'' says
Connery of his role as mentor to the young federal agent, Kevin
Costner.
   Yet Connery is maintaining a classic Bond cool over the
possibility of winning his first Oscar. ``To be honest, I've never
really spent much time thinking about it before,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``I just go on with my work.''
   Neither is he bitter that it has taken the Academy some 40 films
to even nominate him. ``It's all a matter of timing and how your
films and image are presented,'' Connery told the Hollywood
Reporter. ``There are a lot of my films which I'm very proud of,
which I think were artistic successes, but weren't huge box office
successes like the Bond pictures.''
   There's no chance, though, that Connery will snub the Academy if
he wins. ``It'd be important to me, and I'd definitely turn up to
collect it. I'm not one of those actors who'd send along the
cleaning lady instead.''
   Morgan Freeman accomplished the near-impossible: winning a
nomination in a film released early in the year to scant notice.
His role as vicious ``Fast Black'' in ``Street Smart'' was dynamic
enough to remain in Academy voters' minds.
   Born in Memphis and raised in Greenwood, Miss., before moving to
Chicago, Freeman built up an impressive number of stage credits
before appearing in such films as ``Brubaker,'' ``Teachers'' and
``Marie.'' His performance in ``Street Smart'' prompted this
outburst from the New Yorker's Pauline Kael: ``Is Morgan Freeman
the greatest actor in America today?''
   Freeman admits to a rough life while growing up in Chicago's
South Side: ``I stole, I conned, I passed the tests. But I was
scared. I'm not the violent type.'' This contrasts the brutal role
he plays in ``Street Smart.''
   Instead of sliding into delinquency, the young Freeman found
himself attracted to acting, and sold bottles so he would have
money to go to the movies.
   Vincent Gardenia, Cher's excitable father in ``Moonstruck,'' has
been in the New York theater since 1954 and films since 1958. He
also was a member of the ``All in the Family'' cast on television.
   Gardenia was ideal casting as the Italian plumber; his family
emigrated from Naples, and he began acting in New York's Italian
theater. He was delighted with the ``Moonstruck'' script: ``It was
the first about an Italian family in a long time that you don't see
shooting, killings, bombings. It's about love, about family.''
   Denzel Washington was cast in ``Cry Freedom'' after a worldwide
search for an actor to play the vital role of Steven Biko, the
black leader who was beaten to death by South African police while
in their custody.
   Washington admits that his nomination was ``both a letdown and a
great honor.'' The letdown came because Universal Pictures had been
promoting him for best actor, and he had been nominated for a
Golden Globe in that category. He adds that his reaction wasn't the
result of an actor's ego.
   ``It has more to do with my own feelings about Steven Biko,'' he
says. ``I would like to see him in (a starring) light, and I think
most people do. He was not a supporting player.''
   Washington faced an imposing challenge: portraying a
much-admired, even revered figure while making him a believable
human being.
   ``I don't know how to play a saint,'' he says. ``I couldn't get
any advice from anyone on how to play a saint. So that was no
problem.'' Under Richard Attenborough's direction, he created a
portrait of the martyr that was both human and convincing.
   Washington said the effect of ``Cry Freedom'' on the apartheid
issue will be on a personal level.
   ``Most of the comments I've gotten from people were that they
didn't know what goes on in South Africa,'' he said. ``That's where
it will have its most important effect. I don't think it's going to
make a change in the government's attitude or the attitude of the
black people there. It's just a movie, commenting on something from
the outside.''
   Albert Brooks, the astute reporter and failed anchorman of
``Broadcast News,'' is noted for directing himself in films: ``Real
Life,'' ``Modern Romance,'' ``Lost in America.''
   Brooks, a stand-up comedian before making films, says that the
role of Aaron Altman was different from his own life: ``I don't
work in the news business. I don't have a 9 to 5 or even a 9 to 9
job. I don't wear suits. I don't have friends. ... Over a period of
four months I hung out with a dozen reporters. I think what happens
is you sort of compile little things from everybody.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
