<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StungForGifts Bjt   04-08 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stung For Gifts, Bjt,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Always Stung For Presents Throw Bash _ For Themselves</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ladies of the club _ Women Always Stung
for Presents Society _ are throwing a bash today, and as usual the
guests of honor are themselves.
   The dozen or so retired school secretaries plan to treat
themselves to a fancy lunch, toast their single status and present
themselves with an extra special gift.
   That's for the years and years of giving presents to their
married friends, but never getting anything back.
   ``This is really to treat ourselves because no one else really
has,'' explained Betty Kieffer, 63, who's serving as the queen, or
organizer, of today's gathering of the society, otherwise known as
WASPS.
   ``Oh, Lordy, every time you turn around you're giving gifts.
Wedding gifts and baby gifts and shower gifts. You couldn't begin
to count them. You're giving all the time, but you're not getting
anything in return,'' said Alma Eck Mullen, 81, a founding member
of the 38-year-old society.
   Miss Kieffer is giving herself a new white coat. Mrs. Mullen, a
widow who married late in life, is celebrating with a watch on a
necklace.
   Gifts can be whatever the women need or want. Over the years,
presents have included diamond rings, new cars, houses, European
vacations, even a custom-made girdle.
   ``She was quite a heavy girl and she could never get a girdle to
fit her. So she had one made,'' Mrs. Mullen said Thursday.
   Each woman writes a poem, to herself naturally, and gives
herself a card that reads, ``I love me.'' They also sing this peppy
tune:
   ``That's where our money's spent, on all the gals who went. We
bought them everything to keep them supplied. We think the time is
due to get a gift or two. So WASPS let's see what you brought you.''
   The conversation covers just about everything except for
children, grandchildren and, of course, men.
   ``That's why it's so nice. I don't have to listen to stories
about everybody's wonderful grandchildren,'' Miss Kieffer said,
laughing.
   The members, ranging in age from their mid-50s to late 80s, have
been gathering every April since 1950, when Mrs. Mullen and 23
other never-wed secretaries for the Pittsburgh Public Schools
decided enough was enough.
   They formed the society after learning about a similar group in
Des Moines, Iowa. To be eligible, women had to be single and
employed as a secretary for the Pittsburgh Public Schools for at
least 10 years.
   ``If you were married, somebody would have had some plush party
for you. So that was it. We'd be the contributors,'' Mrs. Mullen
said. ``But you could be married after that because once a WASP,
always a WASP.''
   Howard Carroll, a spokesman for the National Education
Association, says the society likely has its roots in the days when
female teachers in some parts of the country were barred from
saying ``I do.''
   ``They just extended themselves through their kids'' in school,
he said.
   The Women Always Stung for Presents Society grew to more than 60
members around 1970, but has since dwindled to 14, seven of them
founding members. Two women are now married. Mrs. Mullen is the
only widow.
   ``A lot of them (members) have died,'' Mrs. Mullen said.
   Secretaries nowadays simply aren't interested.
   ``They don't want to have that brand,'' Jane Viehman, 69, said.
``To say they've been working for 10 years and they aren't married,
I guess it's terrible. It doesn't bother me, but it does some
people.''
   The society meets once a year on April Fools' Day. The date was
pushed back this year since Good Friday fell on April 1.
   The restaurant get-togethers are mandatory and planned months in
advance. Members who can drive pick up those who can't. Just about
everybody comes freshly coiffed and sporting a new outfit.
   ``We enjoy seeing each other because who knows who will be there
next year,'' Miss Kieffer said.
   ``Our girls are all getting older,'' Mrs. Mullen agreed. ``But
we always say if there's one left, that one will go. We'll keep it
up.''
</TEXT>
