<DOCNO> AP880408-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Anti-Yuppies Bjt   04-08 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Anti-Yuppies, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anarchist Group Promises `National Anti-Yuppie Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As if Britain's yuppies didn't have enough to
worry about in the fallout from the stock market crash, they're now
faced with anarchists plotting a ``National Anti-Yuppie Day.''
   Adding to the misery of yuppie job losses, pay cuts and
dwindling stock portfolios is Class War, an anarchists' group,
which announced a 22-city rock concert tour in Britain for August
dubbed ``Rock against the Rich.''
   It said in a statement made available Thursday to The Associated
Press that it hopes the tour will culminate in an anti-yuppie
extravaganza on Sept. 10.
   Just who Class War is has never been clear. ``It's not a club
you join,'' said a sympathizer, who gave his name only as Sean.
   Nor has the size of its membership been divulged.
   Group members sometimes surface in anti-capitalist stunts like a
1984 campaign in which bank windows were smashed, a smoke bomb
exploded near the Bank of England and about 470 people were
arrested.
   But why pick on yuppies? Class War explained: ``All over
Britain, a plague of yuppies are descending on working-class
communities like locusts. The time to resist is now _ let's Rock
Against the Rich.''
   In a telephone interview, Sean said it was ``because people have
been pushed out from areas where they have always lived because of
greed on the part of speculators, because it isn't possible to
afford to buy somewhere to live in London unless you have a hell of
a lot of money.''
   The story of the anti-yuppie campaign was broken, appropriately
enough, in the Independent newspaper, London's newest daily and a
favorite among yuppies. Its good-natured report Thursday on Class
War's manifesto said: ``With this defiant, if ungrammatical,
declaration, a new musical movement has been launched.''
   But the newspaper wrote: ``Rock Against the Rich seems very
unlikely to raise anything like the level of support given by
musicians and audiences to the anti-fascist Rock Against Racism in
the 1970s or pro-Labor (Party) Red Wedge rock tours before the last
general election.''
   The concerts are to be held in cities, like Edinburgh, Scotland,
and Exeter, England, whose run-down inner areas are being
``gentrified'' by wealthy young newcomers, Sean said.
   An exception is Guildford, the heart of the stockbroker belt
south of London, where the concert has been dubbed, ``Rock Against
Stockbrokers.''
   The planned anti-yuppie day's main attraction is an outdoor rock
concert in the Docklands, in London's East End, where gentrifiers
have been clashing with the local residents, the group said.
   Docklands developers say they have rescued the area from
irreversible decline and provided affordable housing for local
residents.
   Joe Strummer, previously guitarist with The Clash, a 1970s rock
group, has agreed to join the tour, as well as other, less
well-known musicians, Class War said.
   The group is targeting yuppies because ``they come off flaunting
wealth when there's none there to start with,'' Sean said.
   London's yuppie class grew visibly during Big Bang, the huge
deregulation of Britain's financial markets in 1986. Expanding
investment firms paid top money to attract brokers and bankers, and
many yuppie-haters reacted with glee to the stock market crash last
October.
   Britain still suffers from class antagonisms and the tug-of-war
between capitalism and socialism continues unabated.
   Some see Class War as just another manifestation of British
eccentricity. Others see a more sinister side in the group's
reported support for ``taxing'' yuppies by mugging and burglarizing
them.
   Class War is ``tapping real feeling in the East End,'' Nick
Cohen, who wrote about the group for the Independent, said in a
telephone interview.
   But ``it's hard to know what their real influence is. Opinions
vary on the left about whether they are publicity-seeking idiots or
whether they are doing anything, even on the far left.''
   ``Their rhetoric is quite nasty,'' Cohen added. ``Nobody else
(political groups) will have anything to do with them.''
</TEXT>
