<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HostageFallout     04-08 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Fallout,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Guns Were Fake, Girl Wasn't Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mentally ill man killed by police was merely
pretending to hold his teen-age girlfriend captive and used toy
guns during a three-hour standoff, authorities said Thursday.
   The guns 19-year-old Israel Ramos held to the girl's head and
brandished at police from the window of his second-floor apartment
were plastic water pistols and the ``hostage situation was a
charade,'' York County District Attorney H. Stanley Rebert said at
a news conference.
   The 15-year-old girl, a York County runaway whose name was not
released, was a willing participant, he said. Officials did not
discuss the motive behind the charade.
   A police marksman shot Ramos once in the abdomen and he died
several hours later at York Hospital.
   Police originally said the marksman fired when Ramos threatened
to kill the girl. But film taken by WGAL-TV in Lancaster showed
Ramos was shot seconds after yelling, ``I'm coming out'' and
placing both hands on a window frame. No gun was in sight.
   Rebert and other officials refused to identify the officer who
fired the fatal shot. They said he was on administrative leave
without pay, pending the outcome of an investigation that is
expected to last up to four weeks.
   The officials refused to say if any charges would be filed
against the teen-ager.
</TEXT>
