<DOCNO> AP880408-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CourtingDelegates Bjt   04-08 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Courting Delegates, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring is in the air and so is courting _
especially among the Democratic presidential hopefuls as they woo
the party's unpledged delegates to the national convention.
   Faced with the possibility that the primary process will not
produce a clear-cut delegate leader, the candidates are focusing on
the 645 ``super delegates'' who could tip the balance in Atlanta
July 18-21.
   Campaign brochures, news clippings and position papers fill the
mailboxes of the super delegates _ 25 governors, 362 Democratic
National Committee members, 253 members of Congress and five elder
statesmen _ who could push a candidate closer to the 2,082 total
needed to nominate.
   Some campaigns rely on phone calls, such as those made to
Patricia Russell, a Democratic national committeewoman from Keene,
N.H., who remains uncommitted.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis phoned twice and his wife,
Kitty, called too. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s staff called as
well. Mrs. Russell says she has heard from all the candidates
except Jesse Jackson.
   Since last fall, the Dukakis campaign has been laying the
foundation with the super delegates through phone calls, mailings
and personal contact, said delegate counter Tad Devine. In recent
weeks, aides have stepped up the pressure.
   ``It's much more focused, an intense effort,'' Devine said.
``When it looks like he's pulling away ... at that time we'll seek
a more formal pledge of support.''
   The Gore campaign has relied on congressional communication on
Capitol Hill as well as phone calls and mailings to the delegates,
said Richard Hutcheson, delegate counter for the senator.
   ``There's great potential among the super delegates,'' said
Hutcheson, who describes the field as ``fertile territory'' for his
candidate. ``The super delegates are most interested in a ticket
that can win.''
   The Jackson forces, however, are just getting started in their
campaign for super delegates.
   ``I looked into what kind of a strategy he had to deal with them
and who he had doing it,'' said John White, former chairman of the
Democratic National Committee who is advising Jackson. ``It turns
out they apparently had very little. There's some mail being passed
back and forth.''
   ``It's something they have to do and they're probably very late
in doing it,'' he said.
   Rep. Mickey Leland of Texas, a member of the congressional Black
Caucus, said last week he will lead the Jackson effort to court the
super delegates.
   ``The front line is the congressional Black Caucus ... to talk
to our colleagues in our states, to lobby people who are super
delegates,'' Leland said.
   Jackson contends that if he leads in pledged delegates after the
last primaries on June 7, he deserves the support of the super
delegates and should get the nomination.
   ``We know that the super votes give rise to super delegates,''
Jackson said last week after meeting with a select group of
Democratic leaders. ``The delegates must respect and respond to the
will of the people.
   ``If we do not believe that, why have a primary? Have a
super-delegate convention and let the super delegates choose
someone of their own,'' he said.
   Willie Brown, California Assembly speaker and Jackson's national
campaign chairman, said the campaign would use primary results to
convince the super delegates.
   ``We will take the popular vote in their state or their district
and say this is a factor you should consider,'' Brown said.
   The constant communication _ by telephone and by mail _ is all
too familiar to some super delegates.
   ``They don't call on a per day basis,'' said Richard Gerber, an
uncommitted super delegate from Norristown, Pa. ``They called
before and after Michigan, before and after Connecticut. They tell
us how well the candidates are doing.''
   Elizabeth Smith of Washington, D.C., said the campaigns phone to
find out ``if there's anything I want to know about the candidate,
if I'm getting the mailings. They're very diplomatic.''
   Dora Olivo, an uncommitted super delegate from Rosenberg, Texas,
has received ``a lot of calls from Dukakis,'' and expects it to get
``hot and heavy'' as the convention nears.
   Other delegates say the courting hasn't even begun in earnest.
   Charles Gifford of Des Moines, Iowa, a former supporter of
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, said he hadn't heard from any
campaign since his candidate dropped out of the race two weeks ago.
   And Bella Abzug, a former congresswoman from New York City, said
she's heard from all the campaigns, but ``I don't think they're
vigorously working on it.''
</TEXT>
