<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ShuttleEscape Bjt   04-08 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Escape, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle to be Equipped With Crew Escape Pole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA says the first space shuttle to fly since
the Challenger accident will be equipped with the equivalent of a
fireman's pole so astronauts can slide to safety if the craft has
to ditch in the ocean.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration chose the pole
escape method Thursday over an alternative that would have used
rockets to propel the crew away from the shuttle Discovery in an
emergency.
   By sliding down the pole, the astronauts would clear the
shuttle's tail before parachuting into the sea, NASA says.
   For all the strength that allows the shuttle to withstand the
buffeting that accompanies a climb or descent through the
atmosphere, the vehicle probably could not survive a crash landing
on the ocean.
   ``The telescoping pole was selected as it has shown to be safer,
simpler to operate, lighter weight and easier to support than the
tractor rocket system,'' said Arnold D. Aldrich, a top shuttle
program official.
   Barbara Selby, a NASA spokeswoman, said the 10{-foot pole
already is being installed in Discovery and will be ready for the
first flight, scheduled for Aug. 4.
   The aluminum and steel pole weighs 241 pounds, 70 pounds lighter
than the rocket system.
   Moreover, top NASA officials have said all along they were
uncomfortable with storing explosive rockets in the crew cabin.
   The Rogers Commission, which investigated the 1986 Challenger
accident, found that no escape method would have saved the seven
astronauts who died in that explosion. But, it said, ``The crew
should have a means of escaping the orbiter in controlled, gliding
flight.''
   The pole is intended for just such a purpose. If the shuttle had
to ditch _ either on an aborted launching or on return from space _
the pole would be extended out the side hatch and the crew would
attach themselves to it with rings on their parachutes and slide
down, one at a time.
   During launch and landing, the unextended pole will be pointed
toward the hatch. It will be stowed while the shuttle is in orbit.
   The Challenger astronauts died during ascent while the solid
rocket boosters were still firing and attached to the shuttle.
Engineers say the new escape system cannot be used while the
shuttle is connected to the rockets.
   ``This decision completes the crew escape system package,'' a
NASA statement said. ``The agency already has replaced the
spacecraft's hatch so it can be jettisoned with explosive bolts and
it is installing a partial pressure suit, oxygen equipment, a
parachute, a life raft and survival equipment for each crew
member.''
   Under the rocket system, the astronauts would have to jettison
the hatch, and, one-by-one, lie on a metal ramp that slanted out
the door. Each one would have to attach a line to a small rocket
housed in an adjacent rack and be pulled out.
   The pole system was tested in February and March, using a fixed
pole that extended through a hatch-like opening in a C-141 cargo
plane. Navy parachutists completed 66 jumps, using cords attached
to their parachute harnesses to slide down the pole and descend to
a safe landing.
   NASA said the side hatch jettison system can also be helpful if
an emergency should require a quick crew exit once the ship is on
the ground. The new hatch contains an escape slide similar to those
on commercial airliners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Teamsters-Truckers     04-08 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Truckers,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Trim Wage Increase To Improve Pension Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamster truck drivers and warehouse workers
are giving up some of the wage increase their union has just
negotiated for them in exchange for more pension and other fringe
benefits.
   The new proposed National Master Freight Agreement unveiled
Thursday differs from the tentative pact signed last week by the
union and Trucking Management Inc., the industry's bargaining arm.
   Duke Zeller, a Teamster spokesman, acknowledged Thursday that
some key provisions in the proposed contract were re-negotiated
this week in response to pockets of opposition to them within the
union.
   ``There were always some i's to be dotted and t's to be
crossed,'' Zeller said. ``Obviously pension matters were of primary
concern and the negotiators responded to the dictates of what the
membership felt was important.''
   Zeller said the union plans to begin mailing out ballots next
week for a rank-and-file ratification vote, with ballot counting
and announcement of the results to occur in mid-May.
   Under the Teamsters' constitution, rejection of a negotiated
contract requires a two-thirds membership vote against it. About
200,000 workers are covered by the contract.
   When signed a week ago, the proposed three-year accord included
an immediate 50-cent hourly wage increase followed by 35-cent
raises in April 1989 and again in 1990.
   The 15-cent difference the first year is being switched to
contributions by employers to the union's pension and health and
welfare funds. The union's pension fund now provides retirees with
a monthly pension check of up to $1,500.
   Instead of a 20-cents-per-hour increase in contributions to the
two funds in each of the three years, trucking companies would now
kick in 35 cents more an hour this year.
   If ratified, the contract would raise the base wage rate for
truck drivers from the current $14.71 to $15.06 hour, retroactive
to April 1. Wages would rise to $15.41 an hour in April 1989 and to
$15.76 in 1990.
   So-called ``casual'' part-time workers now paid about $3 an hour
less than the top scale also will get the same hourly wage and
benefit increases under the renegotiated pact, Zeller said.
   Richard Belous, a labor market analyst for The Conference Board,
a business research house, said the renegotiated contract belies a
myth that, with lower tax rates, workers would opt for more pay
than benefits.
   ``Given the choice between cash and security, workers are
telling their negotiators to go back and get more security.''
Belous said. ``Once they reach a certain pay level, they want more
protection against the vagaries of ill health and old age.''
   The contract also recoups for Teamsters some of the concessions
the union yielded to the industry in 1985.
   A two-tier wage system in which new hires started out at 70
percent of the base scale and rose by 10 percent a year to 100
percent at the end of three years is diminished by half.
   Under the new accord, new hires will start at 85 percent of the
top scale, rising by 5 percentage points every six months until
they reach 100 percent after a year and one-half.
   Many within the union had complained the two-tier scales were
allowing the largest trucking companies who are adding new hires to
their payrolls to undercut freight rates of small companies with
older work forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PrivateMail 530   04-08 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Private Mail, 530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Director, Postmaster General Disagree On Making Service
Private</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's budget director and the
postmaster general disagree over whether the U.S. mail ought to be
turned over to private companies, and postal workers are siding
with their boss.
   Budget director James Miller said in a seminar Thursday that the
Postal Service should not have a monopoly on letter deliveries.
Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank indicated to the same group he
doesn't like the idea of so-called ``privatization.''
   As the two attended meetings sponsored by the conservative think
tank Cato Institute, union leader Moe Biller led 100 picketers
outside in a cold drizzle.
   ``Miller, Miller, he's a jerk; privatization just won't work,''
the group chanted.
   Biller, president of the American Postal Workers Union, called
Miller's proposal ``cockeyed'' and said it would cause chaos with
the mail and increase costs to the public. The APWU is the largest
of four mail unions, representing about 365,000 of the nation's
800,000 postal workers.
   Biller said that accusations that the postal monopoly is causing
increased costs are ``unmitigated lies.'' The CATO Institute, in a
report issued as postal rates went up Sunday, said mail service is
getting slower, more expensive and less reliable because of the
lack of competition.
   Wearing a sign accusing Miller of betraying postal reform,
Biller stood at the doorway of the seminar room for a few minutes
before the budget director arrived. As the doors were closed, he
told seminar organizers, ``You're afraid of a free society.''
   Biller later followed Miller into the hotel and shook his hand,
saying he wanted to debate him on the idea of turning over the
Postal Service to private business.
   Miller said in a speech: ``There is no good reason why it (the
Postal Service) should remain part of the U.S. government, and no
good reason why it should enjoy a monopoly over the delivery of
letter mail.''
   He accused the service of wanting to be a government-protected
monopoly when it comes to letter mail and a federal agency when it
comes to federal subsidies and other benefits.
   Miller denied allegations from the postal unions and others that
his Office of Management and Budget has tried to intrude into
management of the Postal Service, which is an independent
government agency.
   Frank, who took over the Postal Service March 1, suggested
privatization could be a code word for union-busting. He said he is
against eliminating the letter-mail monopoly the service has and
does not believe private companies should be allowed to skim off
profitable segments of the postal service.
   He said, however, he would support a genuine effort to promote
efficiency by sharing work with private mailers and contracting
more non-critical postal services.
   Frank said the Postal Service should be ``the most efficient,
reliable, convenient public service in the country.'' He noted that
private package services deliver only a tiny fraction of the 500
million items a day handled by the Postal Service.
   He said even advocates of privatization realize changes must be
gradual, adding, ``I sense a desire to go slowly, a recognition
that the mail system, like Humpty Dumpty, once broken, couldn't be
put back together again.''
</TEXT>
