<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FDA-AIDSTests     04-08 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FDA-AIDS Tests,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Effectively Bars Home AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has told
prospective developers of home AIDS test kits they must limit
market research to hospitals, clinics and other traditional health
care settings.
   That and other restrictions contained in a March 30 policy
statement effectively bar home test kits by heading off
accumulation of the very kind of data that would be needed to
convince the FDA to approve them.
   Despite the clear signal that the FDA is not disposed to look
kindly on such mass distribution of an AIDS test, the policy letter
said the agency will seek public comment that could lead it to
revise the guidelines.
   FDA spokeswoman Susan Cruzan said Thursday the FDA will publish
its guidelines for considering approval of home AIDS test kits in
the Federal Register, along with its intention to convene public
workshops on the issues surrounding such premarket research.
   The policy letter went to 17 people or companies who had
expressed interest in marketing an AIDS test kit. Those parties,
none identified by the agency, had been told earlier that FDA
permission would have to be granted before they could be sold.
   FDA officials have long expressed skepticism about any home AIDS
test kit winning approval, because the disease is fatal and U.S.
Public Health Service guidelines say any testing should be
accompanied by appropriate counseling.
   The FDA is a part of the Public Health Service.
   An official who insisted on anonymity for fear of being accused
of prejudging applications before they are filed said the existence
of home tests for pregnancy is no argument for the home AIDS tests.
The official said the emotional impact of learning one has a
life-threatening disease is far different.
   The policy letter, signed by Paul D. Parkman, director of the
FDA's Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research, tells companies
not to even bother filing applications for premarket approval
unless:
   _Their kits are labeled and marketed for professional use only
``within a comprehensive health care environment (e.g. hospitals,
medical clinics, doctor's offices, STD clinics, alternative test
sites and mental health clinics.)''
   _Blood is drawn only by a person ``recognized by a state or
local authority to perform such procedures'' _ in other words a
licensed technician.
   _The testing sequence includes a currently licensed screening
test.
   _All results are reported directly to professional health care
providers for reporting and interpretation of results ``as well as
for counseling of the individual.''
</TEXT>
