<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UnpublishedAuction     04-08 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unpublished Auction,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maine Author Takes Bids on Unpublished Novel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It remains to be seen if struggling author Alan
Rosenberg ever will get his books published, but he's already
auctioned off his manuscripts and other memorabilia.
   He raised $965, much less than the $15,000 he spent staging to
stage it Thursday in the penthouse of the New York Hilton, a huge
publicity stunt that surpassed even his own expectations.
   ``I'm thrilled people even thought this was worth something,''
he said. ``We did good.''
   Rosenberg watched as an old Boston Herald baseball cap sold for
$50, a dogeared dictionary for $40 and a manuscript of an
unpublished book he wrote about the second Claus von Bulow trial
fetched for $270.
   The money was of little importance. It was television news
crews, magazine writers, newspaper reporters and other journalists
that he hoped to snare.
   And snared they were as they came to his show, which included
door prizes and an auctioneer who has sold memorabilia of Ernest
Hemingway, Richard Nixon and Babe Ruth.
   Rosenberg failed to find a publisher for his first two books so
he planned the publicity stunt after finishing his latest novel,
``Run Red Riding Hood Run,'' a book that he said mixes murder,
suspense and comedy.
   As was the case with his books on the second Claus von Bulow
trial and his experiences at the Boston Herald, there's no
publisher.
   As part of the hoopla, Rosenberg started the day by marrying
Cathy Lee Counts at City Hall.
   He also attempted to lure several better-known (make that known)
authors such as Stephen King and John Irving. Both said no, but
sent messages, Irving's in the form of a ``rejection post card.
   Armed with the published evidence of his hype, the 34-year-old
Maine author plans to go to a booksellers convention in Anaheim,
Calif., to peddle his product.
   ``This book has never been rejected,'' he said of his latest
work after selling his collection of 30 rejection notices from
publishers for his other books at the auction for $65.
   About 50 people attended the auction, mostly family, friends,
reporters and the 10 models Rosenberg hired to read his work to the
group.
   Several serious bidders also showed up, including Herb
Goldsmith, president of Members Only, the clothing manufacturer.
   ``This is as contemporary as art can get,'' he said, explaining
his interest in the works of a writer whose books have never been
published.
   He bought a first draft of Rosenberg's new book for $45 at the
auction, which, like most items, began with a bid of $2.75.
``Anything that starts at $2.75, I'll bid,'' he said. ``This is
unique.''
   Joyce Burger of Manhattan said she bought a 431-page manuscript
of Rosenberg's new unpublished novel for $270 for a friend who
became interested after reading about the auction in an
advertisement.
   She said her friend was betting on Rosenberg's future and hoped
the manuscript would grow in value.
   ``I think it's the bargain of the century because I am going to
be famous,'' Rosenberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
