<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-08 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Housing Agencies Do Little About Radon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While federal environmental officials say
radon gas causes up to 20,000 cancer deaths a year, federal housing
agencies see little responsibility to respond, the General
Accounting Office says in a new report.
   The report to Congress, made public Thursday, concludes that
agencies in the housing business _ hamstrung in part by a lack of
congressional guidance _ do little or nothing about the threat from
deadly radon.
   The report scrutinizes the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, the Veterans Administration, the Farmers Home Mortgage
Administration and the National Park Service.
   Radon is a naturally occurring, odorless and colorless gas. The
Environmental Protection Agency says radon may cause from 5,000 to
20,000 lung-cancer deaths annually.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Report Says Public Housing Needs Repair, Renovation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government study of the nation's public
housing found that repair and renovation of existing units among
the 1.3 million dwellings nationwide would cost between $7.5
billion and $9.2 billion.
   The report, released today by the Department of Housing and
Urban Development, was based on inspection of 2,196 units and 3,120
buildings at public housing projects across the country at the end
of 1985. It took more than two years and $5 million to compile and
review the final report which was ordered by Congress, HUD
officials said.
   So far, said HUD deputy assistant secretary C. Duncan MacRae,
$3.9 billion has been spent.
   ``HUD is committed to restoring the public housing stock to
decent, safe and sanitary conditions in every instance where that
housing is viable,'' said HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Child Abuse Figure for Missouri Is Corrected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Committee for Prevention of Child
Abuse says its report this week on the deaths of children resulting
from child abuse gave the wrong number of such deaths for Missouri.
   The report said there were seven child abuse fatalities in
Missouri in 1986 and 20 in 1987, but actually there were 19 in each
of those years, according to Deborah Daro, director of research for
the NCPCA. She said Thursday the committee's report was based on an
erroneous figure from the Missouri Division of Family Services.
</TEXT>
