<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   04-08 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Temporarily Suspends Mediation Effort; New Split in
Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN1, NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Marcos McGrath called off
his attempt to mediate between Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and the
opposition, which has refused to negotiate unless the general first
agrees to leave the country.
   Also Thursday, there was a split in the main anti-Noriega
coalition. And police using tear gas and rubber hoses dispersed
hundreds of anti-government demonstrators in the western city of
David.
   A Roman Catholic church communique said mediation efforts were
suspended because the opposition had insisted Noriega _ the
nation's de facto ruler _ agree to depart and the general had
failed to agree in writing to mediation.
   ``The church in no way surrenders the difficult task of
mediation. It still considers it urgent and every day more so,''
said the communique, which asked all parties to remove obstacles so
that talks might begin.
   The opposition National Civic Crusade, which has led the
Panamanian fight to oust Noriega, said in a statement issued after
the church announcement that it stood by its negotiating conditions.
   A sign from Noriega that he was willing to step down remained an
``indispensable and essential condition'' for opening talks, it
said.
   In a communique that was not signed by Noriega, the government
had agreed to church mediation without preconditions.
   Earlier Thursday, two leaders of the opposition Popular Action
Party announced they were breaking with the 10-month-old Civic
Crusade to form the Popular Civic Movement. It was the first major
split in the opposition.
   Roberto Arosemena and Mauro Zuniga told a news conference the
new group had the support of the Authentic Panamanian Party, the
country's largest opposition party. Zuniga said the splinter group
also wants Noriega out, but thinks it is a job for Panamanians, not
Americans.
   The Civic Crusade's campaign to oust Noriega, chief of Panama's
15,000-strong Defense Forces, has been backed by Washington.
   The new opposition group opposes church mediation and does not
recognize Eric Arturo Delvalle, deposed by pro-Noriega lawmakers on
Feb. 26, as Panama's president. Government prosecutor Alvaro
Visuetti disclosed Wednesday that an arrest warrant had been issued
for Delvalle, who is in hiding in Panama.
   Delvalle, in a videotape released to Cable News Network
Thursday, said he would continue to fight to oust Noriega, who he
tried to fire the day before he himself was removed.
   ``Fellow countrymen, we cannot allow a gang of inhuman drug
traffickers to be the owners of our public institutions and of the
country itself,'' he said.
   The tape was reported made Thursday.
   In February, Noriega was indicted in Florida on federal drug
trafficking charges. The United States has frozen Panamanian
deposits in American banks, and Panama's banks closed during the
first week of March.
   Civilian sources contacted by telephone in David said Civic
Crusade members were beaten and arrested when police broke up a
protest march Thursday evening.
   Carlos Secchi, a Crusade member, said police used tear gas and
rubber hoses to break up the march by more than 500 demonstrators.
He said about 15 marchers were arrested. There were no immediate
reports of injuries.
   With the arrival this week of 1,300 extra U.S. troops this week,
there now are about 11,800 American soldiers in Panama to protect
the Panama Canal and guard American installations.
   Another 800 U.S. Marines were to arrive today for jungle
training that had been scheduled months ago. The Marines are slated
to stay for three weeks.
   Banking officials put an end Thursday to government speculation
the country's banks might open today or next week. Sources speaking
on condition of anonymity said they feared the government would
attempt to bleed deposits for its own use if the banks were to open.
   Lacking hard cash, the government has failed to meet its payroll
for a month. People paid by check cannot cash them. Panamanians
with dollars are using them sparingly, and many now depend on
charity for food.
</TEXT>
