<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz-Mideast     04-08 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Mideast,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Ends Middle East Tour, But Plans Another Peace Trip To
Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Shultz
^By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz wound
up a five-day quest for Middle East peace talks today,
acknowledging progress could be measured only in inches.
   But Shultz said he expects to return to the region _ he did not
say when _ to ``to struggle against the odds.''
   He said his goal remains a comprehensive settlement between
Israel and its Arab neighbors and self-rule but not statehood for
the Palestinians.
   ``I think the stakes are very high and the opportunities very
great, even if the probabilities are against you,'' the secretary
told a news conference.
   He praised King Hussein of Jordan for ``having engaged seriously
with us for peace in the region.'' Earlier in the week, he called
the king ``a partner for peace.''
   Shultz did not offer an assessment of Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir of Israel, whose position toward a Middle East peace
conference was an obstacle Shultz could not overcome.
   The secretary had hoped to convene a peace conference by
mid-April to launch talks between Israel and a mixed delegation of
Jordanians and Palestinians.
   ``I don't think we are going to make it and that's obvious,''
Shultz said.
   But he bristled when one of the reporters at a news conference
suggested his mission was doomed to failure.
   ``You have to be willing to do it,'' Shultz said. ``What am I
saving myself for anyway? I have a few more months to go here and I
want to try to leave something constructive for the region and for
my successors, and so I'm going to put my back into it. Why not?''
   The Reagan administration has a little more than nine months
left. The current trip is the third by Shultz to the Middle East
since October to try to break a 40-year impasse between Israel and
its Arab neighbors.
   Since early December, Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip have been rioting against their Israeli occupiers. At least
141 Arabs and an Israeli soldier have been killed in the wave of
violence.
   Shamir objects to the U.S. proposal for a peace conference
because he finds in it opportunities for the Soviet Union to side
with the Arabs, as it usually does, and try to impose an
unfavorable settlement on Israel. Shultz gave assurances the United
States would stand by Israel and not let that happen, but Shamir
held to his position.
   Shultz said he expected to return ``at some point in the
future'' because it takes a special U.S. effort to bring the two
sides together.
   ``You measure headway in inches, not miles,'' he said.
   The secretary said he was leaving special U.S. envoy Wat
Cluverius in the region to continue talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-InternationalBanks 1stLd-Writethru a0432 04-08 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-International Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 11 a.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Banks Criticize Lender Governments On Third World Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 9, 11, 14 to CORRECT spelling of Schulmann.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the international banking
community said today that creditor governments, not banks, have
done too little to help Third World countries with their debts.
   The Third World governments want either grants, more new loans
or relief from the burden of paying many billions on old ones every
year, said Horst Schulmann, a West German who heads the
Washington-based Institute of International Finance.
   ``Creditor governments have not done enough in bilateral
relations to provide more official financing, to open their
economies, or to improve the regulatory and tax regimes for private
lenders and investors,'' said Schulmann.
   Schulmann's comments were in a letter to leaders of the
International Monetary Fund and the Development Committee, a joint
group of the fund and its sister organization, the World Bank.
   The fund and bank are owned by 151 countries. Many of those
governments' top economic officials, including Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III, are expected to attend the two institutions'
joint semiannual meetings here next week.
   Baker and other government leaders have criticized commercial
banks for their slowdown of lending in recent years and have
recently been encouraging a ``menu'' of possible actions by the
banks. Many of these actions would require the banks to get rid of
loans at less than their face value.
   Barber Conable, president of the World Bank, has quietly
suggested that banks might also waive some of the billions of
dollars of interest they collect every year.
   ``We have repeatedly noted the dramatic decline in commercial
bank lending to developing countries and stressed the necessity for
signficantly increased flows from the private banks as an essential
ingredient of the debt strategy,'' he said in a report to be
delivered to the Development Committee April 15.
   Schulmann said many debtor governments have refused to seek the
fund's help because it insists on such ``adjustment'' conditions as
cutting government subsidies and devaluing currencies that lower
their people's living standards.
   Fund officials argue that Third World countries will be worse
off if their govnernments do not ask its help.
   Schulmann said the World Bank had been only partly successful in
getting debtor countries to make similar changes in their policies
and that its lending has grown less than expected.
   ``There is a need for the World Bank to be more innovative in
its approach to the debt problem,'' he said.
   He suggested that it should do more in the way of ``credit
enhancements'' _ the kind of financing that lessens risk for banks.
   Schulmann came out for an issue of ``special drawing rights,''
the fund's own kind of money, to member governments. This measure
has long been urged by Third World governments but opposed by the
United States on grounds that it would encourage inflation.
   Third-World debt is expected to reach $1.245 trillion at the end
of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
