<HEAD>Colorado Delegate Vote Count Reaches 95 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Democratic Party is continuing to tally
results from Colorado's Monday night caucuses, with the share of
uncommitted delegates selected to county conventions on the
increase.
   With 95 percent of the state's 2,784 precincts reporting as of
Thursday, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, declared the winner
on Tuesday, was ahead of Jesse Jackson 43.1 percent to 35.1
percent, the state party figures showed. Uncommitted delegates
comprised 18.7 percent of the total number, a figure that has grown
steadily as reports from rural precincts trickle in.
   According to the Democrats, Dukakis has garnered the support of
5,189 delegates to Jackson's 4,228.5.
   A total of 2,255.5 county convention delegates are uncommitted;
313.5, or 2.6 percent are committed to Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore;
34.5, or 0.3 percent, are backers of Illinois Sen. Paul Simon; and
13.5, or 0.1 percent, are committed to other candidates, the state
Democratic Party figures showed.
   Vice President George Bush received 76 percent of the votes cast
in straw polls taken at Republican precinct caucuses. The straw
polls were not binding.
</TEXT>
