<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Scuffle     04-08 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Scuffle,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fight Erupts in Legislative Assembly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers punched and pushed each other
today in a wild melee in Parliament during a debate over whether to
return the government's budget proposal to the Cabinet for more
work.
   The fighting in the legislature, or Yuan, began when Chu
Kao-cheng of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party jumped on
the podium and grabbed the microphone from the Yuan's vice
president to stop him from calling for a vote on the budget.
   Jaw Shau-kong of the ruling Nationalist Party then grabbed Chu
by the hand and pulled him from the podium. The two rolled down a
stairway leading from the podium to the main floor as they scuffled.
   Chu later told reporters that about 10 Nationalist Party
legislators kicked and punched him after he fell to the floor.
Chu's face was bruised and his glasses were broken.
   After the three-minute melee, the vice president called for a
vote and the lawmakers overwhelming moved to debate the budget
proposal at a later session.
   Chu said earlier in the session that the Cabinet, which
submitted the proposal last month, should propose a new budget for
the fiscal year beginning July 1 by drastically cutting defense and
other expenditures.
   About a third of the proposed budget of 568 billion Taiwan
dollars ($19.8 billion) would go to defense, the government says.
But Chu and several other opposition legislators claim money
earmarked for scientific, education and other purposes also would
be used for defense.
</TEXT>
