<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0849,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing figures. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices eased slightly but stayed above their
record level in Tokyo Friday, while the U.S. dollar also fell.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 258.05-point winner Thursday, shed a modest
20.33 points, or 0.07 percent, closing the week at 26,748.89.
   The Nikkei average had closed Thursday at 26,769.22, topping its
previous record close of 26,646.43, which it reached on Oct. 14,
just before the world-wide stock market crash.
   The dollar finished the week at 125.18 yen, down 0.52 yen from
Thursday's finish of 125.70. It opened the day at 125.52 yen and
ranged between 125.05 and 125.78 yen.
   Currency trading was quiet and in a narrow range ahead of next
week's meeting in Washington of monetary authorities from seven
major industrialized nations, said Taeko Koyabashi of the Bank of
Tokyo.
   She added that speculation over U.S. trade figures due to be
released Thursday in Washington had yet to influence the Tokyo
market.
</TEXT>
