<DOCNO> AP880408-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Elections     04-08 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Elections,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Elections Under Way, Khomeini Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranians voted for a new parliament today,
hours after Iraqi missiles crashed into several cities, in an
election that will help determine the course of the Islamic
revolution.
   The nation's 87-year-old revolutionary patriarch, Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, voted at an open-air election station near his
home in the northern Tehran suburb of Jamaran.
   State-run television showed the black-turbaned leader dropping
his ballot into the box, followed by his son Ahmad. The elections
are the third to the 270-member Majlis, or parliament, since the
1979 revolution toppled the late Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi.
   The vote is seen as a test of strength between fundamentalists
who support an Islamic-style capitalism and radicals who favor a
socialist-style economy. The future course of the Islamic
revolution is uncertain, and Khomeini is reported in ill health.
   Iranian leaders had expressed fear the Iraqis would blitz Tehran
and other major cities to disrupt the polling, but nevertheless
urged the country's more than 20 million voters to cast ballots in
defiance.
   A loud explosion rocked the area near a Tehran railroad station
just hours before Iran's 30,000 polling stations opened. Officials
had no immediate details of the blast.
   But Tehran radio, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp.,
reported that Iraqi missiles crashed into the capital and the
central city of Isfahan. It also said Iraqi warplanes raided the
western cities of Bakhtaran and Hamadan, killing an unspecified
number of civilians.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus,
did not give any turnout figures but reported the Iranian people's
``massive presence'' at the polling stations.
   Khomeini declared last week: ``The people will attend the
election with God's help, even if they are under missile attack. I
will vote under any circumstances.''
   He warned: ``The people must beware and choose candidates among
... those loyal to Islam. They must choose their deputies from
among those who have suffered from poverty and are real Moslems,
not those who obey America's Islam.''
   Tehran was decked out in election posters, including
bedsheet-size cloth banners bearing the names of the candidates.
   The 7{-year-old war with Iraq, the country's most pressing
problem, has not figured in the campaigning. Khomeini has decreed
that the war will not end until his adversary, Iraq's President
Saddam Hussein, has been toppled.
   About 1,400 candidates ran for the four-year terms as
parliamentary deputies. They were approved by provincial and city
governors controlled by Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi.
   That's about 400 more than campaigned in the last election in
1984. This year, for the first time, about 30 women ran.
   The results may not be known for 10 days, and the new parliament
may not sit until June while a new cabinet is screened and nominees
scrutinized by the deputies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-People-Skinner     04-08 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Skinner,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychologist Recovers From Fall in Kitchen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Psychologist, author and teacher B.F.
Skinner, who suffered a fall in his kitchen just before Christmas,
said he is doing fine following an operation for a head injury
suffered in the accident.
   ``It's not a news story at all,'' Skinner, 84, who was injured
Dec. 20, said Thursday. ``I just slipped and fell and had a slight
concussion.''
   Skinner, a pioneer in behavioral psychology at Harvard
University, said he underwent an operation four weeks ago to
relieve pressure from the head injury and was released from the
hospital two weeks later.
   ``I'm in fine shape and I'm back home,'' said the author of
``Behavior of Organisms'' in 1938 and the utopian novel ``Walden
Two'' in 1948.
   Skinner, who retired in 1974, said he plans to close his office
at the university in September. Skinner came to Harvard as a
graduate student in 1928, and has taught at the University of
Minnesota and Indiana University.
</TEXT>
