<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-08 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Winds Abate in West but Snow Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong winds that wracked much of the West, blowing over five
semitrailer trucks in Utah and damaging roofs in Nevada, began to
ease today while other western areas dug out from snow.
   A strong low pressure system over Wyoming combined with a strong
high pressure system off the central Pacific coast to produce the
intense winds Thursday night across parts of the western United
States.
   The stiff winds, gusting up to 63 mph, knocked over the five
semitrailer trucks and blew out windows in four other vehicles near
Wendover, Utah.
   In Nevada, winds were clocked at 60 mph in Elko County and there
were reports of roof damage to homes in the Wells and Spring Creek
areas. A hanger door at the Battle Mountain airport was damaged by
a gust clocked at 82 mph.
   High wind warnings over northwest Utah and much of eastern
Nevada were canceled, but wind advisories remained in effect today
over southern Nevada and northern deserts of southern California
where winds of 25 to 40 were expected.
   Also in the West, snow was scattered over the northern Rockies.
Snow advisories were in effect for portions of central and southern
Montana and for the northern mountains of Wyoming. Some roads in
Yellowstone Park, Wyo., were closed because of the heavy snow.
   In the East, rain continued to fall across much of the upper
Ohio Valley and the middle Atlantic coast states. Rain also was
scattered over North Carolina. Cloudy skies and scattered light
drizzle extended across New England.
   Today's forecast called for rain from New England across eastern
and central New York, the middle Atlantic coast states and North
Carolina; rain and mountain snow from southern Montana through
Utah; showers scattered over eastern Wyoming, the western Dakotas
and across southwest Texas; gusty winds over California and
southern Nevada.
   High temperatures were expected in the 60s or 70s over much of
the nation; in the 40s and 50s from the northern half of the
Pacific coast through Utah, Wyoming and Montana and from the Great
Lakes across the upper Ohio Valley and the northern and middle
Atlantic coast states; in the 80s and low 90s over the desert
southwest; in the 80s across the southern and central Plains,
southern Iowa, Missouri, the lower Mississippi Valley and south
Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 21
degrees at Burns, Ore., to 78 degrees at Glendale, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 52 fair; Boston 41 cloudy; Buffalo 38 drizzle;
Charleston, S.C. 49 fair; Cincinnati 44 windy; Cleveland 39 cloudy;
Detroit 38 fair; Miami 62 fair; New York 45 cloudy; Philadelphia 46
cloudy; Pittsburgh 43 rain; Portland, Maine, 42 drizzle; Washington
47 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 60 cloudy; Chicago 44 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
58 fair; Denver 54 partly cloudy; Des Moines 56 fair; Indianapolis
40 fair; Kansas City 69 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 58 fair;
Nashville 48 fair; New Orleans 64 fair; St. Louis 54 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 55 fair; Anchorage 26 fair; Las Vegas 75
windy; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 77 fair; Salt Lake City 45
windy; San Diego 61 foggy; San Francisco 49 fair; Seattle 39 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 cloudy; Toronto 37 windy.
</TEXT>
