<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZooAtlanta 1stLd-Writethru a0493 04-08 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zoo Atlanta, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famous Gorilla `Willie B.' Will Soon Move Outside</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `For Willie ...' to insert dropped word
`will'; Picks up 6th graf, `And zoo ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie B., one of America's most famous gorillas,
has a new human roommate who's trying to coax the pudgy primate
into taking his first step outside in 25 years.
   Later this month, his keepers at Zoo Atlanta plan to introduce
Willie and his fellow apes to a new outdoor habitat, which replaces
the tile walls and steel bars of their old quarters.
   ``Gorillas tend to be very reticent, and after 25 years in the
same place, he's just gotten used to his old home,'' zoo Director
Terry Maple said. ``This change, although it's a very positive
change, is going to be viewed with some suspicion. We're going to
have to induce him to enjoy his new habitat.
   ``Once he gets over this period, we think he's going to really
enjoy it.''
   For Willie, who arrived in Atlanta 25 years ago at age 3, it
might be the first time in his memory that he will have grass
beneath his feet and the open sky above his head.
   And zoo officials have other surprises for Willie. They hope
that within a year they can introduce him to another gorilla,
probably a female.
   ``We're going to have to do it very carefully, so they don't
fight too much,'' Maple said Thursday. Eventually, he said, it's
hoped Willie will breed.
   On Wednesday, Zoo Atlanta officials gave Willie his first
complete physical, then showed him the new indoor quarters he will
use for sleep and shelter. They hope he'll get used to that within
two weeks, and then, they will open the door.
   To coax him outside, keepers will place Willie's food near the
exit of his night quarters. He already can see that something is
going on; zoo staffers are keeping a round-the-clock watch in the
night quarters, including his keeper of 14 years, Charles Horton,
who is sleeping in the next chamber.
   ``He's literally Willie's best friend,'' Maple said. ``Charles
is a very important part of our strategy of making him
comfortable.''
   In Wednesday's physical, Willie B. _ named for long-time former
Atlanta Mayor William B. Hartsfield _ weighed in at nearly 460
pounds, with a 40-inch neck and a 64-inch chest.
   That's about 60 pounds overweight, but for a gorilla who's lived
in a cage for 25 years, it's not too bad, Maple said.
   ``The preliminary results are that he's in very good health,''
Maple said. ``We're surprised at his muscle tone and the quality of
his condition.''
   Willie's first steps outdoors will be important for him, and
equally important for Zoo Atlanta, Maple said.
   The U.S. Humane Society named the 99-year-old zoo one of the
nation's worst just four years ago, before Maple, a specialist in
primate psychology, was hired and launched a plan to convert the
old facility into a modern outdoor animal habitat.
   ``This is the dawning of a new era at Zoo Atlanta; I have no
doubt about that,'' he said. ``You can call it one small step for a
gorilla, one giant step for gorilla kind _ and certainly for the
zoo.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
