<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RapeOrdeal     04-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Ordeal,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Who Waited for Key to Apartment at Scene of Rape Is
Dismissed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city has fired a police officer
who waited outside an apartment building for a key for nearly 30
minutes while officials say a 12-year-old girl was being raped
inside.
   James Horka, 39, was dismissed Thursday night after a divided
city commission found him guilty of violating five departmental
rules. Horka, an officer for 14 years, said he would appeal his
dismissal.
   ``If I could have changed it in any way, if I would have known
what was going on, believe me, it would not have happened that
way,'' Horka said. ``I still think I did the right thing. No one
got killed.''
   Horka was accused of breaking 10 department rules. The Police
and Fire Commission dismissed the most serious allegation, failing
to request assistance at the scene.
   City attorney Howard Rosenfeld said he was shocked by dismissal
of that count but pleased that Horka had been dismissed.
   ``Officers who have a right to carry a gun and a badge have a
tremendous obligation to the public,'' Rosenfeld said. ``They must
meet that obligation if they wish to remain police officers. In our
opinion, Officer Horka did not meet those obligations.''
   Horka was found in violation of conduct unbecoming an officer,
unsatisfactory performance in the line of duty, improper filing of
a report, abuse of command at the scene, and violation of rules.
The last means that since Horka was found in violation of any
department rule, he was found in violation of that regulation as
well.
   The disciplinary hearings began shortly after Horka and two
other officers answered a report of a home invasion on Dec. 21.
   Horka maintained he did not break into the apartment upon
arriving because he feared the assailant might harm the girl and
her 10-year-old brother inside.
   They waited outside almost 30 minutes with the girl's frantic
mother for the landlord to bring a key, rather than breaking in to
rescue the girl.
   Four officers later entered the apartment through a back door,
which had been unlocked, and arrested Benjamin Valentine, 19, of
Chicago. Valentine was charged with rape, burglary, home invasion
and aggravated kidnapping; he is awaiting trial.
   The two officers who accompanied Horka also are scheduled for
disciplinary hearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
