<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Lebanon     04-08 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Lebanon,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Israeli Troops Wounded By Mine in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Israeli troops were wounded today when the
army jeep they were in hit a roadside mine in southern Lebanon, an
army spokesman said.
   The spokesman said the troops were patrolling near the village
of Merkaba in the center of Israel's self-declared ``security
zone'' when they drove by the mine.
   At the same time, attackers fired at the troops from a distance,
the spokesman said. The troops fired back and gave chase to the
attackers, who managed to flee the security zone.
   Two soldiers suffered light wounds and two suffered moderate
wounds, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity in line with
regulations. The four were evacuated to a hospital.
   Israel established its security zone, a six-to-10-mile wide
strip of land north of the Israeli-Lebanese border, when it
withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon in 1985 following a
three-year occupation.
   The zone is patrolled by Israeli troops and Israeli-allied
Lebanese militiamen.
</TEXT>
