<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fugitive     04-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fugitive,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Reunited With Mother After Two Years in Woods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SNELLVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three children who spent two years in a
tent in the Maine wilderness after allegedly being kidnapped by
their father are back in Georgia with their mother.
   They were reunited Thursday with Amelia Doellefeld in a Bangor,
Maine, courthouse. By evening, they were home in this town about 20
miles northeast of Atlanta.
   ``I just remember my legs were shaking _ I was shaking all
over,'' Mrs. Doellefeld said, referring to the tearful reunion.
   FBI agents arrested the father, 52-year-old Tex Donald
Doellefeld, as a fugitive from justice in the tiny central Maine
town of Greenville late Wednesday. He was released from the
Penobscot County Jail after posting $20,000 bond, a jail spokesman
said.
   Gwinnett County authorities began extradition proceedings after
Gwinnett District Attorney Tom Lawler said he opposed Doellefeld's
release.
   The children _ Jason, 13; Beth, 11; and Max, 9 _ were dirty but
in good condition.
   ``I was talking to Beth and she said it was like being on
vacation,'' said Lyn Mealor, the children's aunt.
   ``I thought many times they were dead and just not knowing was
the worst,'' Mrs. Doellefeld said. ``Are they hurt? Are they safe?
Are their needs being met? At one point, it was so black.
   ``One night I said to myself, I've got to do something or else I
am going to die,'' she said.
   Officials in Maine said Doellefeld was discovered after school
officials recognized photographs of the children printed on an FBI
flier. They said Doellefeld was teaching his children through a
state-approved home tutoring program and was visited by school
officials once a month.
   Paul Fourier, a spokesman for Maine's Inland Fisheries and
Wildlife Department, said Doellefeld had been living with the
children for about two years in a heavily wooded area accessible
this time of year only by snowmobile or seaplanes that could land
on a nearby lake.
   Doellefeld, a homebuilder, lived in an elaborate, well-insulated
tent set up on a wooden platform, Fourier said.
   After Doellefeld allegedly kidnapped the children from their
home in August 1986, a Gwinnett County grand jury indicted him on
three counts of interference with child custody, a felony. A
Gwinnett judge issued a warrant charging him with being a fugitive
from justice in March 1987.
</TEXT>
