<DOCNO> AP880408-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mozambique-Bomb     04-08 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mozambique-Bomb,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mozambique Blames South Africa For Car Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government-controlled media blamed
South Africa today for a car bombing that seriously injured a white
member of the African National Congress.
   South Africa denied responsibility.
   Albie Sachs, a South African lawyer, remained in a Maputo
hospital after the Thursday morning explosion that occurred as he
entered his car outside his apartment in downtown Maputo.
   Sachs was jailed by South African authorities for more than
three months without charge in 1963. He also defended members of
the congress.
   The congress, banned in 1960, is the major guerrilla group
fighting South Africa's white-led government.
   He has lived in Mozambique for 10 years and works at the
country's Ministry of Justice.
   ``The long and criminal arm of the Pretoria regime has again
reached into Maputo to carrry out another savage and odious
crime,'' said Noticias, a Maputo daily.
   ``Sachs committed what is, in the eyes of Pretoria, the greatest
of all crimes: he frontally opposed apartheid, he openly challenged
the racist regime,'' the front-page editorial added.
   Reports on Mozambican radio and television also blamed South
Africa, the national news agency AIM reported.
   South Africa's government-run television quoted Foreign Minister
Roelof Botha as saying that South Africa ``could not be held
responsible for the conflict in Mozambique and certainly not for
violence which emanated from faction fighting in the ANC.''
   None of the Mozambican reports cited any evidence linking South
Africa to the blast, but they noted a recent series of attacks
carried out against ANC members.
   At least six congress members have been killed in countries
outside South Africa this year. South Africa has denied
responsibility for the deaths, although it repeatedly warns it will
cross its borders in pursuit of members.
   Tom Lodge, a political scientist at Johannesburg's University of
the Witwatersrand and an expert on the congress, said Sachs was a
member, but that he was not actively working for the group in
Mozambique and was not an officer in the organization, which is
composed mainly of blacks.
   The U.S. Embassy in Maputo condemned the attack and said, ``We
note that the incident takes place after several recent attacks
against purported members of the ANC.''
   South Africa and Mozambique signed a mutual non-aggression pact
in 1984, but both sidely regularly accuse the other of violations.
   Sachs, born in 1935, was the son of a prominent trade unionist.
Sachs was one of the few whites who participated in the African
National Congress' defiance campaign that led to the organization's
banning in 1960. The campaign urged people to ignore apartheid
laws, resulting in thousands of arrests.
   After being released from detention in 1963, Sachs wrote a book
about his experiences, ``The Prison Diary of Albie Sachs,'' which
was turned into a stage play in Britain.
   He worked in Britain before going to Mozambique. As an employee
of the Justice Ministry, he had just begun drafting a new family
law for Mozambique, AIM said.
   The explosion shattered windows in the nearby Portuguese Embassy
and hurled pieces of the car as much as 50 yards away, AIM reported.
   By law and custom in South Africa, apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
