<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0459 04-08 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Gear Up For Biggest Assault On Gangs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf, ``The anticipated ...,'' to
ADD that governor willing to send Highway Patrol, National Guard to
combat gang violence; picks up 7th graf, ``Police Chief ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police patrolling gang-infested neighborhoods
awash in drugs, bullets and blood are preparing to saturate the
streets of the nation's second-largest city in a declared war on
violence.
   ``We're putting together a task force to suppress gang activity
in the city wherever it's at,'' officer Bill Frio, a department
spokesman, said Thursday. ``We are not going to broadcast how and
when we're going to do it.''
   ``We're out there to let these gang-bangers know that we're
here, we're not going to go away, and this city belongs to the good
people,'' said Detective Tony Celli, using the street slang for
gang member.
   In recent weeks police have arrested hundreds of gang members,
most plying a burgeoning drug trade and enforcing the perimeters of
their ``turf'' with drive-by shootings.
   Gangs were blamed for 387 killings in Los Angeles County in
1987, and as many as 85 so far this year. Violence has continued
despite recent enforcement sweeps, with five people wounded
Wednesday in three drive-by shootings, a common style of attack in
gang wars.
   The anticipated roundup, involving as many to 1,000 police
officers, would be the biggest in a series of mass patrols in
gang-ridden areas south of downtown.
   Gov. George Deukmejian said Thursday that he would send the
California Highway Patrol and possibly even the National Guard to
help local authorities control gang violence if asked to do so by
local officials.
   County Supervisor Kenneth Hahn wrote Deukmejian asking that the
Guard be sent to ride with police officers as a show of force.
   Police Chief Daryl Gates, who has compared the violence to
Lebanon, has won the unprecedented support of politicians fed up
with gang activity.
   Earlier this week, the city finance committee vote 3-0 to
approve a police request for $2.5 million to cover overtime for the
gang sweeps. Approval by the full City Council appears certain on
Tuesday.
   The council also has approved a request for $16 million to hire
400 police officers, largely because of complaints from residents
of poor neighborhoods that they weren't getting enough police
protection.
   And a private group, Mothers Against Gangs in Communities, has
been formed to fight gangs. It plans to push for anti-gang
legislation, to help pay for the funerals of innocent victims of
gang wars and to keep the issue before the public in the style of
Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
   Police provided few details on plans for a sweep that could be
launched this weekend, refusing to elaborate on Gates' promise to
flood the low-income and working-class neighborhoods south of
downtown with blue uniforms.
   Incensed by the Good Friday gang shooting that killed one person
and injured 12 _ none believed to be gang members _ Gates said he'd
deploy 1,000 officers drawn from across the city and working on
overtime.
   In previous sweeps, officers have cruised the streets,
concentrating on street-corner drug markets and stopping people
wearing gang colors. On Wednesday and Thursday, police arrested 210
people for misdemeanors, felonies and outstanding warrants, and 128
of those arrested were alleged gang members.
   Gangs, including the violent Crips and the Bloods which have
spread their activities to cities nationwide, have long been active
in the inner city, and police statistics show no dramatic increase
in the level of violence.
   But authorities say traditional turf battles are giving way to
drug-dealing wars here and throughout the West as Los Angeles gangs
try to control distribution of ``crack,'' the smokeable form of
cocaine.
   Warring gangs, said Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, are creating
``homicide that's worse than Beirut.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
