<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0820EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     04-08 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Agree to Resume Peace Talks on April 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-supported rebels have agreed to
resume high-level talks with Nicaragua's government to end a nearly
7-year-old civil war, but said several conditions must be fulfilled
first.
   The directorate of the Nicaraguan Resistance said Thursday in a
letter that it had agreed to come to Managua April 15 for the
talks, the first since leaders of the two sides agreed to a
cease-fire plan on March 23.
   The second meeting had been scheduled for April 6, but the
Contras said they were postponing it because the Sandinistas had
failed to fully comply with provisions of the cease-fire agreement
signed in the southern border town of Sapoa.
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega, head of the government
delegation and the brother of President Daniel Ortega, had offered
to hold the negotiations either April 9 or April 15.
   Spokesmen for the rebels, known as Contras, charged the
government withheld newsprint from the opposition newspaper La
Prensa, violating the accord's provision for full press freedom in
Nicaragua.
   The government also failed to include all the prisoners the
Contras had asked for when it released 100 political prisoners on
April 1, as called for under the agreement, the Contras said.
   In Thursday's letter to Humberto Ortega, rebel leaders accepted
as an ``involuntary error'' the failure to release all of the
requested political prisoners. It said the government lacked enough
time to arrange for all of the requested names to be released.
   Sandinista and Contra military delegations were to continue
talks today on technical details of providing humanitarian aid to
the rebels and controlling zones where the insurgents are to gather
during a 60-day cease-fire that began on April 1.
   On Thursday, the delegations finished defining exact locations
of the seven rebel zones and began considering a 34-point rebel
plan governing conduct in those zones, said Maj. Gen. Jaoquin
Cuadra, head of the Sandinista military delegation.
   ``We already have discharged an important part of the agenda,
which was the point on localization'' of the zones, Cuadra said
after Thursday's session in Sapoa.
   Cuadra said the government had not formally responded to the
34-point plan presented by the Contras outlining rebel conduct
inside the zones. But he said the plan ``has several positive
points, that perfectly can be considered by the government.''
   The March 23 accord does not specify if and under what
conditions the Contras are to lay down their arms. Contra leaders
have vowed not to.
   Roberto Urroz, a member of the rebel military delegation, called
for complete Contra autonomy in the zones.
   ``What we want is that in the zones we have real control,''
Urroz said, adding the rebels were seeking ``security, integrity
and communications without interference'' from the government.
   Still unresolved were pledges of security for the Contras, how
they would receive food and other supplies, who would control the
areas and how compliance would be verified.
   Meanwhile, President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica announced his
government was prepared to administer a portion of a $48 million
humanitarian aid package for Nicaragua approved by the U.S.
Congress last month to treat Nicaraguan children injured in the
civil war.
   Nicaraguan President Ortega rejected as ``illegal'' plans to
have the U.S. Agency for International Development administer the
aid, including assistance for the Contras.
   The Sapoa accord calls for a neutral party to administer any
outside humanitarian aid for the Contras.
   ``We can never neglect our aid to the children victims of the
war. It is a matter of a humanitarian gesture and I will try to do
it,'' Arias said.
   Arias received the Nobel Peace Prize in December for authoring
the regional peace plan signed by Central America's five presidents
on Aug. 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
