<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru   04-08 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0508,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Meets With Lebanese President, Calls it `Productive'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Shultz meeting Gemayel and
to include first reference to Assad in 8th graf, `Whether it...'
Picks up 10th graf pvs, `An administration...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met
today with President Amil Gemayel of Lebanon in an effort to seal a
Syrian-arranged deal for a new Lebanese constitution to end
Lebanon's 12-year-old civil war.
   Shultz, who is headed home from a futile effort in the Middle
East to try to set up Arab-Israeli peace talks, met with Gemayel at
Larnaca Airport for 90 minutes. The Cyprus stop wasn't announced in
advance.
   After the meeting, Shultz announced that April Glasbie, head of
the Lebanon desk in the U.S. State Department, will go to Beirut to
continue the American mediation. Ms. Glasbie is now in Damascus
holding talks with Syrian leaders.
   Shultz said his talk with Gemayel was ``productive,'' but he
gave no details. After the meeting, Gemayel returned to Lebanon in
the army helicopter which brought him on the 100-mile flight to
Cyprus. He made no statement.
   Shultz told reporters before leaving Amman, Jordan, that
stability in Lebanon would be ``a great advantage in our efforts
against terrorism'' in seeking the release of nine Americans held
hostage in Lebanon.
   He said a new division of power among the competing factions
would help all countries in the area, including Israel, and Syria
itself.
   ``We want to see an election go off successfully'' in Lebanon,
Shultz said, referring to presidential balloting which must be held
by September, when Gemayel's term expires.
   Gemayel, a Maronite Christian, has sought for nearly six years
to gain control of his country. But Syria, Lebanon's more powerful
neighbor to the east, plays a dominant role in Lebanese politics.
   A new distribution of political power in Lebanon could reduce
Syria's military presence there, which is becoming an economic
drain on Damascus.
   Whether it would help American and other hostages is not clear,
although a senior U.S. official said Thursday that Shultz also
talked to Syrian President Hafez Assad about their plight.
   Many of the 22 foreign hostages are believed held by an
Iranian-influenced group, possibly beyond the reach of Syrian
power, although Syria has close ties with Iran. The longest-held
hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   An administration source said Thursday in Santa Barbara, Calif.,
where President Reagan is vacationing, that Reagan sent a letter to
Gemayel expressing concern about the continuing conflict in Lebanon.
   The official said he had not seen the letter, but ``I would
characterize it as underscoring the mutual interests that the
United States and Lebanon have in building peace in the region.''
   In Washington, a State Department official said the United
States was ``serving as a postman between Assad and Gemayel,'' who
have not spoken to each other in over a year.
   The two U.S. officials spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   The aim of a new Lebanese constitution would be to modify the
``national pact'' devised in 1943 that allocated the top positions
in the government to specific religious groups.
   The president is a Christian, the premier is a Sunni Moslem and
the speaker of Parliament is a Shiite Moslem. In the ensuing 45
years, Moslems overtook Christians as a majority and demanded a
larger role.
   If the diplomatic effort succeeds, it will mark a turnabout in
Shultz's fortunes in Lebanon.
   Five years ago, he thought he had worked out an agreement
between Lebanon and Israel for the two to cooperate economically,
politically and diplomatically. Syria undercut the accord and it
fell apart.
   In the meantime, Syria increased its power in Lebanon.
   In southern Lebanon, near the Israeli border, the situation is
especially unstable. Palestinians fought with the Shiite Amal
movement while Hezbollah, an Iranian-linked group, was suspected of
kidnappings and hijackings.
   Israel, which drove to Beirut in a 1982 invasion, is arming the
Christian-led South Lebanese Army militia and occupies a strip of
land north of its border.
   Reagan accused Syria in 1986 of promoting terrorism. He ordered
U.S. Ambassador William Eagleton to withdraw, barred high-level
meetings with Syrian officials, stopped sales of high technology
and imposed other sanctions.
   Last September, Eagleton was sent back to Damascus and most of
the sanctions quietly disappeared. Shultz stopped in Damascus twice
last month and returned again Tuesday.
   Assad is an outspoken supporter of the PLO's having a separate
seat at proposed Middle East peace talks. Shultz's plan would
exclude the Palestine Liberation Organization and seat Palestinians
as part of a Jordanian delegation.
   Assad also demands Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, a
security belt Syria lost in the 1967 Six-Day War that now serves as
a buffer to protect northern Israeli villages from a resumption of
bombardment from across the border.
</TEXT>
