<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghan-Chronology 1stLd-Writethru a0481 04-08 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan-Chronology, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghan Prospects, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with today's announcement in Geneva.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following is a chronology of the major events in
the Afghanistan war:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1978</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   APRIL 27-28 _ Pro-Soviet Marxist party of Afghanistan overthrows
republic and installs Nur Mohammad Taraki as president. Armed,
non-communist resistance begins.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1979</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SEPTEMBER _ Taraki killed in intraparty showdown with deputy
Hafizullah Amin.
   DEC. 24 _ Soviets begin massive airlift to Kabul that brings
40,000 troops to the country within days.
   DEC. 27 _ Amin killed and replaced by President Babrak Karmal in
coup reputedly backed by Moscow.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1980</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JANUARY _ United Nations demands ``immediate, unconditional and
total withdrawal of foreign troops'' from Afghanistan. U.S.
President Jimmy Carter announces sanctions against Soviet Union.
   JUNE 25 _ Soviets reject Carter's proposal for settlement.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1981</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   APRIL _ President Reagan lifts grain embargo imposed on Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   APRIL _ Number of Afghan refugees in Pakistan, rear base of
Afghan guerrillas, reported at 2.5 million.
   JUNE _ In Geneva, U.N. official Diego Cordovez conducts first
indirect peace talks between Afghanistan and Pakistan, which speaks
for Afghan resistance.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1984</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JANUARY _ Guerrillas gain temporary control of Kandahar, the
second-largest city in Afghanistan.
   APRIL _ Soviets begin saturation bombing of guerrilla
strongholds and villages.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1985</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   MAY _ In Pakistan, fundamentalist Moslem guerrillas join
moderates to form seven-party coalition.
   DECEMBER _ Afghanistan offers timetable for Soviet withdrawal.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   MAY _ Karmal replaced by Najib, former head of secret police.
   SEPTEMBER _ Guerrillas, supported by significant U.S. arms
shipments, reportedly receive first U.S. Stinger anti-aircraft
missiles. Within months, they reportedly shoot down average of one
enemy aircraft per day.
   MID-OCTOBER _ 8,000 of the more than 100,000 Soviet soldiers
withdraw from Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 15 _ Guerrillas reject any power-sharing with Communists.
   NOV. 30 _ Najib says Soviet soldiers could be withdrawn in
12-month period.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   FEBRUARY _ Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev offers to withdraw
Soviet troops beginning May 15, if Geneva talks produce accord by
March 15.
   MARCH _ New round of U.N.-mediated talks begins in Geneva. Talks
stalled by disagreements between Afghanistan and Pakistan over
continued foreign aid to warring sides and makeup of future Afghan
government. U.S. and Soviets disagree on military aid to rebels and
government.
   APRIL 3-6 _ Shevardnadze in Kabul to work out plan to pull out
Soviet troops in event negotiations in Geneva fail to produce
accord to end war.
   APRIL 7 _ Gorbachev and Najib meet and issue statement saying
all obstacles have been cleared in negotiations to end war and
Soviets hope to start pulling their troops out in May.
   APRIL 8 _ Cordovez announces a peace settlement to end the war
is completed and ready to be signed by April 14. Details of the
accord, which calls for the United States and Soviet Union to sign
as guarantors, are not disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
