<DOCNO> AP880408-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Pollution     04-08 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Pollution,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smog-Covered Soviet City Site of Mass Anti-Pollution Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 residents of an industrial city
in the Ural Mountains staged a street demonstration to protest smog
that has burned skin and caused lung and heart problems, a
newspaper reported.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda, the daily of the youth organization
Komsomol, said the protesters in the city of Nizhny Tagil demanded
that two 45-year-old coke-burning furnaces at a steel plant be
closed.
   ``Who will answer for the 54 stillborn children in 1987?'' a
crying woman said at the demonstration.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda did not say when the protest occurred in
the city of 405,000 people 900 miles east of Moscow, but it
appeared to have been in February or March.
   There have been several reports of environmental protests in the
Soviet Union since Communist Party General Secretary Mikhail S.
Gorbachev came to power three years ago and encouraged freer
expression.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda, in an article published Wednesday, said
the government lists Nizhny Tagil among the 50 Soviet cities whose
pollution level exceeds sanitary standards.
   Smog is common in the city, and in the morning, the faces of
children on the way to kindergarten burn, the newspaper said.
   One doctor said the number of children hospitalized for serious
lung and heart ailments caused by pollution had risen by 33
percent. He didn't say over what period.
   A commission of the Presidium of the Russian republic's Council
of Ministers, the republic's highest governmental body, ordered the
two coke-burning furnaces at the Nizhny Tagil Metallurgical Complex
closed last September because of excessive pollution, the newspaper
said.
   But the Ministry of Ferrous Metallurgy decided to keep the
furnaces open until new, cleaner furnaces were completed.
   The complex, which includes plants that build railroad cars and
boilers, and a cement factory, spews out 629,000 tons of harmful
substances a year, according to Komsomolskaya Pravda.
   The health problems led to what Komsomolskaya Pravda called ``an
explosion in public consciousness.''
   Children sent the top party official of the metallurgical
complex drawings of ``smokestacks, smog enveloping living areas and
the handwritten words: `I don't want to die!'''
   After the demonstration, the minister of ferrous metallurgy
ordered one of the two coke furnaces stopped, but the other
``continues to pollute the city,'' the newspaper said. A petition
signed by 8,500 Nizhny Tagil residents demanding further action has
been sent to the national Council of Ministers, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
