<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteigerVerdict     04-08 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steiger Verdict,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steiger Guilty Of Theft By Extortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BURT GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top aide to impeached Gov. Evan
Mecham has been convicted of theft by extortion for threatening a
parole board member to get him to support a Mecham appointee.
   Sam Steiger, 59, a former five-term congressman, was found
guilty Thursday by a Maricopa County Superior Court jury that
deliberated for 3{ hours.
   Neither Steiger nor his attorney, Tom Karas, would say whether
they planned an appeal. ``We'll take it one step at a time,'' Karas
said.
   ``It's safe to say I'm not real pleased,'' Steiger told
reporters.
   Steiger was found guilty of threatening to withhold permission
for Ron Johnson, a member of the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles, to work as a part-time Tempe justice of the peace, and
threatening to remove him from the board unless he voted to retain
executive director Patricia Costello, a Mecham appointee.
   Judge Ronald Reinstein scheduled a May 6 sentencing for Steiger,
who faces up to five years in prison. Steiger is free on his own
recognizance.
   ``We don't take joy in a conviction, but we feel it was a fair
trial,'' said prosecutor Michael Cudahy, an assistant attorney
general. ``We felt it was a just verdict.''
   Jury foreman Greg Jones said the deciding factor behind the
verdict was ``the tapes of the phone call between Steiger and
Johnson.'' Johnson called Steiger at home from the office of the
state attorney general, who recorded the call.
   Jones said the jurors had no difficulty reaching a verdict. ``We
listened to all the tapes and examined all the evidence again, but
it was unanimous,'' he said.
   Steiger, asked what he'd do differently, said: ``I'd have
probably hung up on Ron Johnson when he called me at home.''
   Reached shortly after the verdict was announced, Mecham said,
``I'm sad to hear it. Sam meant no harm to anybody, and I'm sorry
to hear it.''
   Mecham was removed from office Monday when the state Senate
convicted him of two impeachment charges.
   Steiger denied on the stand Monday that he threatened Johnson or
told him how he should vote.
   But the state alleged that Steiger followed up on the alleged
threat in a letter and a telephone conversation after Johnson voted
with the board majority to seek Ms. Costello's resignation on
grounds of low staff morale.
   Steiger testified that he did suggest that Johnson should back
Ms. Costello but denied that he tried to ``steal'' Johnson's vote
by threatening his job.
   He acknowledged lying to an attorney general's investigator when
he originally denied making the threat.
   Steiger gave up his 3rd Congressional District seat in 1976 to
run unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate.
</TEXT>
