<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NewYork-Poll 1stLd-Writethru a0455 04-08 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New York-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf pvs, Another 8, to restore date of primary.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis held a widening lead over Jesse Jackson two weeks before
New York's primary, a poll indicated today.
   The Marist College Institute for Public Opinion said 47 percent
of likely New York voters picked Dukakis; 31 percent backed Jackson
and 6 percent chose Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
   An additional 8 percent said they would vote for an
``uncommitted'' slate of delegates that hopes to draft New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo for the nomination at the national convention. The
primary is April 19.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who put his campaign into mothballs on
Thursday, was supported by 2 percent of the Democrats surveyed and
6 percent said they were undecided.
   The margin of error for the poll, conducted Tuesday and
Wednesday, was 5 percentage points.
   In a similar poll conducted in mid-March by the Marist
pollsters, Dukakis was the choice of 37 percent of the Democrats;
Jackson had 28 percent; Gore had 5 percent; uncommitted was at 10
percent; Simon was at 4 percent; and 13 percent said they were
undecided.
   Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute, said Dukakis
appeared to be doing best in the suburban counties surrounding New
York City and in upstate New York. He said Dukakis was running
about even with Jackson in New York City.
   Jackson's support among white voters remained at about 14
percent in the latest Marist poll, the same as in the mid-March
poll.
   Among Jewish voters, who make up about 25 percent of the New
York Democratic primary voters, Dukakis was the choice of 68
percent of those surveyed; Gore was at 10 percent; and Jackson at 9
percent. In the mid-March poll, Dukakis was the choice of 60
percent of the likely Jewish voters; Gore was at 9 percent; and
Jackson was at 4 percent.
   The race appeared to be a bit tighter when only Democrats who
said they were ``very likely'' to vote in the primary were
questioned, said Miringoff, Among that group _ which could be
important if there is a low voter turnout _ Dukakis was at 42
percent; Jackson at 34 percent; Gore at 8 percent; uncommitted at 8
percent; Simon at 2 percent; and 6 percent said they were undecided.
   Regarding Cuomo, 46 percent of those Democrats surveyed said the
governor should run for president, down from 59 percent in
mid-March, while 16 percent said they expected him to eventually
run, down from 24 percent.
   With Cuomo declining to endorse any of the candidates, the
Marist pollsters also asked Democrats if Cuomo should endorse
someone before the New York primary.
   Almost 31 percent said the governor should endorse, 25 percent
said he shouldn't and 43 percent said it didn't make any difference
to them what Cuomo did.
   Cuomo has said he doesn't want to be a candidate, but has
refused to rule out accepting a draft if there is a deadlocked
national convention.
</TEXT>
