<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Coup Failure,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0472 to include Panama in keyword</HEAD>
<HEAD>Attempted Anti-Noriega Coup Failed Ignominiously, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempted coup attempt last month against
Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega failed ignominiously
when an officer loyal to Noriega locked the plotters inside an
arsenal, a newspaper reported today.
   Citing unidentified senior administration officials, the Chicago
Tribune reported in today's editions that the failure of the
allegedly U.S.-backed coup has left the Reagan administration's
anti-Noriega plans in chaos.
   The newspaper said several anti-Noriega members of the
15,000-member Panama Defense Forces went to the Central American
nation's main arsenal in Panama City last month to obtain guns for
the attempt, pretending to be on official military business.
   The guard commander at the arsenal, however, locked the plotters
inside and reported to his superiors that he thought a coup was in
progress, the newspaper reported.
   Swift action by Noriega's supporters put down the conspiracy and
resulted in the purge or arrest of nearly three dozen anti-Noriega
officers during the last several weeks, the Tribune reported.
   The newspaper quoted a source identified only as a well-placed
military expert as saying the abortive coup demonstrates ``the
depth to which the administration planners have underestimated
Noriega and misunderstood the situation there.''
