<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0524,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says It Fired Missiles During Iranian Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Iran retaliating. Pick up
6th graf pvs: ``Iranians went...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it fired four missiles into
Iranian cities today hours before Iranians cast ballots in
important parliamentary elections.
   Tehran retaliated by shooting two missiles into Baghdad, another
two into the northern city of Mosul and one into al-Amarah farther
south, Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said.
   The Iraqi News Agency confirmed one of the strikes on Baghdad
and said civilians were killed. It also said Iraqi civilians were
killed when Iranian long-range artillery shelled Iraqi border
cities.
   An Associated Press reporter in Tehran said there was a loud
explosion before dawn near the city's railway station.
   The Iraqi agency said the missiles were fired into Tehran, the
holy city of Qom, the central city of Isfahan and the northwestern
city of Tabriz. Both news agencies were monitored in Nicosia.
   It also said Iraqi warplanes Thursday night raided a ``large
maritime target,'' which usually means an oil tanker. There was no
immediate confirmation from Persian Gulf shipping sources.
   IRNA said missiles landed in residential areas of Tehran and
Isfahan. It gave no casualty toll. It also said Iraqi warplanes
raided several Iranian cities, but gave no further details.
   The Iranian agency said Iranian planes bombed military targets
in northern Iraq, but the Iraqi agency said the planes bombed
residential neighborhoods in the northern city of Amadiya, killing
civilians.
   Iranians went to the polls to elect 270 members of the Majlis,
or parliament, balloting that was expected to increase the power of
radicals who want economic changes such as land reforms, a minimum
wage and policies that favor the poor.
   On Thursday, Iran said its warplanes sneaked through Iraqi radar
into Baghdad and bombed a military base and oil refinery, killing
or wounding dozens of Iraqi soldiers.
   It was the first reported bombing of the Iraqi capital in three
years. Iraq denied the city was hit Thursday, but the ferocity of
Iraqi attacks later gave some credence to the Iranian claims.
   Both sides bombarded each other's cities and towns Thursday with
missiles and reported scores of civilian casualties.
   Also Thursday, a U.N. team arrived in Baghdad to investigate
Iraqi allegations Iran used chemical weapons in a March 30-31
battle in northeastern Iraq. Iran accused Iraq of using chemical
weapons in the same battle.
