<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Texaco-Pennzoil 1stLd-Writethru a0469 04-08 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Pennzoil, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Feud Between Texaco And Pennzoil Ends Quietly In Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf, `As a ...,' to explain why
transfer was made in four payments. A version moving on financial
wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the end, the four-year corporate war that
forced oil giant Texaco into bankruptcy and the largest civil award
in U.S. history came down to a silent, 10-minute electronic payment
of $3 billion to Pennzoil.
   The transfer settling Pennzoil's takeover lawsuit against Texaco
took place Thursday in a high-security room at Texas Commerce
Bank-Houston _ and, coincidentally, halfway between Pennzoil
headquarters and the Texaco Building.
   As a half-dozen tight-lipped bank and Pennzoil executives
watched, a green computer screen signaled the arrival of four
Texaco payments, starting at 10:03 a.m. and ending at 10:13 a.m.
About a dozen reporters and photographers watched.
   The transfer had to be broken down into four payments, since the
Federal Reserve System can transfer amounts only as high as one
cent short of $1 billion.
   When the transfer was complete, a few people applauded.
   ``We're all very glad it's all over,'' said David Alderson,
Pennzoil assistant treasurer.
   ``Quite frankly, we've been in a holding pattern for over four
years,'' Pennzoil Chairman J. Hugh Liedtke said later Thursday.
   ``We think we're now in a position to invest these funds and to
make up for lost time,'' Liedtke said.
   The settlement of the suit, which stemmed from Texaco's 1984
acquisition of Getty Oil Co., allowed the White Plains, N.Y.-based
company to emerge from bankruptcy protection.
   It was part of Texaco's bankruptcy reorganization plan, which a
federal judge approved March 23. Texaco also will begin paying $2.6
billion to other creditors.
   Pennzoil, looking for long-term ways to invest the windfall,
actually borrowed $3 billion a couple of weeks ago so it could
begin investing it in an orderly manner, spokesman Bob Harper said.
   The war began with Texaco's acquisition of Getty. Pennzoil sued
Texaco, claiming interference with a planned merger between
Pennzoil and Getty.
   In November 1985, a Houston jury shocked Texaco by agreeing with
Pennzoil and awarding the Houston company $10.53 billion in
damages, the largest civil award in U.S. history.
   A state appeals court upheld the verdict, but reduced the $3
billion in punitive damages to $1 billion.
   Nearly a year ago, Texaco filed for bankruptcy protection,
saying it had to do so to avoid posting a potentially ruinous
appeal bond.
   In November, the Texas Supreme Court refused to hear Texaco's
appeal and let the verdict stand. Texaco then said it was going to
the U.S. Supreme Court, but a committee of shareholders proposed
the settlement.
   The premise of Pennzoil's case was that a handshake and a
person's word was as good as a written contract, and that Texaco
violated that rule by plucking Getty from Pennzoil's grasp.
   Texaco contended Getty had invited it to bid and that there was
no valid contract between Pennzoil and Getty because all the papers
had not been signed by the appropriate parties.
   Texaco also put Texas' court system under scrutiny, challenging
the trial judge's credentials and complaining that Texas Supreme
Court judges were influenced by large campaign contributions from
Houston lawyer Joe Jamail, who led the Pennzoil case.
   Although he was delighted to settle the case, Liedtke said the
outcome probably was not as good for Pennzoil as gaining Getty
would have been.
   ``I don't think that ($3 billion) in any way replaces totally
the loss the company has suffered. But it remains to be seen how
astutely these funds are reinvested and perhaps we can make up for
lost ground,'' he said.
   Attorney's fees, including Jamail's, come to about $400 million,
according to Pennzoil. Jamail declined to reveal his share.
   ``I'll spend (the money) on the important things like whiskey
and women,'' he said, smiling.
   Texaco officials had no comment on the payment.
   Pennzoil also announced Thursday that its board adopted a new
anti-takeover defense, a preferred stock purchase rights plan, to
replace a similar ``poison pill'' put in place after the jury made
its award.
   The old plan was designed to block a corporate raider from
appropriating the benefits of the Texaco case before it had been
resolved, Harper said.
   The new plan also was designed to protect Pennzoil from ``unfair
or coercive actions by opportunistic parties'' and give Pennzoil
time to make acquisitions using the Texaco money, Liedtke said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSVirus     04-08 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Virus,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Step In Activation Of AIDS Virus Discovered By Scientists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS virus must make a precise
change in its protein coat before it can infect cells, and drugs
that can block that change might be able to prevent AIDS
infections, researchers say in a study published today.
   The researchers, from the Stanford University School of
Medicine, said they don't know whether such drugs could be
developed in a form that could make tham safe and effective for use
in humans.
   The scientists discovered that the AIDS virus, a piece of
genetic material housed in a complex envelope of fats and proteins,
can infect cells only if its outer envelope protein is clipped into
two pieces.
   If this cleavage doesn't occur, the virus particles assemble and
appear normal but are disarmed and unable to infect new cells, said
the leader of the study, Dr. Mike McCune, who works in the lab of
Dr. Irving Weissman, professor of pathology at Stanford's School of
Medicine. The results appear today in the journal Cell.
   The scientists demonstrated their findings by constructing a
mutant strain of the AIDS virus that could not complete the
critical step. They found it was unable to enter and infect human
cells in tissue culture.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome has struck 58,270 people
since June 1981, the federal Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta
reported this week. The disease has killed 32,545.
   The researchers believe the cleavage step is critical to the
virus' infectivity because it makes the virus' envelope protein
``sticky,'' which allows it to fuse to the membrane of a cell it
seeks to infect.
   After the virus has fused to the cell's membrane, it can enter
the cell and remain hidden from the body's immune system, reproduce
and eventually begin to spread infection throughout the body.
   The scientists believe that if they can prevent the AIDS virus
from sticking to cells, they might be able to suppress infection.
   The study was sponsored by grants from the National Cancer
Institute and the National Institutes of Health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CalifAssembly     04-08 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Calif Assembly,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Penalty, Wiretap Bills Advance In Political Shenanigans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Assembly has approved a bill
to allow the death penalty for people who kill children and set the
stage for a vote next week on a wiretap measure aimed at drug
dealers.
   Both votes were considered defeats for Speaker Willie Brown and
were led by minority Republicans and the so-called Gang of Five,
dissident Democrats opposed to Brown.
   The votes came during a five-hour floor session Thursday marked
by closed-door party caucuses, numerous small floor huddles and a
constant undercurrent of rumors that Brown might soon be ousted by
the 36 Republicans teaming with the Gang of Five. It takes 41 votes
to elect or remove a speaker in the 80-member Assembly.
   The two anti-crime bills had been stalled in the Public Safety
Committee.
   The death penalty bill was killed by that committee on March 21.
On Monday, Republicans and the Gang of Five combined to withdraw it
from committee, on a 41-30 vote, the first such successful
withdrawal motion in 28 years. Such motions are considered a
challenge to the authority of the speaker, who appoints committee
members.
   The bill would make child murder a special circumstance
qualifying a murderer for the death sentence, along with such other
specified crimes as murder of a police office or elected official,
or murder committed during a felony.
   The bill was approved 62-7 after a long and emotional debate and
sent to the Senate.
   The original wiretap bill was approved by the Senate last June
and has been in the Public Safety Committee since then.
   Supporters could not try to withdraw that bill because it hadn't
been rejected by the committee, so instead they took an unrelated
bill introduced by the same lawmaker, Sen. Robert Presley, that was
already on the floor and with his permission voted 48-13 to amend
it by adding the wiretap measure.
   The amended bill is scheduled for a floor vote next Thursday.
   The bill would allow police with approval of the attorney
general or a district attorney to petition a Superior Court for a
wiretap authorization. The police would have to show that it was
likely that a drug possession or sale offense had been or would be
committed.
</TEXT>
