<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrackHouseSting     04-08 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crack House Sting,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 32 In Sting Operation At Seized `Crack House'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided and seized a house where
crack was sold and operated it themselves for seven hours in a
sting operation in which 32 people were arrested, officers say.
   The arrests were a new strategy aimed at sowing fear among crack
users, said Capt. B. Ray Armand, head of the city police narcotic
squad.
   ``You always go after the top people selling the drugs, but now
we're attacking the demand factor,'' Armand said. ``We're probably
going to do this again. It was very successful.''
   During the operation Wednesday night and early Thursday,
officers were leading people they had arrested out the front door
of the house while new customers were coming in the back, he said.
   At times, officers said, people were lined up at the back door
and as many as six customer cars lined the curb while police
hurriedly packaged the crack form of cocaine in plastic bags.
   Several female customers left children, including one less than
a year old, in their cars while they went inside to purchase crack,
officers said.
   Officers said customers continued to enter the house even after
a woman reported on a citizens band radio that police had taken
over the house.
   ``We turned away twice as many (suspects) as we arrested,''
Armand said. ``They will go to any lengths to get drugs.''
   People were arrested on investigative charges of possession of a
controlled substance.
</TEXT>
