<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   04-08 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0545,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Autopsy Report Raises Question on Cause of Girl's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 13th graf, `On Thursday...' to CORRECT that Israeli
civilians damaged two neighboring villages, sted Beita. Pick up
14th pvs, `Israel radio...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An autopsy of an Israeli girl killed in a clash
with Palestinians found that she was struck in the head by a bullet
and a large object and cast doubts on army reports that Arabs
stoned her to death.
   Details provided by Israel television and radio raised the
possibility that 15-year-old Tirza Porat was shot accidentally by
one of the guards accompanying teen-age Jewish settlers on a
holiday hike in the West Bank.
   Two Arabs were killed and two were wounded in the incident
Wednesday in the village of Beita.
   Today, two Palestinians were shot and wounded in separate
clashes with troops in anti-occupation unrest in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials said.
   On Jerusalem's Temple Mount, several dozen Palestinians shouted
nationalist slogans after noon prayers on the Moslem Sabbath.
Demonstrators dispersed quickly after about 10 border policemen
approached.
   It remained unclear how Tirza was killed. The army first said
she and the two Arabs were shot to death. It later said Tirza was
stoned to death by villagers.
   An army official, citing autopsy results, then said Tirza was
struck in the head by both a bullet and a large object, possibly a
stone. The official said the cause of death was not yet known and
that investigators did not know from which weapon the bullet was
fired.
   Israel Television, quoting a military source, said the bullet
was fired from one of the two guards' M-16 rifles but that it
wasn't known who pulled the trigger. The source also was quoted as
saying that when Arabs wrested the guns away from the Israeli
guards, they probably were already empty.
   Israel radio quoted an army report as saying that Tirza also was
struck in the head by a rock hurled by the mother and sister of one
of the Arabs killed. The two women were arrested, the report said.
   The next day, the army blew up five homes of Beita Arabs
allegedly involved in the clash and rounded up hundreds of Arabs
for questioning. Soldiers fatally shot an Arab youth who the army
said ignored orders to stop.
   Tirza, the first Israeli civilian killed in four months of
unrest in the occupied territories, was buried near her home in the
West Bank settlement Elon Moreh. According to U.N. figures, 141
Arabs and one Israeli soldier have died.
   The girl's death increased tension between the 1.5 million
Palestinians and the 65,000 Jewish settlers living the territories
occupied by Israel since the 1967 Middle East war.
   On Thursday, armed Israeli civilians beat residents, broke
windows and fired shots into the air in two villages near Beita.
   Israel radio, citing army investigators, said Wednesday's
violence began after a group of 16 teen-agers from Elon Moreh,
accompanied by two armed guards, were stoned by Arab youths as they
hiked near Beita.
   The two guards disagreed over what to do next, the radio report
said. One of the guards, Romam Al Dubi, 26, wanted to open fire,
but the second guard, Menachem Ilan, 55, asked him not to,
according to the report.
   Al Dubi then told the children to gather around him to serve as
a barrier, and started shooting, the radio report said. The Arab
youths eventually disarmed him and took the Israelis to Beita,
where they were attacked by villagers, the report said.
   Thirteen Israelis were wounded in the clash.
   Israeli media reports have identified Al Dubi as an extreme
religious nationalist and a follower of the anti-Arab Kach movement
of U.S. born Rabbi Meir Kahane.
   Last year, the army barred Al Dubi from entering the West Bank
city of Nablus for three months after he repeatedly sought
confrontations with Arabs over prayer rights at a site in the city,
which is holy to both Arabs and Jews.
   The army's West Bank commander, Maj. Gen. Armram Mitzna, told
Israel Television that ``hundreds'' of Beita villagers played a
role in Wednesday's clash.
   However, army officials also have said many villagers helped the
teen-agers, hiding some in their homes and calling ambulances.
   Beita remained under curfew as soldiers searched for residents,
many of whom had fled to nearby ravines and neighboring villages.
   Israel Television said the army distributed leaflets in the area
calling on Beita residents to surrender.
</TEXT>
