<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pulitzer-Complaint     04-08 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pulitzer-Complaint,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Magazine Calls Reporting Prize Unmerited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An executive of a second magazine has echoed a
complaint that this year's Pulitzer Prize to a Philadelphia
Inquirer reporter should be reconsidered because the winning entry
did not break new ground.
   Harper's magazine publisher John R. MacArthur said Thursday he
agreed with the contention of a Washington weekly, the National
Journal, that the series on secret Pentagon spending by Tim Weiner
leaned heavily on information another reporter published in the two
magazines.
   The formal complaint of the Journal will be discussed by the
executive committee of the Pulitzer board and some kind of judgment
should be made by next week, the board's secretary, Robert
Christopher, said.
   Christopher added that ``breaking new ground'' is not a
requirement for winning the national reporting prize.
   Richard Frank, editor of the National Journal, said in a letter
to the board that Weiner's series was built on an earlier story in
the Journal by David C. Morrison and ``plows no new journalistic
ground.''
   MacArthur said Weiner's stories were accompanied by an annotated
document similar to a feature Morrison did for the January 1987
issue of Harper's.
   ``It doesn't seem quite right that the Inquirer gets a Pulitzer
Prize unless originality has nothing to do with prize giving these
days,'' MacArthur said in a telephone call to The Associated Press.
He said he did not plan to write the Pulitzer board.
   Christopher said only he and the board chairman, David
Laventhol, had seen the complaint, but copies were being circulated
to the half dozen members of the executive committee.
   Laventhol, president of Times Mirror Co., which owns the
National Journal, said the magazine checked with him before
protesting.
   Laventhol said he told the Journal to go ahead if it felt
strongly about the issue. He said his acquiescence did not
necessarily mean he agreed with its position.
   Another board member, Eugene L. Roberts Jr., the Inquirer's
executive editor, said his only role in the review would be to
respond to the Journal's complaint and answer questions of other
board members.
</TEXT>
