<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MountTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0482 04-08 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mount Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Document Theft Case Set For The Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing arguments expected
to be completed by midday. Picks up in 3rd graf, `Mount is ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Merrill Mount is a man of contradictions.
Born and raised in Brooklyn, he has the accent and manners of a
British gentleman. A published biographer and Guggenheim Foundation
fellow, he wears natty suits from the Salvation Army.
   Perhaps the biggest contradiction, however, is whether he is a
scholarly collector of rare documents or a thief.
   Today a jury will be asked to decide if he is a scholarly
collector of rare documents or a thief. Closing arguments were
expected to be completed by midday, with jury deliberation to
follow.
   Mount is charged with interstate transportation of stolen goods,
letters and documents he allegedly stole from the Library of
Congress and the National Archives. The charge carries a possible
sentence of 10 years in prison and $500,000.
   Mount's friends say the charges are unbelievable. His lawyer
says they are unprovable.
   ``I don't think he could have done it psychologically,'' said
Gloucester artist John Manship, who testified for Mount during his
three-week trial. ``He has too much respect for history and
scholarship to steal from archives.''
   An engaging man with a sharp wit and piercing blue eyes, Mount
contends he has been reduced to poverty since the government seized
his savings. He was evicted from his Washington boarding house and
has stayed at a YMCA during the trial. The court rejected his pleas
for money to bring witnesses over from Ireland who he claims can
prove his ownership of the documents.
   ``I'm not allowed witnesses,'' he said. ``It's not a trial.''
   Mount is charged with selling a Boston bookshop letters written
by artist James McNeill Whistler, Winston Churchill and author
Henry James that belonged to the Library of Congress. He was
arrested while allegedly trying to sell letters and documents
signed by Abraham Lincoln and various Civil War generals that had
been taken from the National Archives.
   Mount has not been charged with theft, but Assistant U.S.
Attorney Martin Murphy said in the trial's opening arguments that
it is the government's contention that Mount took the papers.
   The prosecution presented testimony establishing that Mount had
access to the documents in May and July 1987.
   Mount testified he bought the Whistler papers at Paris shops in
the 50s and 60s and received the Civil War papers from an Irish
parish priest in 1961 who gave him the documents in a biscuit tin.
The priest has since died.
   The defense also has noted that Mount has over the years donated
many of his papers to the Library of Congress.
   ``Why would I steal from my own heirs?'' Mount asked.
   Charles McGinty, Mount's public defender, has attacked the
government's case as a ``shoddy arrest not justified by any kind of
investigative effort.''
   ``They never had definitive word from the institutions that the
letters were missing from their files,'' he said.
   The defense's case has largely rested on Mount's testimony and
the prosecution has raised questions about his background. At the
time of his arrest in August, the government revealed Mount was
born Sherman Suchow 59 years ago in Brooklyn and once was charged
with making false statements in a passport application.
   Mount freely admits he is ``a product of Brooklyn,'' and
attributes his accent to his Irish neighbors. His conviction on the
passport charge was reversed on appeal.
   Mount has been recognized for his work as an artist and writer.
He has written well-received biographies of painters John Singer
Sargent, Gilbert Stuart and Claude Monet. He received a Guggenheim
fellowship in 1956.
   But Mount frets his reputation has been destroyed by the case no
matter what the verdict.
   ``To be charged with something of a sleazy nature at this time
in my life, it's a disgrace,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
