<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     04-08 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nardi Pleads Guilty To Being Presser Ghost Employee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after lawyers for Teamsters President
Jackie Presser challenged federal prosecutors to ``put up or shut
up,'' a potentially key witness for Presser's labor racketeering
and embezzlement trial entered a guilty plea.
   John A. ``Jack'' Nardi Jr., 46, appeared before U.S. District
Judge George W. White and pleaded guilty Thursday to being a
``ghost employee'' of Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland from 1972 to
1978. He was paid about $109,000 without doing any work for the
local, of which Presser was secretary-treasurer.
   The guilty pleas put in effect an agreement that requires Nardi
to testify as a government witness. The judge deferred sentencing
and said that Nardi's cooperation with government prosecutors would
be considered when sentencing eventually occurs.
   Nardi's plea came as Presser's lawyers were seeking to have
White dismiss all charges _ labor racketeering, embezzlement and
falsifying documents _ against the Teamsters boss.
   In documents filed with the court Wednesday, defense lawyers
alleged that an internal memo to former FBI Director William
Webster showed that Webster knew that Presser was authorized to
hire Nardi and others who did no work.
   Presser's role as an FBI informant has been confirmed repeatedly
in various legal proceedings.
   Presser's defense team stated: ``If authorization existed, then
no crime was committed ... but now when the proceedings have
reached the appropriate juncture for (prosecutors) to come forward
with its evidence and, in effect, `put up or shut up,' it fails to
`put up' anything.''
   Presser's trial is scheduled to begin July 12.
</TEXT>
