<HEAD>Corrupt Miami Cop Gets 35 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An officer found guilty of racketeering and drug
charges in a cocaine-corruption scandal that rocked the Miami
police department has been sentenced to 35 years in prison and
fined $250,000.
   U.S. District Judge Kennth L. Ryskamp said Thursday that Osvaldo
Coello, 28, will have to serve at least 11 years before being
eligible for parole.
   Prosecutors said Coello belonged to a band of 15 corrupt
officers who stole drugs from smugglers and resold them.
   Coello was convicted Feb. 9 of racketeering, racketeering
conspiracy and two counts each of cocaine conspiracy and possession
with intent to distribute cocaine.
   He was acquitted of violating the civil rights of three men who
drowned in the Miami River during a raid on a drug boat.
   Coello was recaptured Oct. 5 in the Bahamas after he jumped bond
following a mistrial last year.
