<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Germans, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0523,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Germans Held By Shiites Freed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT names and ADD details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West German relief workers held
captive by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem militants were freed when
rival Syrian-backed Shiite militiamen overran the militants' south
Lebanon stronghold, police said today.
   The pair, a man and a woman who worked for a West German
humanitarian organization identified as Asme Humanitas, disappeared
after leaving the Palestinian refugee camp of Mieh Mieh in Sidon
Wednesday morning, police said.
   They were released Thursday night, police said.
   They were identified as Heinrich Strubig, 47, the director of
the organization in Mieh Mieh, and his assistant, Petra Schnitzler,
24, of Hamburg.
   Police said they had been held in the basement of a mosque by
the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, in the coastal town of
Ghaziyeh.
   Fighters of Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal militia released
them when they stormed Ghaziyeh after a four-day battle between the
rival factions for control of predomininantly Shiite south Lebanon.
   The Germans were taken from Ghaziyeh to the Hammoud Hospital in
Sidon, the provincial capital, this morning, police said.
   Doctors pronounced Trobig physically fit and quickly discharged
him, police said.
   But Ms. Schnitzler, who is diabetic and had several scratches on
her hands, was kept in the hospital for treatment, police added.
Doctors said she suffered bullet shrapnel cuts on one hand and
burns from another bullet that grazed her left wrist.
   Ms. Schnitzler, interviewed by a Sidon reporter, refused to say
whether she had been tortured in captivity.
   The abduction of the two West Germans had not been reported
before they were found.
   Ms. Schnitzler told The Associated Press that she and Strubig
were in an ambulance to distribute food and medicines when they
were stopped by armed men in at least two cars.
   The men fired several shots, forced the pair into a car and
drove them to the mosque.
   Strubig said the organization, based in Stadtoldendorf, began
providing social and medical assistance to Palestinian refugees and
poor Lebanese villagers in the Sidon region last November.
   Twenty-two foreigners, including nine Americans, are being held
captive in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East corresponsdent for The Associated Press. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
