<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-Flu     04-08 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Flu,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Separate Flu Variations Floating Around U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dominant type of flu this season has evolved
into four separate variations, complicating the task of developing
the proper vaccine for next winter, federal health officials say.
   Deaths from influenza and pneumonia have exceeded the Centers
for Disease Control's statistical ``epidemic threshold'' for the
past seven weeks. That figure is one indicator that the flu season
remains under way _ although the agency does not attempt to
tabulate the specific numbers of Americans dying from flu. Data is
collected from 121 cities but the CDC does not attempt to project a
national figure.
   Although the 1987-1988 flu season is winding down, some activity
continues, the CDC said. New York, Connecticut and New Hampshire
reported ``widespread'' flu outbreaks last week _ covering areas
including more than half the population.
   Eight other states _ Alaska, Delaware, Montana, New Mexico,
North Dakota, Oregon, Vermont and Washington _ reported less severe
``regional'' outbreaks.
   The type A-H3N2 flu prevalent this season has long been
associated with ``excess mortality,'' the CDC said.
   Late last year, when the influenza season got under way, the CDC
saw evidence of an apparent ``drift'' in the type A-H3N2, one of
three major types of flu.
   The A-H3N2 virus, the CDC said at the time, was ``drifting''
away from the Leningrad flu, the A-H3N2 strain the 1987-1988 flu
vaccine was designed to stop, and toward a somewhat different form.
   The CDC said Thursday in its weekly report it has now identified
four different variants of A-H3N2 flu virus circulating in the
United States in recent months; they are known as the Sichuan flu,
the Victoria flu, the Sydney flu and the Shanghai flu.
   The 1987-88 vaccine did not protect patients against the various
A-H3N2 viruses ``as well as it could have against (the) Leningrad
(flu),'' said Suzanne Gaventa, a researcher with the influenza
branch.
   The four different viruses present a problem for immunization
experts, Ms. Gaventa said.
   The Atlanta-based CDC's Immunization Practices Advisory
Committee each year recommends which flu types the next winter's
vaccine should protect against, and which specific strains of those
types should be targeted. The reports of the four different A-H3N2
strains circulating this past winter ``will be used in deciding
which H3N2 antigen to use'' in next winter's vaccine, Ms. Gaventa
said.
   A flu vaccine can't protect optimally against four different flu
viruses belonging to the same type, she said. Instead, vaccine
experts will try to determine which virus to target, and how much
protection that vaccine might offer against closely related viruses.
   CDC recommends flu vaccine particularly for older people and
those who might be prone to severe complications from the flu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UnhealthyBuildings     04-08 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unhealthy Buildings,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy-Efficient Buildings May Pose Health Risk, Researchers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor indoor air quality caused by
energy-efficient heating, cooling and ventilation systems is a
serious health problem that may be aggravated by ignorance among
contractors, says an industry spokesman commenting on a study
released today.
   The study found that U.S. Army trainees housed in modern
barracks were about 50 percent more likely to contract a
respiratory infection during basic training than those who stayed
in older, better ventilated buildings.
   The study examined the incidence of influenza and other
respiratory illnesses among about 400,000 trainees at four U.S.
Army training centers from October 1982 to September 1986.
   The study says the findings may apply to office buildings and
other structures designed for maximum energy efficiency.
   ``In tight buildings with closed ventilation systems,
airborne-transmitted pathogens are not only recirculated and
concentrated but also efficiently dispersed through indoor living
spaces,'' the researchers wrote in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   By contrast, in `leaky'' older buildings, ``airborne-transmitted
agents are diluted by fresh, outdoor air and (are) relatively
quickly exhausted from indoor spaces,'' said the researchers from
the Walter Reed Army Insitute of Research in Washington.
   ``It is a serious problem, and there's a lot of talk about it
... but it doesn't seem like too many people are doing too many
things to correct it. Maybe it's because they don't know what to do
to correct it,'' said David Bevirt, director of research for the
Sheet Metal and Air Conditioning Contractors National Association
in Vienna, Va.
   ``As soon as you take in additional ventilation, you're losing
more energy ... and so it's a trade-off'' between energy efficiency
and air quality, he said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   Although there are modern ventilation systems that offer energy
efficiency as well as improved air quality, they tend to be more
expensive and many contractors may not know about them, Bevirt said.
   His association is putting together a manual for its members
worldwide that includes information on how to test air quality and
what can be done to maximize it while offering energy efficiency as
well, he said.
   Most office buildings and other structures built during the
energy-conscious 1970s feature tight insulation and ventilation
systems designed to keep outside air outside, Bevirt said.
   In such buildings, ``Up to 95 percent of the air in the building
is recirculated,'' exposing occupants to used air that may be
filled with viruses and other contaminants, said Paul Klein, a
spokesman for the Army institute.
   The Walter Reed study was not the first to examine the so-called
``sick building syndrome,'' but it covered a larger population over
a longer time period, Klein said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   The researchers, led by Dr. John F. Brundage, noted that
respiratory tract infections are the most common infectious
illnesses in adults. They said recent studies indicate that such
infections annually account for 75 million U.S. physician visits,
1.25 million hospitalizations, $15 billion in direct medical costs
and about 150 million lost work days.
   Klein said the Army is reviewing the study's results to see how
much the building-related illnesses cost and whether any changes
are needed in the design and construction of its buildings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Chambers     04-08 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landlord Moves To Evict Robert Chambers' Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord is seeking to evict the mother of the
young man who pleaded guilty in a Central Park sex killing from her
luxury apartment for non-payment of rent, according to court papers.
   The papers, filed Tuesday in Manhattan Civil Court, show that
the landlord, 11 East 99th Associates, claimed Mary P. Chambers had
not paid rent from August through February and owed $16,733.40,
which includes $100 in legal fees.
   Mrs. Chambers' son, Robert, 21, pleaded guilty on March 25 to
first-degree manslaughter in the strangulation death of 18-year-old
Jennifer Levin. His agreement to plead came while the jury was
deliberating over a verdict.
   The court papers showed Mrs. Chambers, 55, pays $2,376.20 a
month for her fifth-floor apartment on the upper East Side. There
was no indication of the size of the apartment.
   According to the court papers, Mrs. Chambers, a night nurse who
makes about $70,000 a year caring for an elderly wealthy patient,
was served with legal papers warning her that eviction proceedings
were under way.
   Meanwhile, she filed a $40,000 counterclaim Thursday, charging
that the apartment has not been properly maintained.
   The phone of her lawyer, David Rosenholc, went unanswered
Thursday. But in court papers responding to the landlord's
petition, he alleged his client had not been properly served with
the papers and that the rent had not been properly calculated.
   The landlord's attorney, Niles Welikson, could not be reached
for comment. His telephone was answered by a man who said Welikson
could not be reached.
</TEXT>
