<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-AfghanProspects 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 04-08 0926</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Prospects, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,860</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs grafs 7-8 with new grafs 7-9 to update with Tass
dispatch and clarify that interim government discussion outside
U.N. talks</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The emerging agreement in Afghanistan would
send the Red Army home but may not stop the bloodshed in that
war-torn country.
   Under the United Nations-brokered deal, the Soviet Union could
continue arming the Kremlin-backed regime that seized power a
decade ago and the United States could continue arming the Moslem
guerrillas.
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his Afghan ally Najib
said jointly Thursday that ``the last obstacles to concluding the
agreements have now been removed'' and that Soviet troops can start
leaving on May 15 if the agreement is signed quickly.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez later told reporters the agreement
is ``now finalized and open for signature.'' He said the signing
ceremony is expected to take place within a week.
   President Reagan was ``cautiously optimistic'' but ``wants to
see the fine print,'' said Howard Baker, White House chief of staff.
   Secretary George P. Shultz said today on CBS's ``This Morning''
that judging from public statements, ``perhaps ... what we
suggested will be agreeable to them, but we still want to see the
answer.''
   Privately, administration officials interpreted the
Soviet-Afghan statement as acceptance of U.S. conditions on aid.
   With the apparent resolution of the aid issue, Cordovez is
expected to turn his attention to a Pakistani demand for the
formation of an interim government during the Soviet withdrawal,
according to U.S. officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The composition of such a government would be settled outside
the United Nations talks by the Afghans themselves, according to
Cordovez, American officials and a dispatch by the official Soviet
news agency Tass.
   With no interim government, say the Pakistanis, civil war will
rage, preventing the return to Afghanistan of an estimated 3
million Afghan refugees driven into Pakistan and another 2 million
in Iran.
   Guerrilla leaders, and many U.S. government analysts, believe
the pro-Kremlin regime will collapse as the Red Army leaves. But
Najib and his Soviet allies believe the regime will survive.
   And the warring Afghan parties remain far apart over how to
govern their nation.
   The Soviet-Afghan communique urged formation of ``a coalition
government with the participation of all forces representing Afghan
society, including those who are currently opposed to one
another.'' And it urged a ``multi-party system,'' rather than
one-party rule patterned after the Soviet Union.
   The resistance has rejected Najib's calls for ``national
reconciliation.'' On Thursday, it announced the formation of a
government to rule over guerrilla-controlled territory and the head
of the resistance alliance, Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, said the
guerrillas ``will try to intensify'' the war.
   ``No doubt, when the Russians leave Afghanistan, Najib's regime
will collapse,'' he said. ``To avoid anarchy and possible armed
clashes to seize power, it's necessary that all parties agree to a
temporary government'' in those parts of Afghanistan under
guerrilla control.
   Not all the leaders of the seven-party resistance agreed that
formation of a guerrilla government was a good idea. Ahmad Gailani
of the moderate National Islamic Front of Afghanistan said it could
cut the nation in half.
   ``If there are two governments in Afghanistan, there is the
danger of partition into north and south or east and west, as with
North and South Korea, or East and West Germany,'' he said,
advocating a transitional government in exile until the pro-Kremlin
regime is overthrown.
   One congressional source who closely follows events in
Afghanistan reached a similar conclusion, based on the formation of
a new province in northern Afghanistan, where the Soviets have
taken steps to fortify natural gas fields.
   The guerrillas also are split over whether Afghanistan should
have an Islamic or secular government.
   Yunis Khalis of the hardline Hezb-i-Islami faction said that
``colonialist countries, the superpowers _ East or West, American
or Russian _ have joined hands to prevent the creation of a total
Islamic government in Afghanistan.''
   Soviet analysts believe the pro-Kremlin government has a good
chance of surviving. The U.S. embassy in Kabul sent a cable to
Washington last September advising the Soviets that Najib's 110,000
troops in the army, police and secret police might be strong enough
to resist the guerrillas.
   A leading Soviet expert on Afghanistan, Yuri Gankovsky, said in
a lecture in Washington on Wednesday that ``the regime of the
People's Democratic Party may survive.''
   ``It is impossible to predict the future of Najib'' and his
colleagues, Gankovsky said. ``Their life is in the hands of the
almighty.''
   And Vladimir Semyonov, in a commentary distributed by the
semi-official Soviet news agency Novosti, said that Gorbachev and
Najib concluded that ``the policy of reconciliation has found a
broad response in the opposition, including the armed opposition.''
   U.S. government analysts scoff at the notion that a pro-Soviet
government will survive the Red Army withdrawal.
   The Soviets have been handing out passes to government officials
for safe exit from the country, according to a New York-based
organization called Freedom House which has ties to the resistance.
Western intelligence in Kabul has also reported that lists are
being drawn up for possible evacuation.
   And one administration observer of Afghan events, asked why
Gorbachev found it necessary to hold a surprise meeting with Najib
in the Soviet Central Asian city of Tashkent, said ``Najib must
have been demanding a bigger dacha than he had been allotted on the
Black Sea.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bryan Brumley writes on national security issues
from Washington.
</TEXT>
