<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0564,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal Wins Showdown With Hezbollah, With 62 Killed In Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs UDPATE with German hostages freed. Pick
up 4th graf pvs: ``Diehard fighters...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem Amal
militia held control of south Lebanon today after a four-day battle
with Iranian-backed rivals, police said.
   The fighting killed 62 people and wounded 150, police reported.
   Two West German relief workers who were being held by Hezbollah
members in the basement of a mosque in the coastal town of Ghaziyeh
were freed when Amal militiamen overran the town.
   They had been abducted Thursday, but their disappearance had not
been reported. They were identified as Heinrich Strubig, 47, and
Petra Schnitzler, 24, of the Asme Humanitas organization.
   The mainstream Amal, led by Justice Minister Nabih Berri, held
all major towns and villages in the south and their supply routes,
police said. Amal is Syria's closest ally in Lebanon.
   Diehard fighters of the Iranian-backed fundamentalist Hezbollah,
or Party of God, were holed up in three hamlets west of the market
town of Nabatiyeh with Shiite mediators negotiating terms for their
surrender and safe conduct, police said.
   Amal's triumph reflected Syria's determination to crush a
growing challenge by Iran to its role as the main power broker in
Lebanon.
   Syria is Iran's main Arab ally in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf
war against Iraq.
   But it has been alarmed at Hezbollah's widening influence and
its efforts to seize control of Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites, the
country's largest sect.
   Police said that one of the hamlets where Hezbollah was still
holding out was Jibsheet, its main stronghold in the south.
Jibsheet is 15 miles southwest of the provincial capital of Sidon.
   Amal fighters surrounded it, along with neighboring Sharkieh and
Houmin al-Fouka, police said. Berri's fighters were expected to
occupy the villages once Hezbollah evacuated them.
   Friction between the secular leftist Amal and the fundamentalist
Hezbollah, which seeks to create an Iranian-style Islamic republic
in Lebanon, has sharpened since the kidnapping of U.S. Marine Lt.
Col. William R. Higgins.
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was kidnapped near the ancient
port of Tyre Feb. 17 while serving with a U.N. observer group in
south Lebanon.
   An underground Shiite extremist group calling itself the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth claimed responsibility.
   Amal accused Hezbollah of being behind the abduction and rounded
up several Hezbollah members it said were involved in the
kidnapping. But a major dragnet failed to locate Higgins or his
captors.
   Hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella for several Shiite
factions holding many of the other 21 foreigners missing in
Lebanon. Nine of the hostages are American.
</TEXT>
