<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Demjanjuk-Citizenship     04-08 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk-Citizenship,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys For Demjanjuk Seek To Have His Citizenship Restored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for John Demjanjuk filed court papers
today to have the retired autoworker's U.S. citizenship restored,
more than a week before a panel of Israeli judges is to announce
its verdict in Demjanjuk's yearlong war crimes trial.
   The papers also claim that the U.S. Justice Department
suppressed information from witnesses that would have helped
Demjanjuk substantiate his claim of mistaken identify.
   Demjanjuk was stripped of his citizenship in 1981, when a U.S.
District Court judge ruled that he lied on his immigration papers
to cover up his past. Demjanjuk, 68, was extradited to Israel more
than two years ago to stand trial. A three-judge panel heard
evidence about whether he was the death camp guard called Ivan the
Terrible, who ran the Treblinka gas chambers in Nazi-occupied
Poland in 1942 and 1943. An estimated 850,000 Jews were murdered at
Treblinka during the period.
   Demjanjuk, who lived in a Cleveland suburb, claims he is the
victim of mistaken identity. The Israeli judges are expected to
render a verdict April 18.
   In the documents, Demjanjuk's attorneys ask that the order
stripping him of his U.S. citizenship be overturned. Demjanjuk, a
Ukrainian, became a U.S. citizen in 1952.
   Demjanjuk has said he was drafted into the Soviet Army, captured
by the Germans and was a prisoner of war for the remainder of the
war.
   Ed Nishnic, Demjanjuk's son-in-law, said his family has
anonymously received documents belonging to the Justice
Department's Office of Special Investigations, which prosecuted
Demjanjuk's denaturalization trial.
   ``We've acquired documents through unknown sources that really
lay out, plain and clear, what OSI's intentions were from the
beginning. That they did not believe Mr. Demjanjuk was in fact Ivan
the Terrible and they went ahead and prosecuted him and suppressed
the evidence that would help him prove his case,'' Nishnic said
today outside the courthouse.
   The OSI materials were received in 1986 and 1987, according to
the court documents. The family claims there were many more
witnesses than represented by the United States and that those
witnesses likely to know Ivan the Terrible's identify could not
make an identification of Demjanjuk.
</TEXT>
