<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0561,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Announces Geneva Accord; Gorbachev Says Pullout to Begin May
15</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Gorbachev saying pullout not a
`present to Reagan;'' and details from radio report. PIcks up 5th
graf pvs, `Soviet troops...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev today confirmed
that Soviet troops will begin leaving Afghanistan on May 15 but
said it was not a present to President Reagan, Radio Moscow
reported.
   The broadcast said Gorbachev made the declaration during an
address to Communist Party officials in the Soviet city of
Tashkent, where he met Thursday with Afghan leader Najib.
   ``At the same time, the Soviet leader said the withdrawal of the
troops should not be regarded as a sort of present to President
Reagan on the eve of his visit to the USSR,'' Radio Moscow said.
   Reagan plans to visit Moscow from May 29 to June 2 for his
fourth summit with Gorbachev.
   Radio Moscow also broadcast the news that an agreement to end
the Afghan war had been completed in Geneva and was ready to be
signed.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez said in Geneva that a signing
ceremony is expected to take place Thursday.
   Gorbachev and Najib announced after their Taskkent meeting that
all obstacles to a peace agreement had been removed. Gorbachev said
then that the Soviet Union's troops could start leaving on May 15
if the Geneva accords were signed soon.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979. An estimated
115,000 are helping the Marxist government fight Moslem insurgents.
Pakistan has been representing the guerrillas at the Geneva talks.
   The official Tass news agency issued an urgent report shortly
after Cordovez' announcement that the Afghan and Pakistani
representatives had said they were prepared to sign the accord.
   Tass quoted Cordovez as saying the composition of the Afghan
leadership in Kabul was a matter to be determined by the Afghans
themselves.
   The Soviet Union and Afghanistan have objected repeatedly to
Pakistan's insistence that arrangements for a transitional
government in Afghanistan be worked out before a Geneva accord is
signed.
   An earlier Tass dispatch quoted Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul
Wakil and his Pakistani counterpart, Zain Noorani, as saying in
Geneva the accords were ready for signature.
   The major Soviet newspapers today carried pictures of Gorbachev
and Najib meeting in the Central Asian city of Tashkent, along with
a text of their joint statement.
</TEXT>
