<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz Bjt   04-08 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Ends Trip Without Middle East Breakthrough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Shultz arrival in Washington mid-evening EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
headed for home Friday without a breakthrough on Mideast peace
talks, but he vowed to find the time to try again ``and struggle
against the odds.''
   En route, Shultz made a surprise stop in Cyprus to make some
headway on a new power-sharing arrangement in battered Lebanon.
   A U.S. Army helicopter flew Lebanese President Amin Gemayal from
Beirut to meet with Shultz. A senior U.S. official said Gemayal was
willing to consider Syrian demands to dilute the powers of his
office, which traditionally is reserved for a Maronite Christian.
   Shultz worked out the terms with Syrian President Hafez Assad in
Damascus on Tuesday. The Syrian leader did not offer to withdraw
his army from Lebanon, but the United States is hoping that could
occur if the country, torn by civil war for 12 years, is stabilized.
   Shultz cautioned reporters in an airborne news conference not to
assume the surge of Lebanon diplomacy ``means some big new
development in Lebanon or on the hostages.''
   Nine Americans are being held hostage in Lebanon by groups that
U.S. terrorism experts believe are controlled by Iran.
   In acknowledging only ``inches'' of progress over six days in
the Middle East, Shultz did not assign blame to Israel or Jordan,
the key parties who did not accept his proposals. And he said he
was not discouraged.
   ``Whether you are discouraged or not has to do with your
expectations of what might happen,'' he said. ``If you have the
expectation everything all of a sudden is going to fall into place
you'd be discouraged, but I am not that naive to think the
difficult problems fall away.''
   In fact, Shultz said, ``I think we've probably gotten a little
further than I expected we might. So we'll keep at it. And I will
find time, as time goes along, to come back and work at it myself.''
   After several days of praising King Hussein of Jordan for taking
a ``constructive' approach to a U.S. plan for negotiations and
implying Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir had not, Shultz
said: ``The Israelis are as interested in peace and stability as
Jordan and the Palestinians, perhaps even more so.''
   He said both Shamir and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres had urged
him to keep at it, although Shamir still has ``reservations'' about
a Middle East peace conference.
   Shultz had hoped such a meeting could be called in mid-April,
but he acknowledged that obviously was now impossible. He said he
had not altered the ``time line'' of his proposal, however. It
calls for a conference attended by the United States, the Soviet
Union, China, Britain and France to launch negotiations shortly
afterward on Palestinian self-rule.
   The talks would be held between Israel and a mixed delegation of
Jordan and Palestinians, approved by the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   The self-rule would give Palestinians on the Israeli-held West
Bank and Gaza control over their daily lives, but not over security
or foreign affairs for three years. Meantime, wider negotiations on
an overall settlement of the Arab-Israeli dispute would begin seven
months after the opening of the first stage of the talks.
   ``There's a big need, and a very explosive kind of area,''
Shultz said of his determination to hold negotiations before the
Reagan administration leaves office next January. ``So it's worth
swimming upstream under the circumstances.''
   Earlier, at a news conference in Amman, Jordan, his last shuttle
stop, Shultz dismissed a reporter's suggestion his mission was
doomed to failure.
   ``Who's afraid to struggle against odds?,'' he said. ``You have
to be willing to do it. What am I saving myself for anyway?
   ``I've a few more months to go here and I want to try to leave
something constructive for the region and for my successors, so I
am going to put my back into it. Why not?''
</TEXT>
