<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StampSales     04-08 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stamp Sales,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stamp Sales Swamp Some Post Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortages of 3-cent stamps are being reported
at some post offices, but depleted inventories are being rapidly
refilled, the U.S. Postal Service reported Friday.
   ``The stamps are out there, but some offices have a lot more
than others,'' spokeswoman Tanya Perkins said.
   More than 1 billion 3-cent stamps were sent to local post
offices in preparation for the rate change, from 22 cents to 25
cents, last Sunday, Perkins said.
   And another 600 million of the 3-cent stamps are in warehouses,
being used to replenish stocks where needed, she said.
   ``We had asked local offices to predict how many they would
need, and some had a lot more demand than expected. We've been
filling orders all week,'' Perkins said.
   Sales of coils of 100 of the stamps have been especially heavy,
she said, rather than people buying just a few stamps to tide them
over.
   On the other hand, Perkins said plenty of the undenominated
``E'' stamps remain available. Some 6 billion E-stamps, which
represent the new 25-cent rate, have been shipped to post offices.
   Apparently, Perkins said, people are choosing to buy 3-cent
stamps in order to use up the 22-cent stamps they had on hand,
before buying the new higher rate stamps.
   Perkins said that the stamp shortages are scattered across the
country, rather than being confined to any particular area.
   Most offices also have 1-cent and 2-cent stanps available, she
added, and stamps can also be purchased by mail and telephone.
</TEXT>
