<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--BuriedAlive     04-08 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Buried Alive,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Co-workers Revive Man Buried in Sewer Cave-in</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Co-workers dug frantically with their
hands, helmets and shovels to save a man buried when underground
walls suddenly gave way, covering him with two tons of dirt,
officials said.
   Pete Schillaci, 33, was in fair condition Friday at Oregon
Health Sciences University Hospital.
   He had been hooking up an underground sewer line when the
accident occurred Thursday. He was underground for less than 20
minutes.
   ``Everything was looking good, and then with absolutely no
warning two tons ... came down on us,'' said Jerry Kuhn, himself
mired to the waist.
   Kuhn pulled himself from the hole and, together with backhoe
operator Paul Thompson, began scooping at the earth.
   After about four minutes, Kuhn said, they uncovered Schillaci's
face.
   The men followed procedures they had learned in a
cardiopulmonary resuscitation class at work. When emergency crews
arrived, Schillaci was turning blue from lack of oxygen and blood
was trickling from his mouth, said firefighter Brice Brinkhead.
</TEXT>
