<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalDeath     04-08 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Death,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Probe Continues Into Drug Error That Killed Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No punitive action was planned and no
charges were filed against a hospital where a man died after he was
injected with the wrong drug while undergoing kidney dialysis,
officials said.
   Angelo Carillo, 68, died Wednesday at Our Lady Of Lourdes
Medical Center in Camden. He and two other elderly patients went
into cardiac arrest after a technician accidentally injected them
Wednesday with the wrong drug, authorities said.
   Investigations by the state Department of Health and Camden
County Prosecutor Samuel Asbell show that a technician accidently
gave the patients an injection of the painkiller lidocaine instead
of mannitol, which regulates blood pressure.
   The other two patients, a man and a woman, were revived and were
in stable condition, hospital officials said.
   ``There's no criminality. It's a mistake. It's considered
accidental,'' George Kerns, a spokesman for Asbell's office, said
Thursday.
   State Department of Health spokeswoman Marilyn Riley said no
punitive action by the department was planned.
   She said an initial report by a team of nurses from the health
department said three certified kidney technicians working under a
supervising nurse were involved.
   She said a bottle of lidocaine was incorrectly placed on a shelf
where mannitol is stored. The technicians removed the lidocaine
from the shelf without looking at the label and injected the
patients, Ms. Riley said.
   Lidocaine is used in kidney dialysis as an anesthestic to numb
the area where a large needle is inserted, while mannitol is used
to stimulate kidney functions, Ms. Riley said.
   She said the kidney center staff has removed all lidocaine from
the dialysis area and will use a topical anesthetic in its place.
   Kidney dialysis machines purify a patient's blood if the kidneys
don't function. The center has given 300,000 treatments since
opening in 1969, officials said.
</TEXT>
