<1ST_LINE>u a PM-US-Panama     04-08 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Hints At New Sanctions Against Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff Howard
Baker today hinted the United States is preparing to announce new
economic sanctions against Panama to force the ouster of military
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Administration sources, requesting anonymity, said the most
likely prospect was that the administration would invoke an
emergency law to forbid American companies, subsidiaries and
individuals from paying taxes, fees or other payments to Panama.
   The United States has been trying to get American firms to
withhold the payments voluntarily.
   The law, known as the International Emergency Economic Powers
Authority, has been used before against other countries, including
Iran and Libya.
   Baker, briefing reporters at a seaside hotel during Reagan's
10-day vacation, said sanctions already imposed by the United
States have had a ``remarkable success'' as the United States tries
to convince Noriega that he should leave.
   ``What happens next is a matter that the president will address
and will address promptly, perhaps even today, on what other steps
are to be taken,'' Baker said.
</TEXT>
