<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--AIDS-Europe     04-08 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--AIDS-Europe,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European AIDS Cases Up 124 Percent In One Year, WHO Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of AIDS cases reported by European
countries to the World Health Organization more than doubled during
last year, the U.N. agency said Friday.
   The WHO weekly newsletter said 28 countries had reported 10,181
cases as of Dec. 31, 1987, representing a 124 percent increase from
the 4,549 cases reported a year earlier.
   The highest European per capita rate was registered in France,
with 55.3 cases per million population, followed by Switzerland
with 53.8 per million and Denmark with 44.7 per million. This
compares with a rate in the United States of 216 per million
population, WHO said.
   The Netherlands reported a rate of 28.8 cases per million
population, Belgium 28, and West Germany 27.4.
   Among the East bloc countries, Czechoslovakia and Hungary
reported the highest number of cases, eight each, for rates of 0.5
and 0.8 cases per million population, respectively, WHO said.
   East Germany reported six cases, and the Soviet Union and Poland
reported three cases each, it said.
</TEXT>
