<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissLawSchool     04-08 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss Law School,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Back Ousted Law School Professor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half the students at the University
of Mississippi law school want a faculty committee to reconsider
its recommendation the school dismiss its 1988 ``teacher of the
year'' co-winner.
   Students boycotted classes Thursday and have signed petitions in
support of Associate Professor Steve Thel.
   Thel ``is an outstanding professor,'' said Jack Williams, editor
of the Mississippi Law Journal on the Oxford campus.
   A committee of tenured law school faculty voted last month to
recommend administrators terminate Thel's contract, although he
will be allowed to finish the school year.
   The matter is pending before Dean Thomas Edmonds, who will make
his recommendation before forwarding the matter to Chancellor
Gerald Turner.
   The faculty committee's review of Thel's teaching, research and
productivity ``resulted in a vote not to continue his employment at
the unversity,'' Turner confirmed Wednesday.
   Thel, 34, a three-year university employee, declined to comment.
   At least 167 students _ about half the law school student body _
had signed a petition demanding Thel's contract be renewed, said
Williams, a third-year student from Amarillo, Texas.
   The petition claims tenured faculty members are playing politics
in their recommendation to terminate Thel's contract.
   ``We do not understand the logic behind ostracizing a professor
who has expressed a genuine concern for the academic development
and general welfare of the students,'' the petition said.
   Mike Leonard of Oxford, a first-year law student, said the
school's ``old guard'' doesn't like Thel. ``He's a Northerner, and
he's liberal,'' Leonard said. Turner denied that was a factor.
   Thel and Patricia Morgan were named ``teacher of the year'' in
student balloting last month.
   Edmonds, the law school dean, was out of town and unavailable
for comment on the student demands.
   Associate Dean Larry Bush said administrators canceled classes
for three hours Thursday because of a campus awards ceremony, ``so
it's difficult to tell how many didn't come to class.''
   Instructors at the school set their own policies on absenteeism,
he said.
   Officials said Thel is ineligible for tenure _ a guarantee of
job protection _ because he hasn't been at the university the
required six years.
</TEXT>
