<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Maneuvers,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots Warned Of Mock Military Air Battles Over Wisconsin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots have been warned to be
extraordinarily careful over parts of central Wisconsin this
weekend and next week because 400 to 500 military aircraft will be
taking part in eight days of mock air battles.
   ``Many of these are fighter aircraft, traveling at speeds up to
700 mph and flying as low as 100 feet off the ground. Needless to
say, non-military pilots would be wise to stay out of the area
completely,'' said John Dorcey, aviation safety manager for the
state Department of Transportation.
   The exercise beginning Saturday and running through April 16
will take place in an area bounded roughly by Eau Claire, Stevens
Point, Oshkosh, Wisconsin Dells and La Crosse.
   The exercise, called Sentry Independence, involves thousands of
participants from the Air National Guard, Air Force Reserve, the
active Air Force, Army National Guard, Army Reserve, Marine Corps
and the Navy Reserve.
   It's the fifth year of the exercise, but for the first time the
participants will include members of the German and Netherlands air
forces, Dorcey said.
