<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--DoubleTransplant     04-08 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Double Transplant,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Gives a Heart, Gets A Heart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Stanford University Medical Center
has performed a rare transplant operation in which a man gave his
heart to another and then received the heart and lungs of an
anonymous donor.
   The patients were doing well Thursday, said Vaughn Starnes,
chief of the center's heart-lung transplant program.
   In the ``domino'' operation April 1, John Hasenkamp received the
heart of Steve Rasmussen, who got a new heart and lungs.
   Starnes said Rasmussen, 28, of Santa Cruz, was near death from
lung disease but his heart was healthy. Hasenkamp, 48, of Redwood
City, had a damaged heart.
   The only other transplant of this kind on record was performed
last May at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, officials said.
   Both heart and lungs were transplanted into Rasmussen because
that method provides the necessary blood supply for healing, said
Starnes.
</TEXT>
