<HEAD>Working On New Album</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everybody wants to sing like Roy Orbison.
   Orbison, who made his fame decades ago with such hits as
``Pretty Woman'' and ``Only the Lonely,'' says he's found that
while working with some of today's top recording artists.
   ``With some of the people, because of who they are, I expect
that we'll be writing a rock 'n' roll tune. And it turns out that
they have more of a Roy Orbison-type ballad in mind,'' he said in a
recent interview.
   ``Lately, though, we're just writing songs, which I prefer _ not
trying to imitate anything in particular from the past. And nobody
dominates the writing sessions, it's just whichever of us has the
hot idea at the moment.''
   Earlier this week Orbison, Tom Petty and Jeff Lynne worked on a
new album he expects to have out later this year.
   ``We just finished one tune and hope to finish another. I have
enough material for an album already, but I'd like to get three or
four more. That shouldn't be a problem.''
   Probably not for the man whose been a perennial favorite for
three decades with such hits as ``Crying,'' ``Running Scared,''
``It's Over'' and ``Leah.''
