<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Protest     04-08 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Protest,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Disperse Anti-Bases Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today dispersed about 800
demonstrators who tried to rally in front of the U.S. Embassy
calling for the dismantling of American military bases in the
country.
   Police said at least 20 police officers suffered minor injuries.
Three demonstrators were arrested, they said.
   The demonstrators were negotiating with police officials late in
the afternoon when a group of protesters dashed across the street
towards the embassy.
   The police gave chase, using riot clubs, while another group
succeeded in going to the side of the embassy. Other demonstrators
hurled stones at the riot police.
   A fire truck opened their water cannons against the
demonstrators who scurried into sidestreets fronting the U.S.
embassy.
   Earlier, the demonstrators were chanting ``dismantle the U.S.
bases'' and ``down with imperialists'' as they arrived near the
embassy from a downtown plaza.
   Police Col. Conrado Francisco said at least 20 policemen
suffered stoning and clubbing injuries.
   A rally official who spoke on condition of anonymity said they
had no figures on how many demonstrators were injured but said two
leaders were apprehended by police.
   Police could not immediately confirm the arrest of the two
officials but said they arrested three other demonstrators.
   The United States and the Philippines began talks last Tuesday
on the status of American military bases here. The outcome of the
talks, expected to last three months, will determine whether the
government allows the bases to remain after their lease expires in
1991.
   The six U.S. bases are the largest American installations left
in Southeast Asia.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt, head of the American negotiating
panel, says the installations are essential to protect the region
from Soviet expansion.
</TEXT>
