<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Doctrine     04-08 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Doctrine,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Denounces Abuses, Seeks Settlement with Rebel Bishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Friday condemned
doctrinal and liturgical abuses in the Roman Catholic church and
said he still hopes for a settlement with rebel French Archbishop
Marcel Lefebvre.
   ``The need to distinguish from what authentically builds up the
church from what destroys her is becoming in the present period a
particular demand of our service to the whole community of
believers,'' the pope wrote Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the
Vatican's powerful guardian of church orthodoxy.
   Ratzinger's Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith has
worked toward reaching a settlement with Lefebvre, who heads the
traditionalist Pius X Fraternity, based in Switzerland.
   Lefebvre was suspended from his priestly functions by Pope Paul
VI in 1976, meaning he is not allowed by the Vatican to say Mass or
give the sacraments.
   He continues to celebrate the forbidden 16th century Latin
Tridentine Mass and claims to have millions of followers worldwide.
   In October, the pope charged Cardinal Edouard Gagnon with the
task of trying to resolve the Lefebvre case.
   Lefebvre has ordained illegally more than 200 priests in the
past 15 years. In February, he was quoted in an interview with the
French newspaper Le Figaro as saying he planned to consecrate three
bishops this June, a move that would lead to his automatic
excommunication.
   ``Your Eminence knows very well how many efforts have been made
by the Apostolic See since the beginning of the existence of the
`fraternity,' in order to ensure ecclesial unity in relation to its
activity,'' the pope wrote Ratzinger in a letter released by the
Vatican.
   ``I would assure your eminence once more of my desire that these
efforts should continue. We do not cease to hope that ... they will
bear fruit,'' the pope wrote.
   Also referring to Lefebvre, the pope wrote: ``All the bishops of
the Catholic Church ... are bound to collaborate with the Apostolic
See for the welfare of the whole mystical body, which is also the
body of the churches.''
   In his letter, the pope said the church was striving to ensure
that the doctrine of the 1962-65 Second Vatican Council was being
followed.
   ``However, side by side with this effort there have appeared
tendencies which create a certain difficulty in putting the council
into practice,'' the letter said. ``One of these tendencies is
characterized by a desire for changes which are not always in
harmony with the teaching and spirit of Vatican Council II.''
   ``These changes claim to express progress,'' the letter
continued, ``and so this tendency is given the name
`progressivism.' In this case, progress consists in an aspiration
towards the future which breaks with the past, without taking into
account the function of tradition, which is fundamental to the
church's mission.''
   The pope also denounced what he described as the opposite
tendency of ``conservatism'' or ``integrism.'' This tendency
``stops at the past itself, without taking into account the correct
aspiration towards the future,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
