<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0637 04-08 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0637,900</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf pvs to include tax comparison; inserts 1 graf
after 7th graf pvs, White House, with charitable contributions.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and his wife,
Nancy, had an adjusted gross income of $345,359 in 1987 with a
federal tax liability of $86,638, according to tax returns released
today.
   That income was $8,990 above what the Reagans reported for 1986,
while their tax bill rose $5,822. Taxes as a percentage of the
Reagans' gross income rose from 25.1 percent to 27.5 percent.
   The couple had $67,392 withheld for federal income taxes last
year and paid an additional $30,000 in quarterly payments, for a
total of $97,392.
   That means they paid $10,754 above what they owed the
government. Rather than getting a refund, the couple elected to
apply that amount to their 1988 taxes.
   Included in the gross income was the president's $200,000
salary, $54,179 in interest income, $46,208 in capital gains and
$29,711 in income from his pension for serving as governor of
California from 1967-75.
   The income also included $1,526 in appearance fees paid to the
president and Mrs. Reagan. This included $1,312 paid to Reagan for
his appearance on NBC-TV's ``Tonight'' show and $214 paid to Mrs.
Reagan in residual talent fees for re-runs of two programs in which
she had appeared in 1986.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the $1,312 fee paid
to the president was ``required to be paid ... under union
agreements'' in the television industry, and said that the $1,312
was donated along with other money to his alma matter, Eureka
College in Illionois.
   Charitable deductions totaled $25,407.
   After deductions, the Reagans' total taxable income was $263,767.
   The tax returns were released a day after White House chief of
staff Howard Baker said that Reagan and his wife had made sure
``all of the i's were dotted and the t's were crossed'' before
leasing a $2.5 million Los Angeles home purchased by friends.
   But questions about the arrangements the Reagans made with the
consortium that purchased the home persist. These involve the
secrecy surrounding the identities of the 18 to 20 Reagan friends
who purchased the home, and the question of why the Reagans decided
to lease, rather than buy, the house.
   The Reagans consider the home-leasing arrangement a private
matter, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater has said. And on
Thursday, Baker said the pair ``may not like'' all the press
scrutiny surrounding the deal.
   In Washington, Donald Campbell, the deputy director of the
Office of Government Ethics, confirmed that lawyers representing
the consortium approached the agency in July 1986, and ``we did
make an analysis'' of the proposition at the time.
   Campbell said the office produced an informal opinion on the
ethical ramifications of the deal.
   The White House, which has made only a limited disclosure of the
terms of the three-year lease the Reagans signed effective March 1,
said that before buying the three-bedroom, six-bath house, the
prospective owners, most of them friends of the Reagans, sought an
opinion on the propriety of the deal.
   It said the opinion concluded that the Reagans would comply with
standards of conduct regulations and conflict of interest statutes
if they paid a fair-market rental or purchase price.
   It said the lease terms were negotiated by representatives of
the owners and the Reagans, based on fair-market value rental
estimates from two independent appraisers.
   The home, on a 1\-acre property in the poshest section of Bel
Air, is near the Kirkeby estate where the television series
``Beverly Hillbillies'' was filmed. It has a heated swimming pool
and a three-car garage.
   Real estate sources estimate the monthly rent at $12,000 to
$15,000, based on fair-market value.
   The Reagans are known to feel strongly about their privacy, and
the first lady during the early years of the administration made it
clear she wanted information about the president's health handled
carefully by the White House press office. And the first couple has
chafed over past reporting of difficulties involving Reagan
children and relatives.
   On Thursday, Baker was asked if the president and his wife were
upset by the spate of media reports on the home-leasing deal.
   ``Oh, I don't think so,'' said Baker, standing outside a seaside
resort hotel cottage not far from Reagan's mountaintop ranch. ``I
think after eight years, they've come to understand that that
occurs, and while they understand it, they may not like it, but
they are not angry about it.
   ``The White House, the president and the first lady went to
great lengths to make sure that this was an arms-length
transaction, that there was a full appraisal of the rental property
and that all of the i's were dotted and the t's were crossed,'' he
said.
   Baker said that Reagan and his wife have handled the leasing of
the home ``in precisely the right way and really beyond legitimate
criticism.''
   The property was purchased in August 1986 by the consortium,
which has incorporated itself as Wall Management Services, Inc.
   Realtor Jeff Hyland of the Los Angeles firm of Alvarez, Hyland &
Young, said that with rising prices since the purchase, the land
alone is worth $3 million.
   ``They got a great buy,'' he said. ``They bought it for land
value. As far as I am concerned, they got the house for free.''
   Realtor John Aaroe of the Jon Douglas Co. said the house, built
in 1954, still has the original kitchen and needs a great deal of
renovation.
</TEXT>
