<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MagazineCensored     04-08 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Magazine Censored,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Officials Cite Offensive Language In Removing Article</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An award-winning play about a student's suicide
has been deleted from a San Jacinto College literary magazine
because the school chancellor believes the play's language is too
offensive.
   ``It's an excellent play. Good work. But I had a real problem
with the harsh language. I'm the publisher and it's sold to
students and the community we serve,'' Chancellor Tom Sewell said.
   As a result Robert Earl Milstid's play ``Just A Phase,'' about a
17-year-old student whose social and domestic woes drive him to a
beer-soaked suicide, has been dumped from next week's issue of The
Prism.
   ``I'm not a member of the Moral Majority or anything, but it's
not appropriate for the public we send it to,'' Sewell said.
   The one-act play drew big crowds last year during three
performances, received good reviews in the campus newspaper and in
December earned the author an Excellence in Play Writing honor for
originality at the American College Theater Festival in Denton.
   Sewell said he would have considered barring the campus
production had he known about its content beforehand.
   Milstid, 24, said he used cursing in his play for realism, not
for shock.
   ``It's sad that one person in a high position has a right to
dictate his opinions to college students about what we can and
can't read,'' Milstid said. ``But I understand where he's coming
from. I'm used to dealing with overly conservative viewpoints.''
</TEXT>
