<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     04-08 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jakes Accuses West of Slander and Creating Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Milos Jakes
on Friday launched a stern attack on the Western media, accusing
them of creating unrest in Czechoslovakia.
   Addressing a two-day meeting of the party's Central Committee,
Jakes also announced plans to speed up some of the modest economic
reforms the conservative Prague leadership has adopted to try to
stimulate the economy.
   He also said there would be a limit of two five-year terms for
the party leader and three successive terms for regional party
officials.
   In addition, Jakes said, party officials should not accumulate
too many functions and should be elected by secret ballot.
   He stressed, however, that the Communist Party must retain its
powerful role as the leading force of Czechoslovak society, saying
that the party must strengthen its ``influence on what is happening
in society.''
   ``In no case can party work be narrowed to mere educational
activity,'' he stressed.
   In his 57-page speech, published by the state news agency CTK,
Jakes accused unidentified ``hostile propaganda'' abroad of
preparing ``a slanderous campaign'' connected to the 20th
anniversary of the failed Prague Spring reforms of former Communist
party leader Alexander Dubcek.
   He also accused unidentified Western media of fomenting unrest,
particularly among religious believers, who have recently staged
two unusual demonstrations calling for religious freedom.
   Almost 500,000 Roman Catholics have signed an unprecedented
petition for more freedom to practice religion.
   ``Recently, we have been witnessing how anti-Communist forces
try, with the assistance of some Western media, directly to
organize the creation of opposition groups, incite them toward
actions which are to create unrest and tension in our society and
even hide this behind religious motivation,'' Jakes said.
   ``We have to reject these efforts resolutely,'' he added. ``In
our state, all believers can enjoy religious freedoms ... and take
part in religious life and rites.''
   ``Do not let us overrate or underrate the endeavors of the
enemies,'' Jakes went on. ``We have considered this in the
(Politburo) ... we shall not permit anybody to parasite on the
process of restructuring and democratization.
   ``The laws of the state are valid for all and those who violate
them must count on legal consequences.''
   Jakes' words signaled that opposition groups will not be
included in any immediate dialogue with the Communist authorities,
as has been hinted at in Poland, Hungary and the Soviet Union.
   Turning to the economy, Jakes noted that performance had
improved in the first quarter of this year, but that almost one in
five state-run enterprises is performing below target.
   He said a new law on enterprises which decentralizes their
management will come into force July 1 this year, and not next
January as originally announced, and also spoke vaguely of plans to
trim the central bureaucracy.
   Later this month, according to informed sources, parliament will
approve the merger of four technical ministries into a ``super
ministry'' of engineering, headed by 51-year-old technocrat
Ladislav Gerle.
   Social welfare and health ministries, transport and
communications ministries and the ministries running agriculture,
water and forestry are also likely to be merged.
   It is estimated that 30,000 to 50,000 bureaucrats will lose
their jobs.
</TEXT>
