<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietFire     04-08 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Fire,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents of Leningrad Helped Dry Books After Disastrous Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Leningrad helped dry books in
their homes after a fire at the Leningrad library founded by Peter
the Great, according to an expert helping the Soviets cope with the
disaster.
   ``This was the biggest disaster in modern history to a
library,'' Sally Buchanan said Friday. ``This material was valuable
to not only Soviet scholars, but scholars from all over the world.''
   The Feb. 14 fire damaged or destroyed an estimated 4 million
books at the U.S.S.R. National Academy of Sciences, founded in
1714, said Ms. Buchanan, one of three U.S. experts who helped the
Soviets begin restoration.
   Many books suffered water damage, and the library called on
residents for help, handing out wet books with instructions for
drying them, Ms. Buchanan said. Not one was stolen, she said.
   ``Many of these books were rare books and they all came back
beautifully dried,'' she said. ``They ended up drying something
like half a million books.''
   The Soviet Union's state cultural fund chairman, Dmitri
Likhachev, has accused Communist Party officials of trying to
conceal the extent of the damage and of using bulldozers to clear
away piles of damaged books.
   Library officials in Leningrad have said those charges are
false, and Ms. Buchanan said she ``saw no indication that the
library had tried to cover up the fire. The library was very candid
about what the losses were.''
   Ms. Buchanan, assistant director of preservation at the
University of Pittsburgh's Hillman Library, said flames destroyed
an estimated 400,000 books and damaged 3.6 million more, including
17th-century scientific collections, Ms. Buchanan said.
   Soviet librarians are still assessing the damage and exact
losses won't be known for at least another month, Ms. Buchanan
said, but some of the burned books, particularly those concerning
science history, were probably the only ones in existence.
   The library, in a 1920s building, contained more than 12 million
books, manuscripts and periodicals.
   ``The only way this library is going to recover from this is
with help from the international library community to replace the
materials that have been lost,'' she said.
   Ms. Buchanan has led restoration efforts in several library
disasters, including a fire at a Los Angeles library two years ago.
She and the other two U.S. experts have been invited to return to
Leningrad within the next year.
</TEXT>
