<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key lime pie may well join the porpoise
and the largemouth bass on the somewhat lengthy list of what the
Legislature considers official.
   At the suggestion of a constituent, state Rep. Norman Ostrau is
planning to sponsor a bill for an official state pie.
   ``It encompasses everything that's Florida,'' said Bob Roth, who
proposed the bill to Ostrau. Roth's wife, Terry, makes the tart pie
as part of the family's citrus business in Davie.
   Key limes, small and yellowish, are indigenous to south Florida,
but the pies also are made with the more familiar dark green
varities.
   Previous legislatures have designated the porpoise the state
mammal and the manatee as its marine mammal. The largemouth bass is
the state freshwater fish and the sailfish its saltwater fish.
Agatized coral is the state stone, and ``The Cross and Sword,''
which tells the story of the Spanish colonization of St. Augustine,
is the official state play.
   To date, orange juice _ the official state beverage _ is the
only food item on the list.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pheasant egg hunt for Chinese children is being
planned by biologists from Michigan's Department of Natural
Resources.
   They hope to retrieve eggs from China's Szechwan province to
bolster and perhaps supplant the state's ringneck pheasant
population, which has declined drastically the past two decades.
   Biologists think the Szechwan pheasants are better adapted to
survival on the brushy, rural terrain of southern Michigan.
   ``The children are looking for them anyway, because they eat
them, or feed them to their dogs or sometimes just smash the eggs
and nests, because they don't like pheasants because they eat their
crops,'' said DNR biologist Peter Squibb, head of the program to
rebuild the pheasant flock.
   The children will be paid about 25 cents for each egg. DNR
officials hope to return with 2,000 eggs, half of which are
expected to hatch successfully and lead to a population of 2
million to 3 million birds in the 1990s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor was last seen saying, ``This
state needs a new constitution,'' before the lights went out.
   But Gov. Ray Mabus didn't let the power failure wipe out his
town meeting Thursday night with more than 200 residents.
Illuminated by flashlights and without a microphone, Mabus
continued the meeting in the dark until power was restored about 25
minutes later.
