<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Grandmother'sCompassion     04-08 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grandmother's Compassion,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Seeks 2nd Chance For Her Kidnappers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the urging of a kidnap victim, a
judge has sentenced the two men who pleaded guilty to the abduction
to prisons where they can get help with their crack cocaine
addictions.
   Annie V. Brown, 53, was kidnapped March 3 by two men who bound
her with electrical cord and gagged her with a sock, then forced
her into the trunk of her car while they drove around for three
hours.
   After she was let out, she grabbed a gun that had been concealed
in the car and held one of them until police arrived.
   ``The thing that amazed me about her was that she still had
compassion for these people. You'd think that somebody tied up in
the trunk for three hours would have wanted them sentenced to as
long as she could,'' Assistant State Attorney Refik Eler said.
``She seemed to feel it was more important that they be helped. A
lot of victims that I see will just say `Fry 'em.'''
   He noted that her compassion is even more remarkable since her
daughter was murdered in 1980, leaving her to raise her
grandchildren.
   ``I feel compassion for them because they're young men,'' Mrs.
Brown said Thursday after sentencing.
   Samuel Alexander, 21, and Donald G. Alexander, 24, not related,
admitted Thursday that they kidnapped Mrs. Brown.
   Mrs. Brown asked Circuit Judge Hudson R. Olliff to give them a
second chance and urged that they be sent to a prison where they
could rehabilitate themselves.
   Each could have received up to nine years, but Olliff imposed
less-than-maximum terms.
   In addition to the kidnapping, Samuel Alexander also pleaded
guilty to a charge of grand theft for stealing Mrs. Brown's car. He
was given six years in prison. Donald Alexander pleaded guilty to
an additional charge of armed robbery and was sentenced to 5{ years.
   Olliff said he will ask that Samuel Alexander be placed in a
youthful offender facility where he can learn a trade. Officials
will be asked to place Donald Alexander, a former University of
Florida student and Army veteran, in a prison where he can get drug
counseling.
   The two men visited Mrs. Brown on March 3 and Donald Alexander,
a friend of two of Mrs. Brown's children, asked her to write a
letter of reference for him to get a job.
   When she turned to go into her house, she was grabbed by Donald
Alexander, who demanded all her money. At the same time, Samuel
Alexander tied her hands.
   ``At this time, I was sure they were going to kill me,'' said
Mrs. Brown, who told the men where she had $20 hidden. They got the
money, then took her out to her car and put her in the trunk.
   The men finally stopped, and Donald Alexander opened the trunk
and said he would free her if she would write him a check.
   ``I said `You have to give me the keys so I can get a pen out of
the glove compartment,''' Mrs. Brown said. While she opened the
glove compartment, she grabbed a .22-caliber pistol she kept hidden
under the front seat.
   She held Donald Alexander at gunpoint until police arrived.
Samuel Alexander fled but turned himself in the next day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
