<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FirstCitizen Bjt   04-08 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First Citizen, Bjt,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>97-Year-Old Alien Is First Amnesty Applicant To Obtain Citizenship</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 98-year-old woman who moved to the
United States in 1927 on Friday became the first person to gain
citizenship under the amnesty program allowing aliens to legalize
their status.
   ``It seems like it is not true,'' Clara Escobedo de Martinez
said in Spanish after the ceremony. ``It is so big, it seems like a
fairy tale.''
   The widow and great-grandmother sat in a chair, raised her hand
and took the oath of allegiance to the United States in Spanish
from U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela.
   ``What you're doing today, Dona Clarita, very much is a heroic
event,'' said Vela.
   A case of overnight nerves sapped some of her strength, Mrs.
Escobedo said. But after it was over she felt strong enough to wave
a flag provided by the local chapter of the Daughters of the
American Revolution.
   A cake inscribed ``Congratulations Citizen Clara'' and a special
luncheon held by the Immigration and Naturalization Service awaited
her at the Fort Brown Motor Hotel about a quarter-mile from the
Mexican border.
   INS district director Jerry Sewell said the reception was his
agency's way of thanking Mrs. Escobedo for being a public relations
agent for the one-year amnesty program ending May 4.
   Mrs. Escobedo appeared on parade floats and television
commercials and helped motivate other aliens to apply under the
Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986 offering legal residency
and ultimately citizenship to those able to prove they have lived
here illegally since before 1982.
   ``She is the first person in the United States who applied for
amnesty to become a citizen,'' Sewell said.
   She is not the oldest person to apply for amnesty under the
program; that distinction apparently goes to Carlos Romero-Gaitan
of Los Angeles, a 101-year-old Mexican who was smuggled into the
country in the back seat of his son's car 14 years ago.
   Joining Mrs. Escobedo in becoming citizens Friday were a
74-year-old daughter, Consuelo Martinez Zarate, and two
granddaughters, 47-year-old Rakel Zarate and 44-year-old Genoveva
Zarate de Sanchez.
   ``It has given me new dimensions of my love for this country,''
said Rakel Zarate.
   Mrs. Escobedo, who said her husband was killed by Pancho Villa's
men during the Mexican revolution, lived in the United States
legally from 1927 until 1962.
   But in a bureaucratic mix-up, immigration officials took away
her ``green'' card _ which is now blue and shows legal residency
status _ because they thought she had been living in Matamoros,
Mexico, in violation of the card's terms.
   She has lived as an undocumented alien with relatives in
Brownsville since 1979.
   Officials gave her a new green card in February and were able to
waive the normal five-year wait for citizenship because she
satisfied that requirement 56 years ago, in 1932, said Sewell.
   Otherwise she would have had to wait until 1994, when she would
have been 104.
   Mrs. Escobedo said she had always planned to become a citizen
during her first 35 years in this country, but kept putting it off.
   She never learned to speak English, but the requirement does not
apply to applicants over age 50 with more than 20 years of U.S.
residency.
   She learned how to say at least one English word on Friday.
   ``Citifen? Citipen?'' Mrs. Escobedo said haltingly under her
daughter's coaching.
   ``I am American citizen,'' she finally said, with a broad smile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   04-08 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Complete on Ending Afghan Civil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations on an Afghanistan settlement were
completed Friday, allowing the Soviet Union to pull out of a war
with Moslem guerrillas to which it had committed a force of 115,000
soldiers.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez said he expects the five-point
peace plan to be signed by next Thursday. The signing will end
nearly six years of indirect talks in which he was the go-between
for Afghanistan and its eastern neighbor, Pakistan.
   A U.N. spokeswoman, Therese Gastaut, said the date of the
signing ceremony will be announced Monday.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev confirmed that Soviet troops
will begin leaving on May 15, but added the withdrawal is not ``a
present to President Reagan.'' The two begin their fourth summit
May 29 in Moscow.
   Although Cordovez has a mandate from all sides to promote
dialogue within Communist-ruled Afghanistan, there is no guarantee
the 10-year-old war will stop.
   The U.S.-supported insurgent alliance was not included in the
negotiations and issued a statement Friday saying its fighters
``will not be bound by the outcome of the Geneva agreements and
they will continue the war as long as the Russians and their
puppets are present in Afghanistan.''
   In a statement approved by all sides, Cordovez stressed that
``any questions relating to the government in Afghanistan'' are an
internal matter.
   ``We have discussed, we have negotiated. That's over,'' he told
reporters. ``The documents are now finalized and open for
signature.''
   He called the settlement a ``historic opportunity'' for
Afghanistan.
   Agreement became possible after what diplomatic sources said was
a secret understanding that Washington will phase out aid to the
guerrillas while Moscuw cuts off military support to Kabul.
   Cordovez said all parties are ready to sign, including the
Soviet Union and United States as guarantors, after a final round
of negotiations that lasted more than five weeks.
   The agreement covers Afghan and Pakistani assurances of
non-interference in each other's affairs, safe and voluntary return
of Afghan refugees, and superpower guarantees. A fourth part ties
the others together and Cordovez said a memorandum of understanding
was added on the U.N. role in supervising the agreement.
   Texts are to be published later.
   Moslem insurgents began fighting after a Communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December
1979.
   Pakistan represented the guerrillas in Geneva and delivers
supplies to them, including highly effective U.S. Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles. About 3.5 million Afghan refugees live in
Pakistan, most in border cities and camps that serve as bases and
supply points for the insurgents.
   The United States had said it would not sign the U.N. accord
until the Soviets agreed to ``symmetry'' _ a simultaneous end to
military aid on both sides.
   Diplomatic sources called the informal agreement on ending
outside aid a face-saving solution for both sides. Cordovez said it
was not part of the U.N. settlement.
   A senior U.S. diplomat in Moscow said the deal was made through
behind-the-scenes diplomacy.
   In a clear allusion to the question of outside military aid,
Cordovez said he was convinced all parties ``will exercise
restraint in taking any actions'' that might violate the letter and
spirit of the accord.
   ``The agreement is designed to bring peace to Afghanistan and
the conditions for such a peace would not be obtained if actions
are taken which would fuel hostilities,'' he said.
   Intense Soviet diplomatic activity this week preceded the
agreement.
   Gorbachev met Najib, the Afghan leader, in the Soviet Central
Asian city of Tashkent earlier this week and they issued a joint
statement Thursday saying all issues had been resolved.
   Yuli Vorontsov, deputy Soviet foreign minister, flew to Geneva
to meet the Afghan foreign minister, Abdul Wakil, apparently
because Afghanistan had been holding out over a border dispute with
Pakistan.
   The dispute, dating to 1893, had provoked arguments over the
U.N. settlement's reference to boundaries. A source close to the
talks said it was resolved on Friday.
   Early last month, Afghanistan and Pakistan agreed on completion
of the Soviet troop pullout in nine months, with half leaving in
the first three months. The timetable had been a major sticking
point.
</TEXT>
