<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BankError     04-08 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Error,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$121 Grocery Trip Turns Into $80 Million Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No matter how many steaks Carol Armstrong
placed in her shopping cart, her husband knew the grocery trip did
not cost what their bank said she spent _ $80 million.
   ``I was a little surprised. I knew it was a mistake,'' Richard
Armstrong, 41, said Friday.
   An shopping trip March 23 to a supermarket cost $121.78, which
Mrs. Armstrong paid with an automated teller card from Wells Fargo
Bank. But a bank error added $80 million more.
   Armstrong, an electronics technician, said he realized something
was wrong several days later when he couldn't withdraw money from
their account. He tried unsuccessfully several times, then called
up his balance on the machine.
   ``This huge number with a minus sign comes spilling out,''
Armstrong said.
   Since the automated teller only goes up to $1 million, the
machine showed his account overdrawn for that amount.
   Despite this shock, Armstrong wanted to buy some flags and went
to a flag store. ``I said, `I think I'm a million dollars short, so
can I write a check?'''
   Since the owner knew him, Armstrong was allowed to write a check.
   He then called his bank, which, he said, insisted the Armstrongs
had mistakenly written a check for $80 million. He noted, however,
that $80,000,121.78 had been deducted from their account and
finally deduced that the mistake stemmed from the check for
groceries.
   Still, Armstrong was left without money over Easter weekend.
   ``I had to rob my kid's piggy banks,'' he said.
   Wells Fargo corrected the Armstrongs' balance Tuesday. A bank
spokeswoman said it was a clerical error.
</TEXT>
