<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     04-08 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: ``I'd Wage A Real War, Not A Phony War, On Drugs''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tough stand on drugs was the main
theme Friday as Michael Dukakis, his presidential hopes buoyed by a
new poll, campaigned in the Long Island suburbs of New York City.
   Asked at a senior citizens forum what he would do to protect the
elderly from criminals, the Massachusetts governor quickly turned
his answer to drugs. ``I'd wage a real war, not a phony war, on
drugs,'' he said, drawing loud applause. ``We've got to get tough
on the flow of drugs into this country.''
   An earlier speech at St. John's University, billed as a major
foreign policy address, also emphasized the need to deal with drug
trafficking.
   ``In Latin America, the gravest threat to our security comes not
from the Sandinistas, but from drugs,'' he said.
   In the three-way Democratic race for the 255 delegates at stake
in the New York primary on April 19, Dukakis held a growing lead in
a new poll by the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion.
   The survey of 404 likely Democratic voters found 47 percent
naming Dukakis as their presidential choice, while 31 percent
picked Jesse Jackson and 6 percent Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee.
   The interviews were conducted Tuesday and Wednesday and the poll
had a margin of error of 5 percent, meaning the figures could be
off by 5 points up or down.
   A Marist poll taken less than a month ago reported Dukakis was
the choice of 37 percent of likely Democratic primary voters while
Jackson had 28 percent.
   At the senior citizens forum held at Adelphi University, Dukakis
said he was opposed to means testing for Social Security and said
that two-thirds of the people receiving the federal retirement
benefits had no other income.
   At St. John's, Dukakis advocated using a portion of foreign aid
for drug enforcement programs in producing countries.
   He also criticized the Reagan administration's ties to Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega of Panama.
   ``The American people deserve a full explanation of what and why
we were doing business with Noriega,'' he said.
   On the Persian Gulf, Dukakis said the United States should
``challenge China and the Soviet Union to join the agreement
recently signed by Japan and the Western powers to stop the sale of
long-range missiles to all countries in the Middle East.''
   He said the United States also ``must enlist every nation we can
in the effort to ban poison gas, something that is being used right
now, right now, and to impose tough sanctions against any country
dumb enough and savage enough to use these weapons against their
fellow human beings.''
</TEXT>
