<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marines-Panama     04-08 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marines-Panama,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Leave For Jungle Exercises In Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN CALLISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL TORO MARINE AIR STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clutching sack lunches
along with their rifles and machine guns, 290 Marines boarded giant
cargo jets and flew to Panama on Friday for jungle training
exercises.
   The Marines joked among themselves, listened to a Dixieland jazz
band and waved to Mom as they passed in front of television cameras
before boarding two C-141 jets that took off before noon.
   ``I'm just going down to get a suntan,'' said Cpl. Mark
Stelluto, 21, a radio operator from Fullerton. ``We have been told
to be on our best demeanor.''
   The Marines, dressed in camouflage and carrying M-16 rifles,
M-60 machine guns and other weapons, are members of the 2nd
Battalion, 9th Marine Regiment, and the 1st Battalion, 5th Marine
Regiment, based at Camp Pendleton, 60 miles north of San Diego.
   The exercise is unrelated to a U.S. military buildup prompted by
Panama's current political turmoil, said Lt. Gene Browne, a Camp
Pendleton spokesman. Five hundred more Marines leave next week for
the training, he said.
   The last of 1,300 other U.S. troops arrived Thursday at Howard
Air Force Base outside Panama City, completing a buildup meant to
provide greater security for the Panama Canal, American
installations and U.S. citizens.
   ``This whole thing for us is purely coincidental,'' said Browne.
``This particular training evolution has been scheduled since
December.''
   ``We don't have jungles in Southern California and they do down
there at the Army school so we go there to train,'' he said.
   The government-controlled press in Panama contends the Marines'
arrival is a step toward a U.S. invasion aimed at ousting Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega, head of the 15,000-member Panamanian Defense forces,
refused to step down when fired by the country's civilian
president, who then went into hiding. Noriega has been indicted in
the United States on drug charges, and the Reagan administration
has been trying to oust him with economic pressure.
   The arrival of the 800 Marines will bring to more than 12,000
the number of U.S. military personnel in the Central American
country.
   The Marines leaving Friday range in age from 18 to 45, and while
few have combat experience, executive officer Brad Stephan said
they were prepared to fight if necessary.
   Said Lance Cpl. Rodolfo Gonzalez, 21: ``I'm looking forward to
it. I've never been down there.'' He said his biggest worry was
getting sick from the food.
   Nicaraugan-born Juan Chamorro dropped one of his weapons as he
boarded the plane. His penalty, several push-ups, was imposed
immediately; he did the exercises with his feet on the boarding
ramp and his hands on the ground.
   When asked if he was nervous, Stelluto said: ``No. It will be
hard enough just to deal with the insects and frogs and the things
in the jungle like that as it is.''
</TEXT>
