<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     04-08 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Democrats Will Get Act Together Before Fall Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush looked ahead
to the fall presidential campaign on Friday and said he didn't
expect the Democrats ``to hemorrhage to death'' despite their
hard-fought campaign.
   Bush, on his first political trip since Bob Dole quit the race
and Pat Robertson scaled back his effort, was asked by reporters if
he minded not having the discipline of a primary race.
   ``I'm delighted it's worked out the way it has. You offset
staying in the news through combat by the luxury that comes with
having the time to deal with issues. I wouldn't trade, let's put it
that way,'' he said.
   ``I wish I thought the Democrats would have a unity problem but
I don't think they will. I'm not counting on the blood on the floor
that exists on this moment to carry over and cause the Democrats to
hemorrhage to death,'' he said.
   Bush toured an aircraft assembly plant and climbed into the
cockpit of a General Dynamics F-16 fighter jet and planned to
attend several fund-raisers during his two-day swing through Texas
and Florida.
   Bush said he had no intention of making an early selection of a
running mate. ``I'm not in the mode of picking or even going
through the elementary selection process,'' Bush said.
   He said there had been ``a lot of plain manila envelopes ... a
lot of speculation'' on a possible vice presidential choice. ``None
of it is authorized by me,'' Bush added.
   Bush reiterated that he would not publicly make a recommendation
to Attorney General Edwin Meese over whether Meese should resign
because of his current legal difficulties. However, Bush said that
he would ``adhere to and advocate the highest possible ethical
standards'' if elected president.
   ``I'm not going to get into the Meese matter. I want to keep
talking about high standards,'' Bush said.
