<HEAD>Freedom Asked For Woman Who Refuses To Disclose Daughter's
Whereabouts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for plastic surgeon Elizabeth Morgan
asked a federal judge Friday to free her from jail, where she has
spent seven months for refusing to allow visits between her
daughter and the girl's father.
   Attorney Stephen Sachs said the incarceration, the latest event
in a bitter custody battle, has become irrational and
unconstitutional because ``Dr. Morgan will never relent.''
   The plastic surgeon has been at D.C. Jail since last Aug. 28,
when she refused a D.C. Superior Court judge's order to allow her
5-year-old daughter to visit her ex-husband, who she charged had
abused the child.
   She has refused to disclose her daughter's whereabouts since
then.
   Sachs said that since Judge Herbert Dixon ordered the woman
jailed to coerce her to reveal the girl's whereabouts, ``Dr.
Morgan's incarceration has become punitive.''
   ``She will never comply with the order of the Superior Court,''
Sachs told U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson. ``It is not
likely any woman, any parent, could relent when she has seen what
has happened to her daughter.''
   The woman has charged through a long-running battle over the
girl's custody that Eric Foretich, also a prominent doctor in the
Washington area, abused the child. Foretich has denied the charges.
   Johnson said the issue of whether the length of incarceration
was unconstitutional had not been dealt with by the lower court or
by the local appeals court and so a federal court may not be the
proper forum for the case.
   The judge said she expected to rule next week on whether to
release the woman.
