<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-Congress     04-08 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Congress,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Operation Alliance Not Stopping War On Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turf wars, mismanagement and lack of
leadership plague a government task force created to stop the flow
of drugs across the U.S.-Mexico border, a congressman who
investigated the operation said Friday.
   ``Once again, a lack of leadership is undermining the war on
drugs,'' said Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., chairman of the House
Government Operations justice subcommittee, which spent a year
scrutinizing Operation Alliance and issued a critical report this
week. ``No one is in charge, no one is responsible.''
   Operation Alliance, set up in August 1986 to coordinate
drug-fighting efforts in the Southwest by a variety of federal
agencies, is headed by Frank Keating, assistant Treasury secretary
for enforcement.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese's chose Keating this week to fill
the No. 3 spot in the Justice Department, that of associate
attorney general.
   The Treasury Department said it had no comment Friday on the
report and a spokesman for the Justice Department, which has
several agencies involved in the alliance, referred questions to
Treasury.
   English, D-Okla., said he doesn't fault Keating for Operation
Alliance's failure to quell drug smuggling but blames the
administration for not giving someone the authority to marshal
staff and resources from the various agencies.
   ``Operation Alliance is a good idea that isn't working because
of turf battles and a lack of strong leadership from the top. The
agencies, including the Customs Service, Drug Enforcement
Administration and the Border Patrol, have been mired in the same
interagency feuding which has frustrated nearly all of our federal
anti-drug abuse programs,'' English said.
   ``In good conscience, I can't say Operation Alliance has made
much of a contribution,'' English said from Oklahoma.
   English blamed part of the problem on Mexico's ``refusal to
participate'' and also on Customs for not lending its air wing in
the fight on drugs along the 2,000-mile border.
   ``Operation Alliance is limited to ground action, but 60 percent
of cocaine comes in by air,'' English said.
   The report said that although administration officials had
promised to put an additional 300 Border Patrol agents along the
U.S.-Mexican border, where one-third of marijuana, cocaine and
heroin are believed to be smuggled into the country, there has been
a net loss of agents.
   Participating agencies failed to coordinate efforts and did not
use the El Paso Intelligence Center, or EPIC, where U.S. narcotics
information is stored and disseminated, the report said.
   The subcommittee compared the number and size of seizures in the
year before Operation Alliance with the first year after it went to
work, and found the size of the seizures had increased dramatically.
   But it said it was concerned the number of seizures has ``not
increased as dramatically as the administration has implied.''
   According to the report, EPIC figures indicate there were 246
cocaine seizures along the Southwest border totaling 2,256
kilograms between July 1985 and June 1986. But during the following
year, there were 120 cocaine seizures totaling 7,685 kilograms.
</TEXT>
