<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     04-08 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accord Removes a Thorn, But Won't Speed Up a Treaty, Baker Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet decision to withdraw from
Afghanistan will remove one contentious issue from next month's
Moscow summit agenda but probably won't speed negotiations on a
superpower arms accord, the White House chief of staff said Friday.
   ``I think it will have a salutary effect on attitudes, but I do
not think it is likely to have a major impact on the other issues
on the agenda,'' Howard Baker told reporters covering President
Reagan, who was vacationing in California.
   Meanwhile, the State Department awaited notification that the
Kremlin had accepted an American proposal under which each side
would continue aiding its allies in the Afghan war as the estimated
120,000 Red Army troops leave Afghanistan.
   The Kremlin had rejected an earlier U.S. proposal that both
sides stop arming the warring parties during the nine months over
which the Soviets agreed to withdraw their troops, plus three
months thereafter, said State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   The United Nations mediator, Diego Garcia, told reporters in
Geneva that an agreement could be signed by the end of the week,
and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said the Red Army could
start leaving May 15.
   ``We have discussed, we have negotiated. That's over,'' mediator
Cordovez said. ``I want to inform you that the documents are now
finalized and open for signature.''
   Even though the Afghanistan accord is likely to improve the
atmosphere, at the May 29-June 2 summit, Reagan and other
administration officials say they do not expect to reach agreement
before the summit on the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
The treaty would cut U.S. and Soviet long-range nuclear arsenals by
30 to 50 percent.
   Soviet officials say publicly that a START treaty could be
signed at the summit, but privately acknowledge it is unlikely they
can reach agreement.
   Baker denied published reports, attributed to anonymous United
Nations officials, that the superpowers had agreed to stop aiding
the warring Afghan parties. And he stressed that the administration
was withholding formal endorsement of the U.N. agreement until
reading the final terms.
   ``We have made it known that we will continue to aid the
mujahadeen if the Soviets continue their aid to the Kabul
government,'' he said. ``The mujahadeen are not being abandoned.
They're not being put at a disadvantage. They will be supplied as
long as there is a need for that and as the Soviets continue to
supply the Kabul government.''
   ``After we've had a chance to examine the text of the agreement
and heard formally from the Soviet Union, we will decide if all of
the conditions have been met for us to continue and to participate
as a guarantor of this agreement,'' Baker said.
   Neither the United States nor the Soviet Union nor the Afghan
guerrillas are direct parties to the U.N. talks, which involve the
government of Pakistan and the Kremlin-backed regime in Kabul.
   U.S. officials say agreement on aiding the Afghan parties hinges
on a clause in the U.N. accord guaranteeing that foreign powers
will not intervene or interfere in Afghan affairs.
   Pakistan, which has been channeling an estimated $600 million a
year in covert U.S. aid to the guerrillas, has agreed to continue
that program as long as Moscow aids Kabul, said administration
officials who spoke on condition they not be further identified.
</TEXT>
