<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HostageFallout     04-08 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Fallout,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Hostage Situation Was a Charade</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HX1-2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was killed by police after pretending
to hold a teen-age girl hostage for three hours had a history of
erratic behavior and family problems, said a woman who had been one
of his many foster mothers.
   Israel Ramos, 19, died Wednesday at York Hospital from a single
gunshot wound to the stomach to end a three-hour standoff in which
he held police at bay from his apartment with what turned out to be
plastic water pistols.
   Police originally thought Ramos had taken a 15-year-old girl
hostage, but after the shooting she told authorities the drama was
a charade and she was a willing participant.
   Debbie Ocasio, who took in Ramos when he was 15 and had a
history of family problems, said: ``I knew he was erratic, so I
wanted to help him. I knew that if I could just talk with him, that
would help.''
   Ramos was born in Puerto Rico and spent most of his life on the
streets in New York City, said Mrs. Ocasio. He came to Pennsylvania
with his mother about four years ago.
   Ramos' mother suffered from mental disorders and frequently
spent long periods in state hospitals, forcing her son to live with
foster families, Mrs. Ocasio said. His father remained in Puerto
Rico.
   While living with the Ocasios, Ramos attended high school,
maintained a B average and saw a counselor, she said. But his life
always took a turn for the worse whenever he saw his mother.
   ``Something about her just set him off,'' Mrs. Ocasio said.
   Hoping to stabilize him, Mrs. Ocasio said she arranged for Ramos
to live with a foster family in Philadelphia. He stayed there for
some time before moving back to York to live with his mother, but
she was admitted to Harrisburg State Mental Hospital about a year
later, and Ramos ``went downhill from there,'' Mrs. Ocasio said.
   District Attorney H. Stanley Rebert said Friday the
investigation of the incident is continuing. He would not identify
the girl involved nor say if she was being held for questioning.
   Police originally said the marksman, whom they have refused to
identify, fired when Ramos threatened to kill the girl. But
videotape recorded by WGAL-TV in Lancaster showed Ramos was shot
seconds after yelling, ``I'm coming out,'' and placing both hands
on a window frame. No gun was in sight.
   Carl Robertson, director of the York Spanish-American Center;
the mayor; and Police Chief William Hose did not return phone calls
for comment Friday afternoon.
   The officer who fired the fatal shot has been placed on
administrative leave without pay, pending an investigation that
could last four weeks, Rebert said.
   The district attorney said Ramos had a ``long-standing history
of mental health problems involving bizarre and unpredictable
behavior.''
   Police records indicate Ramos sometimes went into public
buildings impersonating health and police officials. He once went
into City Hall carrying a briefcase and asked to see Mayor William
Althaus. Police said Ramos was apprehended after threatening the
mayor and a pellet gun was confiscated.
   John Gentzler, Ramos' boss at York Snacks, said he worried about
Ramos, but not that he might hurt someone.
   ``He tells me he had no friends,'' Gentzler said. ``I knew he
needed some help, so I reached out to him as a father figure.''
   Gentzler said Ramos, who worked the overnight shift, got along
well with employees. He did have ``a little verbal battle with a
few workers'' early Wednesday, but Gentzler said he didn't think it
was anything to worry about.
</TEXT>
