<HEAD>Man Nearly Hit On Airport Runway Wanted To Go Home To Jamaica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was almost hit by a
Continental Airlines jet when he sneaked onto a busy airport runway
told deputies he wanted to hijack a plane home to Jamaica,
authorities said.
   Keble Arnold, 28, was charged with criminal trespass and jailed
without bail.
   Arnold was wearing five pairs of pants, possibly to protect
himself from the cold if he decided to stow away aboard an airplane
at Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport, sheriff's
spokesman Al Gordon said.
   ``He said he wanted to hijack a plane, but from the pants he was
wearing it looks like he was ready to stow away if he had to,''
Gordon said.
   Deputies said the jet, Flight 1734 from Denver, was traveling
140 mph when it almost hit Arnold while landing Wednesday night.
   Ron Gardner of the Broward County aviation department said
stowing away in an airliner's wheel wells was risky.
   ``It's cold up there and there's no air,'' he said. ``There have
been stowaways who have frozen to death, and then dropped out of
the plane when the landing gear came down.''
