<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     04-08 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Trade Missile Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Iran-Elections, Bjt
^By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq fired four long-range missiles into
Tehran and other Iranian cities Friday before Iranians began voting
in parliamentary elections. Iran said it fired rockets into Baghdad
and other cities in retaliation.
   Each side said the other's missiles hit residential areas,
killing civilians.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, also
reported that Iraqi warplanes hit a ``large maritime target,''
which usually means a tanker, off Iran's Persian Gulf coast before
dawn.
   There was no immediate independent confirmation.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, said Iranian artillery shelled the strategic Dukan
hyrdoelectric dam in northeast Iraq, where Revolutionary Guards
have captured a large chunk of mountainous Kurdistan in the last
three weeks.
   It was not known whether the dam, 60 miles north of Iraq's
Kirkuk oil fields, was damaged.
   The Iranians occupy heights overlooking another important dam
and power station on Lake Darbandikhan, south of Dukan. Crippling
or capturing the two facilities could leave the strategic region
around Kirkuk without power.
   Both Iran and Iraq have fired nearly 300 long-range missiles
into each other's population centers in the latest chapter of the
so-called ``war of the cities.'' Hundreds of civilians have been
killed on both sides since the battle broke out Feb. 29.
   The Iran news agency said that Iraqi missiles were fired Friday
into residential neighborhoods in Tehran, the holy city of Qom, the
central city of Isfahan and Tabriz in the northwest.
   It said Iraqi warplanes raided several Iranian cities, but gave
no details.
   The Iraqi missiles smashed into Iran hours before polling
stations opened, killing or wounding civilians, the agency said. It
gave no figures.
   However, the attacks appeared to fall far short of the missile
blitz Iranian leaders had been expecting during the elections for
the 270-seat Majlis, or parliament.
   The agency said the Iranians retaliated by firing two missiles
into Baghdad, two into the northern city of Mosul, two in the
border town of Khanaqin and one into al-Amarah, an Iraqi military
area in the south, causing ``considerable damage and casualties.''
   The Iraqi News Agency confirmed one of the strikes on Baghdad
and said civilians were killed, without citing a number. It
reported other fatalities from long-range Iranian artillery fire on
Iraqi border cities.
   Iran said its warplanes bombed military targets in northern
Iraq, but the Iraqi News Agency said the jets hit residential
neighborhoods in the northern city of Amadiya and in border towns,
killing civilians.
</TEXT>
