<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDS-HealthWorkers 2ndLd-Writethru   04-08 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Health Workers, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0682,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven State Grants Announced For AIDS Training</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 1 graf to list four previously established centers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven regional centers have been awarded $5.2
million to train health professionals in AIDS prevention and
treatment, federal officials announced Friday.
   Dr. Robert E. Windom, assistant Health and Human Services
secretary for health, said the new centers will join four
established last year in providing service to 47 states, the
District of Columbia, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands.
   He said other centers will be added later this year.
   The centers are expected to collaborate with medical and nursing
schools, hospitals, health departments and other organizations to
train primary care providers for local communities and to train
selected health professionals to serve as instructors in their
communities.
   Each center also is expected to provide hotline, clearinghouse
and referral services to health professionals within its region.
   Grants supporting the first year of the three-year projects were
awarded to:
   _University of Southern California, Los Angeles, $791,883, to
serve five counties in Southern California.
   _University of Colorado, Denver, $900,000, to serve Colorado,
Kansas, Nebraska, New Mexico, North Dakota, South Dakota, Utah and
Wyoming.
   _Emory University, Atlanta, $949,760, to serve Alabama, Florida,
Georgia, North Carolina and South Carolina.
   _University of Illinois, Chicago, $808,835, which will serve
Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Minnesota, Missouri and Wisconsin.
   _Louisiana State University, New Orleans, $549,661, to serve
Arkansas, Louisiana and Mississippi.
   _University of Maryland, Baltimore, $480,000, to serve Delaware,
Maryland, Virginia, West Virginia and the District of Columbia.
   _University of Massachusetts, Worcester, $717,625, which will
serve Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island and Vermont.
   The first four training centers were established last September
with HHS grants to New York University, Ohio State University, the
University of Washington and the University of California-Davis.
</TEXT>
