<2ND_LINE>AM-Wild Fires,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brush Fire Threat Continues Across Florida; Thousands of Acres
Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters worked Friday to contain brush fires
across the state that were fueled by dry wind and burned thousands
of acres of grassland, trees, bushes and shrubs.
   Two firefighters suffered minor injuries fighting the blaze
Thursday. No damage to buildings was reported.
   The largest fire destroyed 1,500 to 2,000 acres at the edge of
the Osceola National Forest, said Larry Amison, spokesman for the
state Division of Forestry.
   He said firefighters were trying to hold fire lines, Amison
said. ``But there's a large unburned area inside the line, and
they're not confident they'll be able to hold it if the winds pick
up.''
   A fire that authorities tried to contain near Port St. Lucie was
the biggest concern, said Seb Farina, Division of Forestry
spokesman. The fire had burned nearly 1,300 acres and endangered a
residential subdivision.
   ``It's out of the (fire) lines,'' Farina said. ``There are some
structures that could be threatened. It's not a hysterical sort of
thing, but it's the fire with the greatest potential.''
   Because Florida remained dry Friday, with wind gusting up to 20
mph, officials expected the fire problem to continue.
