<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lottery-DogBite     04-08 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottery-Dog Bite,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dog Bites Man _ After He Wins $2 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen Stillman may have won $2 million
in the New York Lottery, but the thrill of victory didn't stop him
from feeling the agony of ... a dog bite?
   He showed off the poodle-inflicted bite at a news conference
Friday.
   When the winning numbers were broadcast April 6, Stillman, 34,
flew up the stairs, hugged his wife and, in the uproar, got bitten
by his dog, he said.
   Stillman and his wife, Cathy, of suburban Greece, have played
the same six numbers for four years. Those numbers _ 17, 24, 27,
31, 39 and 43 _ represent the jersey numbers of their favorite
sports figures, including baseball Hall of Famer Willie Mays and
Dave Winfield of the New York Yankees.
   The couple will receive an after-tax check of $76,190 annually
for 21 years, with the first pay-off coming in about two weeks.
They said they plan to take a vacation, pay some bills and send
their 16-year-old son to college.
   Stillman is a restaurant manager. His wife works at the
restaurant and attends the University of Buffalo. They said they do
not plan to quit their jobs.
</TEXT>
