<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--US-Kurds     04-08 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--US-Kurds,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurds Demonstrate Against Iraqi Chemical Warfare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 Kurds, some wearing gas masks,
demonstrated Friday at the Iraqi Embassy to denounce President
Saddam Hussein for his use of chemical warfare against civilians.
   Chanting ``Saddam Butcher of the Kurds,'' the demonstrators also
held up photographs of scarred bodies they said were victims of a
March 16 chemical attack on the northern Iraqi town of Halabja.
   About 5,000 Iraqi Kurds were reported killed in the Iraqi
bombing raid on the town, which had been captured by Iran. Several
dozen wounded were flown by Iran to Europe and the United States
for treatment of mustard gas exposure.
   The Kurdistan Democratic Party, which organized the rally, said
survivors have testified that thousands of people are still buried
under the ruins in Halabja and that the town has turned into an
open grave for more than 4,000 dead. Seven thousand were wounded,
the party said.
   The protesters called on the United Nations and international
humanitarian organizations to send emergency relief and medical
supplies to the town, and to condemn Hussein.
</TEXT>
