<HEAD>Plantings of Spring Vegetables Up 7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vegetable farmers have boosted plantings for
this spring's fresh market by 7 percent over a year ago to 178,000
acres, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said acreages are
up for carrots, celery, sweet corn, lettuce and tomatoes. However,
reduced plantings were reported for broccoli and cauliflower.
   Plantings of the Texas honeydew melon crop were estimated at
6,500 acres, up 41 percent from a year ago.
