<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore     04-08 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Fires First Salvos In New York Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. donned an olive-green field
jacket for his opening salvo in the New York presidential primary's
battle of the airwaves.
   ``I'm a Vietnam veteran _ one of the lucky ones,'' Gore says in
a new ad for television. Because of his experience, he says, he has
worked ``for arms control, for peace, for a strong bargaining
position with the Russians.''
   Gore's experience is the focus of two new ads that began airing
in New York this week. A third, unveiled Friday, touts a commitment
to education and suggests using the military against drug smugglers.
   On the stump Friday, Gore underscored the drug theme by telling
a Long Island audience, ``This administration declared a war
against drugs and drugs won. They've got to say yes to funding for
drug programs.''
   Gore's new ads, with one mild exception, do not take direct aim
at his opponents as did earlier commercials. ``We just do issues,''
said a senior adviser, Bill Haddad. ``That's what we've been doing.
That's going to continue.''
   Gore, who has not won a contest since Super Tuesday, hopes to
revive his struggling candidacy in New York, and television ads are
a key segment of his strategy. Those out this week are the first of
six that are planned.
   But the effort may be hamstrung by the sky-high price of
advertising in New York. Gore media manager David Garth has
indicated discontent with the size of the campaign's TV buy.
   Garth said ideally he would want to spend $2 million on TV time,
but would settle for $1 million. Gore aides said they had committed
$500,000 and hoped for more. The Gore campaign is $1.5 million in
debt.
   The first two Gore ads are biographical spots aimed at
introducing him to voters. The field jacket ad shows him standing
in front of Manhattan's Vietnam War memorial as he recounts his
experience and his efforts for peace; in his only reference to his
opponents, he says, ``I believe no other Democrat running for
president has the experience to make that fight.''
   The second advertisement presents a sequence of still photos and
footage _ Gore at Harvard, in the Army, in the Senate, and talking
to voters. An announcer says: ``Vote for Al Gore. He's got a solid
record. He can win.''
   In the third, Gore, his tie loosened, declares: ``We're losing
too many kids to drugs and an inadequate education.'' Education is
important to the nation's security, he says, ``and if that means
using the military to help stop drugs at our borders, then let's do
it.''
   Gore has been more aggressive in campaign appearances, directly
criticizing his opponents, Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts
and Jesse Jackson.
   Dukakis has been on the air this week with biographical ads.
Jackson, who has bought very little ad time over the course of the
campaign, was filmed campaigning in Brooklyn on Tuesday for
possible advertising footage, but aides said his ad strategy for
the primary was uncertain.
   ``It's not until April 19,'' said Jackson ad man Dan Mowbray.
``And in the Jackson campaign that's a world away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
