<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Knights     04-08 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Knights,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Knights of Malta Convene Secret Conclave To Select New Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Knights of Malta convened a secret conclave in a
hilltop villa Friday to elect a new leader of the 900-year-old
Roman Catholic charitable order.
   Thirty-six electors clad in black robes locked themselves in a
third-floor room of a palazzo on the Aventine Hill to cast ballots
for a new grand master. Two of the candidates are Americans.
   The previous grand master, Angelo de Mojana di Cologna, died
Jan. 18 at the age of 82 after 25 years as the knights' leader.
   The result of the election is not expected to be announced until
early next week after ratification by Pope John Paul II.
   A grand master, who is elected for life, carries the title of
prince and ``most eminent highness.'' Equal in rank to a cardinal,
he is considered the highest ranking layman in the Roman Catholic
church.
   The order's 78th grand master will be chosen from among 22 of
the electors who have attained the rank of ``Professed Knights of
Justice.''
   To be eligible, the new leader must have followed vows of
poverty, obedience and chastity and be able to prove 200 years of
nobility on the side of both parents.
   The group _ formally known as the Sovereign Military Order of
the Hospital of St. John of Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta _ was
founded during the crusades when it opened a hospice for pilgrims
in Jerusalem in the early 11th century.
   It has the status of an independent state and has diplomatic
relations with 50 nations.
   The order has about 10,000 members, led by Italy with 2,800.
About 2,500 members live in the United States.
   The knights operate about 200 hospitals and first aid centers in
90 nations, mostly in poor areas and war zones.
   The 36 electors, all members of the Council Complete of State,
assembled for a morning Mass in the villa's 18th century Santa
Maria del Priorato church.
   In his homily, the prelate of the order, Archbishop Mario Brini,
said the new grand master should be ``a man of great faith, imbued
with charisma of the order which Pope John Paul II has not
hesitated to count among the treasures of the church, a heritage
which must be defended and strengthened to make it always more
adaptable to the changing needs of the times.''
   Following the service, the group walked in a slow procession
around the church courtyard and through a passageway flanked by
orange trees. The 22 Knights of Justice wore the order's
eight-pointed white cross on their sleeves, while the others wore
the emblem over their chests.
   The officials then entered the villa and went to the Hall of the
Council Complete of State, where they sat at a long table covered
by a red cloth. The room, which is reserved for elections of grand
masters, is lined with portraits of previous leaders and has a
splendid view of the capital.
   The 22 candidates include de Mojana's interim replacement,
Giancarlo Pallavicini, a Hungarian-born American biochemist, and
Cyrille Toumanoff, who was born in the Soviet Union and lives in
the United States. Their American hometowns were not immediately
available.
   The others are nine Italians, four Austrians, two Englishmen,
two Czechoslovaks, and one each from West Germany, Hungary and
Spain.
   The rest of the council is made up of presidents of the order's
associations around the world, including New York financier J.
Peter Grace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
