<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-08 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Coast Gets Rain; Rockies Get Snow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain soaked the East Coast from Virginia to southern New England
on Friday, while light snow fell in the northern Rockies and high
winds buffeted the Southwest.
   Showers were heaviest in Maryland and Virginia. Salisbury, Md.,
got 2.72 inches of rain in a 24-hour period ending at 8 a.m. EDT.
Langley Air Force Base and Norfolk Naval Air Station, both in
Virginia, got nearly an inch of rain apiece in six hours.
   In Montana, Billings got 3 inches of snow, West Yellowstone 2
inches and Butte and Bozeman 1 inch.
   Snow advisories were issued for the central third of Montana and
the north-central mountains of Wyoming due to high winds that were
blowing snow and causing hazardous driving conditions.
   Elsewhere, temperatures were chilly in the Northwest, where four
towns in western Oregon tied or set record lows for the date:
Klamath Falls' 17 degrees bettered the 22 degrees set in 1982;
Medford's 25 beat the 27 degrees set in 1919; Astoria's 30 bettered
the mark of 31 set in 1975, and Portland tied its 32-degree mark
set in 1952.
   Wind advisories were issued for southern Nevada and the northern
mountains and deserts of southern California. Winds of 35-40 mph
were recorded in Sandberg and Daggett, in California's northern
deserts. Northern and central California coastal waters also were
under a gale warning.
   Florida, the Gulf Coast and the Mississippi, Tennessee and Ohio
valleys all enjoyed sunshine and mild temperatures.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 26 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif. The morning low
was 2 degrees in McCall, Idaho.
   Saturday's forecast called for widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms extending from Texas across Oklahoma to eastern
Kansas; rain from western Kansas across Nebraska and the Dakotas to
Minnesota, mixing with snow in western parts of South Dakota and
Nebraska; and rain and drizzle in eastern New England.
   High temperatures should be in the 60s to 70s for much of the
nation, dipping into the 40s to 50s from the Middle and Northern
Atlantic States to eastern Ohio, and from northern Michigan across
northern Minnesota and the Dakotas and western parts of the central
Plains to the north-central Rockies, into the 30s in the mountains
of Wyoming and Colorado, into the 80s in southern Florida, the
central Gulf Coast, from southern and eastern Texas to central
Missouri and most of California; and into the low 90s in the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
