<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Honduras-Travel     04-08 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Honduras-Travel,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Issues Travel Advisory For Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department warned Friday against
travel to Honduras by U.S. citizens because of anti-American riots
that erupted in that Central American nation.
   Honduran President Jose Azona Hoyo declared a state of emergency
in the country's two major cities, Tegucigalpa and San Pedro Sula,
after students smashed shop windows and overturned cars in the
violence, sparked by the forced deportation to the United States of
a Honduran suspected of drug trafficking.
   ``Until the situation is clarified, the Department of State
recommends that U.S. citizens defer travel to any area of Honduras.
Expiration for this travel advisory is indefinite,'' said Sondra
McCarty, a department spokeswoman.
   On Thursday, five people were killed in an attack on the U.S.
Embassy. About 2,000 university students attacked two U.S. Embassy
annex buildings and set both ablaze. At least 10 people were
wounded, none of them Americans.
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Friday
the Reagan administration was puzzled by amount of time it took
police to arrive on the scene Thursday evening.
   ``We do not understand the slow response. We are highly
concerned over the threat this posed to American and Honduran lives
and the destruction of American property,'' she said, and the
matter had been taken up with Honduran authorities.
</TEXT>
