<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalBriefs     04-08 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch Says He Was Speaking To Jews, Not For Them, On Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch said Friday he was speaking
to Jews, not for them, when he said they would be ``crazy'' to vote
for presidential candidate Jesse Jackson.
   Koch stressed that when he recently criticized Jackson, he had
said Jews and ``supporters of Israel'' would be crazy to vote for
Jackson. The reason, he said, was that Jackson had expressed
positions that would weaken U.S. support for Israel militarily,
economically and morally.
   He also said Jackson would bankrupt America through a $300
billion spending program for ``pie in the sky'' social programs and
would disarm the United States.
   ``Supporters of Jesse Jackson are saying Koch can't say these
things. They they will cloud it by saying it's divisive,'' Koch
complained. ``What do you think a political campaign is? A
political campaign is divisive. Somebody's got to win and
somebody's got to lose.''
   He added, ``You gotta earn your right to be the president. That
person is the most important person in the whole world politically.
Shouldn't we know what he stands for?''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Detroit Mayor Says He'll Donate To Jackson Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman Young, who two weeks ago backed the
presidential bid of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in Michigan,
surprised some Jesse Jackson supporters by reportedly offering to
donate $10,000 to $20,000 to Jackson's campaign.
   Young met Thursday with Joel Ferguson, an East Lansing developer
who headed Jackson's efforts in Michigan. Though the mayor wouldn't
specify how much he would give, Ferguson said Young offered between
$10,000 and $20,000 to Jackson's campaign.
   ``He called it a modest contribution. I called it substantial.
It's a statement that Jesse appreciates,'' Ferguson said.
   Young said he was willing to contribute because Jackson's
campaign has united black and white voters as well as raising
issues of economic and racial justice.
   Jackson crushed Dukakis in Michigan's Democratic caucuses on
March 26.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects LaRouche Attempt To Get On Ballot In Indiana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge rejected an attempt Friday
to put political extremist Lyndon LaRouche on the ballot for
Indiana's May 3 Democratic primary for president.
   U.S. District Judge S. Hugh Dillin ruled against a LaRouche
argument that the candidate's rights were violated by a requirement
that his campaign submit 500 signatures from each of the state's 10
congressional districts on his ballot petitions.
   Because LaRouche's campaign turned in fewer than the required
500 signatures for the 10th District, the Indiana secretary of
state's office refused to certify him for the ballot.
   Dillin also told lawyers from the state attorney general's
office that they could ask LaRouche to pay the state's costs
because his attorneys had failed to do proper research and had
brought what amounted to a frivolous action.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Slow Caucus Count Prompts Talk About Having A Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado's slow reporting of Democratic caucus
results has prompted talk about switching to a primary system for
presidential races.
   Democratic caucuses were held in Colorado Monday but the state
party was continuing to report results later in the week;
meanwhile, Wisconsin's presidential primary was Tuesday. ``Colorado
never even had its hour in the sun,'' said former Gov. Richard
Lamm, adding: ``By the time we got our results in, Wisconsin was
the news.''
   Lamm, a Democrat, had raised the matter of a primary with other
Western governors a few years ago when the 1988 Super Tuesday round
of primaries and caucuses, through much of the South, was taking
shape.
   ``I think our strength is in unity,'' Lamm said Wednesday in an
interview with the Rocky Mountain News. ``Colorado is never going
to be a major player by itself.''
   State Democratic Chairman Buie Seawell has said he favors the
concept but state Republican Chairman Bruce Benson is cool to it.
``I suppose I could be talked into it, but I'm not wild about it,''
said Benson.
</TEXT>
