<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietTrade     04-08 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Trade,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Expects No Breakthroughs in Soviet Trade Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUSTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity said
Friday that he expected no breakthroughs in trade talks next week
with Soviet officials in Moscow.
   But Verity, who is leading a delegation of American officials
for the tenth session of the Joint Commercial Commission, said he
was hopeful the negotiations could lay the groundwork for expanded
trade.
   The joint commission was formed in 1973 to bring trade agencies
of the two governments together. The meetings will take place at
the same time a trade delegation of 400 American businessmen will
be in Moscow for talks on trade opportunities.
   Verity, who will be meeting with Soviet officials including
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, said the United States would
seek expanded opportunities for American companies to sell their
products in the Soviet Union.
   Last year, trade between the United States and the Soviet Union
totaled $1.5 billion, two-thirds of that in grain sales. This
represented just 0.5 percent of American export sales and was a
decline from $4.5 billion in U.S.-Soviet trade in 1979, before
President Carter imposed the trade embargo after Soviet troops
invaded Afghanistan.
   ``We are not going to Moscow for any breakthroughs,'' Verity
said. ``We do not expect any dramatic increase in trade to result.
What we hope to do is to create a new climate and a foundation for
future trade.''
   Verity said he would stress that expanded trade can only take
place if the Soviets make ``further improvements elsewhere in our
bilateral relationship, particularly on human rights and
immigration.''
   Asked whether the Thursday announcement that Soviet troops would
begin pulling out of Afghanistan on May 15 would help the trade
talks, Verity said he believed that President Reagan was ``very
happy'' with the development.
   ``There isn't any question in my mind that if the Soviets would
continue to indicate that they would like to lessen tensions, that
would certainly have an effect on the American people and the
American Congress,'' Verity said.
   Verity, who will leave for Moscow on Sunday, won Cabinet
approval earlier this week for a plan to set up high-level working
groups with the Soviets to spur exchanges in five areas: food
processing, energy, construction equipment, medical products and
the services sector, including insurance.
   Verity said it was hoped that these working groups will provide
channels to develop specific markets for U.S. products.
   The meetings next week are expected to produce some agreements
on the establishment of joint ventures between American companies
and the Soviet Union.
   The trade meetings will come six weeks before Reagan travels to
Moscow for his fourth summit conference with Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
