<HEAD>Seven Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAZEWELL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wreckage of a private airplane with
seven bodies inside was found Friday in the rugged mountains around
Cumberland Gap, officials said.
   The Cherokee Six Saratoga left Boca Raton, Fla., on Easter
Sunday and was lost to radar contact in the mountainous Cumberland
Gap area late that evening, said Adele Sparks of the Civil Air
Patrol in Knoxville.
   The plane was reported missing Tuesday by the sister of the
pilot, James Cox, 44, of Ridgefield, Ind., Ms. Sparks said.
   The passengers had not yet been identified by name, but were
Cox's wife, his parents, a 13-year-old daughter, a friend of the
daughter's and a 9-month-old child, she said.
   Efforts to find the plane had been confined to the ground by bad
weather until Friday afternoon, when the weather broke enough to
allow airborne search, Ms. Sparks said.
   The wreck was about four miles east of the Cumberland Gap, where
Tennessee, Kentucky and Virginia abut, Ms. Sparks said.
   The plane hit the top of a ridge on the Kentucky-Virginia state
line, she said. The wreck was about four miles east of the
Cumberland Gap, where Tennessee, Kentucky and Virginia abut, she
said.
   The initial impact sheared off one wing, and the plane continued
for about a half-mile before hitting a ridge on the Kentucky side
of the line, Ms. Sparks said.
   The plane was registered to Cox Engineering Co. of Ridgefield.
</TEXT>
