<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0710 04-08 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0710,0981</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Arab Worshipers Wounded, Firebomb Tossed at Consulate
Official's Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One graf SUBS for 8th graf pvs, Army spokesmen ... UPDATING
with TV report girl was shot; INSERT one graf after 15th graf,
``Give yourselves ... UPDATING with army bulldozer hits shops; 4
grafs SUB for final 5 grafs pvs, Last year ... to UPDATE.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers wounded nine Arabs in street battles
after weekly Moslem prayers Friday, and a firebomb was hurled at
the home of a U.S. consulate official in Arab east Jerusalem, but
no one was injured.
   Most protests dispersed quickly on what proved one of the
quieter Moslem sabbaths in four months of Palestinian unrest.
   Consulate spokesman David Good said the firebomb was tossed at
7:30 p.m. while his 5-year-old daughter and two maids were in the
house. He said it damaged the porch but caused no injuries.
   A guard protecting the house was in the back of the building at
the time of the attack, Good said. He said consulate officials
decided to provide him with a guard several days ago because of
growing tensions in the area.
   Arab youths chanted anti-Israeli slogans, raised black mourning
flags and threw rocks at soldiers after services at mosques in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, which have been swept by
violence since Dec. 8.
   A prayer leader at the sacred Al Aqsa mosque condemned the peace
plan of Secretary of State George P. Shultz. ``It is known that the
United States does not give people their true rights,'' said
Muhammed Siam.
   A military official said the army continued investigating the
death of a 15-year-old Jewish girl in a clash with Arabs on
Wednesday.
   It was first reported that the girl, Tirza Porat, died from a
stone thrown by Arabs. But Israel television, citing an army
investigation, said Friday she apparently was shot to death.
Results of the army probe leaked to Israel TV and radio indicated
she may have been shot inadvertently by an Israeli.
   Arab hospital officials reported nine Palestinians wounded by
soldiers Friday in four separate clashes in the West Bank and Gaza,
which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   The largest toll was at the Jabaliya refugee camp in Gaza, where
worshipers emerged from a mosque and marched to an Israeli military
base. Palestinian reports said they hurled rocks at soldiers, who
responded with tear gas and gunfire, wounding five.
   On Jerusalem's Temple Mount, the sacred hill Arabs call Haram al
Sharif, dozens of Palestinians chanted nationalist slogans after
noon prayers at Al Aqsa and paraded with a black flag to mourn
Arabs killed in the violence.
   At least 141 Palestinians have died since Dec. 8, according to
U.N. figures. An Israeli soldier was stabbed to death and Miss
Porat was the first Israeli civilian killed.
   ``With our blood and spirit, we will redeem you, Palestine!''
the demonstrators at Al Aqsa chanted. Youngsters threw rocks at
border police perched on rooftops with sniper rifles, but were
dispersed without incident.
   Inside the mosque, prayer leader Siam urged worshipers to reject
the U.S. peace initiative.
   ``Give yourselves to Allah, but not to Shultz,'' Siam said. ``He
is not the person to decide what is good and what is bad for us.''
   In the West Bank village Beit Ummar near Hebron, an army
bulldozer plowed into shops after a demonstration, said Mustafa
Natshe, the former mayor of Hebron. Army officials said they had no
report of the incident.
   Shultz headed home Friday after an unsuccessful five-day effort
to arrange negotiations between Israeli and Arab leaders.
Palestinians accused him of trying to crush the rebellion with his
peace effort.
   A senior military official said Friday the army still had not
determined what killed Tirza Porat, who was on a Passover holiday
hike with other teen-age children of Jewish settlers in the
occupied West Bank. Two Arabs also were killed, and two Arabs and
13 Israelis injured.
   ``We know she was struck by a bullet and a stone,'' the official
told The Associated Press. ``The exact cause of death is not
known.''
   According to an army report leaked to Israeli radio and
television, the clash began when 16 teen-agers and their two guards
were stoned by youths from Beita, an Arab town.
   The radio quoted the report as saying the guards disagreed over
what to do. It said Romam Al Dubi, 26, wanted to shoot but the
other guard asked him not to.
   Al Dubi told the children to gather around him and started
shooting, the radio said, then the Arab youths disarmed him and
took the Israelis to Beita.
   A large crowd attacked the Israelis in the town, reports have
said, but the army stressed that many villagers helped the
teen-agers.
   Israeli media reports have identified Al Dubi as a follower of
the anti-Arab Kach movement of U.S.-born Rabbi Meir Kahane.
   Israel television, quoting a ranking military source it did not
identify, said the bullet in Miss Porat's head was fired from the
gun of one of the Israeli guards but it was not known who pulled
the trigger.
   The army said a Beita resident on Friday handed Al Dubi's M-16
rifle to a soldier, and TV reports said eight bullets were still in
the magazine.
   Israel radio quoted an army report as saying Ms. Porat was also
struck in the head by a rock hurled by the mother and sister of an
Arab killed in the clash. The two women are under arrest, the
report was quoted as saying.
   Beita remained under curfew Friday. The army said soldiers
demolished eight more homes of suspects, bringing the two-day total
to 13.
</TEXT>
