<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Violence     04-08 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Violence,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syrian-Backed Moslems Claim Victory In Lebanon; Two Germans Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-backed Amal militiamen claimed
victory in south Lebanon on Friday after four days of clashes with
rival Iranian-backed Shiite fighters which left 62 dead and 150
wounded, police said Friday.
   The Syria-backed Amal militia led by Justice Minister Nabih
Berri apparently had battled the more militant Hezbollah, or Party
of God, which is loyal to Iran.
   Amal won the key town of Ghaziyeh, a Hezbollah stronghold, in a
sweeping attack Thursday after its fighters took control of the
inland market town of Nabatiyeh.
   Police said two West German relief workers who were held captive
for 14 hours by Hezbollah were freed Thursday when Amal militiamen
took Ghaziyeh.
   The Amal commander in Nabatiyeh, Mahmoud Faqih, said the
crackdown on Hezbollah was ``inevitable.''
   ``They were harrassing the population, kidnapping innocent
people and confiscating property owned by the Christians,'' a
minority in the area, Faqih told The Associated Press at his
bullet-riddled office in Nabatiyeh.
   Hezbollah forces, loyal to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,
remained entrenched in three hamlets west of Nabatiyeh with Shiite
mediators negotiating terms for their surrender.
   Trouble between Amal and Hezbollah began Feb. 17, when Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins, the U.S. Marine who commands U.N. truce
observers, was kidnapped near Tyre and Amal rounded up dozens of
Hezbollah members it accused of involvement.
   Shiite militants loyal to Iran are believed to hold most of the
22 foreign hostages in Lebanon, who include nine Americans. Held
longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of
The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The West Germans, who work for a West German humanitarian
organization identified as Asme Humanitas, disappeared after
leaving the Palestinian refugee camp of Mieh Mieh in Sidon
Wednesday morning, police said.
   They were identified as Heinrich Strubig, 47, the director of
the organization in Mieh Mieh, and his assistant, Petra Schnitzler,
24, of Hamburg.
   Ms. Schnitzler suffered bullet shrapnel cuts on one hand and
burns from another bullet that grazed her left wrist. She told The
Associated Press that she and Strubig were riding in an ambulance
to distribute food and medicine when they were stopped.
   ``We were intercepted by armed men in at least two cars, who
fired several shots over our vehicle,'' she said.
   Police said the West Germans had been held in the basement of a
mosque.
</TEXT>
