<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador-Meese     04-08 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Meese,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Backs Anti-Drug Force in Ecuador Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III
called anew on Friday for a multinational force to combat global
drug trafficking.
   He addressed a news conference in Quito following his arrival in
Ecuador on Thursday night.
   The U.S. Embassy said Meese canceled a visit Friday to an
anti-drug operations site in the Ecuadorean Amazon jungle and
instead toured a police academy.
   He is scheduled to fly to Guayaquil, Ecuador, on Saturday for a
meeting with President Leon Febres Cordero before traveling on to
Peru and Bolivia.
   Meese is accompanied by John Lawn, head of the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration, on a fact-finding mission to measure
the success of Latin American nations' efforts to halt cocaine
trafficking.
   He told reporters Friday the proposal for a multinational
anti-drug force was ``favorably received'' in his meetings with
government officials in the Dominican Republic and Colombia before
coming here.
   ``This is an idea that has a lot of merit and should be explored
in the future,'' Meese said.
   DEA officials say Ecuador's role in cocaine trafficking is less
significant than that of its Andean neighbors.
   Production of coca leaf, the raw ingredient of cocaine, is on a
minor scale in Ecuador. But in recent years international drug
smugglers have begun using this small nation, wedged between
Colombia and Peru, as an important transshipment point.
   Peru is the world's largest grower of coca leaf. Most of its
production is partially refined and smuggled into Colombia, where
the drug is refined into pure cocaine for export to U.S. and
European markets. Bolivia is the second biggest grower and a major
refiner as well.
   Reagan administration officials have praised Febres Cordero for
his commitment to the battle against drugs, and Congress has
increased funding for the fight.
</TEXT>
