<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0734 04-08 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0734,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Moves to Counter Doubts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 2nd graf to UPDATE with campaign
manager saying Jackson won't meet with Jewish umbrella group. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs bgng: Concerning his ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, campaigning across the city
boroughs, said Friday he had ``sent a message no one can miss'' to
allay concerns that he harbors anti-Semitic feelings, and he moved
to counter criticism that he lacks the government experience to be
president.
   ``Our own commitment is to end any vestiges of racism, of
anti-Semitism, or sexism,'' he said, and in one appearance he
described the link between blacks and Jews during the civil rights
movement. Growing up in the South, Jackson said, ``it was
commonplace to see signs that said `blacks and Jews and dogs are
not welcome.'''
   Jackson will not, however, meet with a Jewish umbrella group to
address their concerns, said Gerald Austin, Jackson's campaign
manager.
   The National Jewish Community Relations Council had sought such
a meeting, but Austin said Jackson could not take the time from his
campaign for New York's April 19 primary.
   ``We've already answered all these questions. I don't see why we
have to go to a meeting to answer all the questions again,'' Austin
said outside of a fund-raiser in Wading River, on Long Island.
   ``We're talking to the people in New York City. A lot of them
happen to be Jewish. We are talking about issues that are important
to us as opposed to the issues that are important to one group of
people,'' he added.
   Concerning his lack of experience in office, Jackson told a
senior citizens forum in Garden Grove, Long Island that he would
recruit government officials to his administration and ``put
together a competent and credible management team'' and cabinet.
   ``Some office holders are not leaders and some leaders are not
office holders,'' he said. ``...I am a leader.''
   One of Jackson's two Democratic rivals, Sen. Albert Gore Jr.,
told the same forum that he does not intend to stop making
experience an issue in the campaign. He cited his own credentials
as a member of Congress and leader on various legislative matters
of concern to the seniors.
   Jackson listed various economic proposals: to freeze the
military budget, create a merger review board for corporate mergers
and invest public pension funds in housing construction projects.
   In earlier remarks, Jackson discussed black-Jewish bonds during
the civil rights struggle of the 1960s.
   In a breakfast speech to union officials at Sardi's restaurant
in Manhattan's theater district, Jackson said that during his youth
in the South, ``It was commonplace to see signs that said `blacks
and Jews and dogs are not welcome.'''
   He also spoke of people who were killed during the civil rights
years. He cited the shooting deaths of three white civil rights
workers in Mississippi in the early 1960s, pointedly noting that
two of them were Jewish.
   Many Jewish voters, a large and active voting bloc in New York's
critical April 19 primary, oppose Jackson's support for a
Palestinian homeland and were alienated by his 1984 use of the
offensive term ``Hymietown'' to describe New York City. Moreover,
they are wary of his previous association with Nation of Islam
leader Louis Farrakhan, who called Judaism a ``dirty religion.''
   Asked how he would respond to that resistance, Jackson told
reporters, ``We continue to build relationships. We continue to
heal relationships. Ours is an inclusive outreach campaign.''
   Additionally, he said Jews are among many minority and ethnic
groups he has involved in his campaign.
   At the senior citizens forum at Adelphi University in Garden
Grove, a woman asked Jackson to comment on the lack of U.S.
intervention when Hitler was killing Jewish people during World War
II.
   ``We did not act quickly,'' at that time, Jackson replied. ``We
did abandon many Jewish people to Hitler's hell. It was a tragic
mistake.''
   Jackson went on to mention two issues of key importance to
Jewish voters. He said Americans must fight for the right of Soviet
Jews to emigrate, and for the right of Israel to exist and be
assured of security.
   Jackson, whose once poor campaign has seen a dramatic boost in
fund-raising, took a veiled swipe at the fat checkbook of rival
Michael Dukakis, telling the labor breakfast, ``You can have the
greatest fund raisers going, and no message and no vision _ and
then what.''
   Jackson also spoke to an enthusiastic crowd at a high school in
Wyandanch, N.Y. About 1,000 youth, including band members in bright
green and gold, crowded in the hall to applaud his call for
excellence in academics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
