<DOCNO> AP880408-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 2050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0774 04-08 1091</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0774,1,040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Seeks To Soothe Jewish Concerns in New York</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 graf after 7th graf bgng: Jackson would ... to
UPDATE with campaign manager saying he will not meet with Jewish
umbrella group. Picks up 8th graf pvs bgng: Jackson has ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, reaching out to Jewish primary voters in New
York, said Friday he was trying to ``heal relationships'' that
frayed during his 1984 presidential campaign. Republican George
Bush, his own nomination secure, surveyed the Democratic race and
said ``I wouldn't trade'' places.
   The Democrats focused on New York and its April 19 turning-point
primary with 255 delegates, with Michael Dukakis and Albert Gore
Jr. both waging war on drugs.
   Jackson, campaigning in Manhattan, was asked by reporters about
his relationship with the Jewish community, severely strained since
he referred to New York as ``Hymietown'' during his 1984
presidential bid.
   ``Our own commitment is to end any vestiges of racism, of
anti-Semitism, or sexism...,'' Jackson said. ``We've sent a message
no one can miss.''
   A poll released Friday by the Marist College Institute for
Public Opinion showed Jackson was supported by just 9 percent of
Jewish voters. Michael Dukakis was the choice of 68 percent of Jews
surveyed, while Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee was favored by 10
percent.
   Jews make up one-fourth of the voters expected to cast ballots
in the state's contest.
   Jackson would not say whether he has agreed to meet with Jewish
groups, but he said, ``We continue to build relationships, we
continue to heal relationships.''
   However, his campaign manager said late Friday that Jackson will
not meet with a Jewish umbrella group to address their concerns.
The National Jewish Community Relations Council had sought such a
meeting, but campaign manager Gerald Austin said Jackson could not
take the time for the meeting.
   ``We've already answered all these questions. I don't see why we
have to go to a meeting to answer all the questions again,'' Austin
said.
   Jackson has alienated Jews by endorsing a homeland for
Palestinians and because of his close relationship with Louis
Farrakhan, the Black Muslim leader who has called Judaism a
``gutter religion.''
   Asked what his relationship with Farrakhan is today, Jackson
said, ``We do not have one. It is precisely that.''
   One of Jackson's antagonists, New York Mayor Edward Koch,
defended his comment that Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for
Jackson. ``Supporters of Jesse Jackson are saying Koch can't say
these things,'' the mayor said. ``What do you think a political
campaign is? A political campaign is divisive. Somebody's got to
win and somebody's got to lose.''
   Overall, the Marist poll showed Dukakis leading Jackson among
likely Democratic voters by 47 percent to 31 percent, with Gore
receiving support from 6 percent.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, who has not endorsed any of the Democratic
hopefuls, said the poll indicated to him that it might be a tight
race because he expected both Jackson and Gore to continue to pick
up support. As for Dukakis, he said, ``I don't know how much room
there is to go.''
   Cuomo also revealed that he has already voted by absentee ballot
for one of the candidates, but refused to say which one.
   Dukakis and Gore waged war on the Reagan administration's drug
war during their campaign stops.
   ``This administation declared a war against drugs and drugs
won,'' Gore said in Brentwood. ``They've got to say yes to funding
for drug programs.''
   ``I'd wage a real war, not a phony war, on drugs,'' Dukakis told
senior citizens. ``We've got to get tough on the flow of drugs into
this country.''
   Bush was out on the road again, touring an aircraft assembly
plant in Fort Worth and attending several fund-raisers during a
two-day swing through Texas and Florida. Bush is virtually assured
his party's nomination after Bob Dole dropped out and Pat Robertson
severely scaled back his campaign.
   Bush said he didn't think the Democratic infighting would last
into the fall campaign.
   ``I wish I thought the Democrats would have a unity problem but
I don't think they will. I'm not counting on the blood on the floor
that exists on this moment to carry over and cause the Democrats to
hemorrhage to death,'' he said.
   Asked if he minded not having the discipline of a primary
contest, Bush said, ``I'm delighted it's worked out the way it has.
You offset staying in the news through combat by the luxury that
comes with having the time to deal with issues. I wouldn't trade,
let's put it that way.''
   In Albany, N.Y., the state Democratic Committee's executive
director, John Marino, said some party leaders are beginning to
throw their support to Dukakis. Cuomo and state Democratic Chairman
Laurence Kirwan had urged the 300 members of the state party
committee on Thursday to choose one of the three presidential
contenders.
   ``After yesterday, I got a clear sense of some movement to
Dukakis,'' said Marino. ``By next Monday or Tuesday, we'll have a
much better feeling for that. Maybe there'll be a bandwagon effect
(for Dukakis), but you may have a backlash reaction.''
   Later Friday, however, Cuomo at a news conference said he did
not care whether Democratic leaders endorsed candidates or not. ``I
did not offer instruction to people that they must endorse or
should endorse. Why should I? I haven't endorsed myself. I'm not
instructing or suggesting.''
   Cuomo said he was in discussions with the three candidates about
making campaign appearances with them all, time permitting. ``I'll
go anywhere with them,'' he said.
   Some Democrats in New York are backing an uncommitted slate of
delegates to the party's national convention in Atlanta in July in
hopes of generating a draft of Cuomo to be the presidential nominee.
   Cuomo has said he does not want to be the candidate. But he has
refused to endorse any of the three contending Democrats, and has
not ruled out accepting a draft for the nomination if the
convention is deadlocked.
   Another prominent Democrat who has counted himself out of the
presidential race, Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, indicated Friday that
he has had no second thoughts about his decision.
   Nunn, who announced last year that he would not be a candidate,
conceded that it would be difficult to turn down a presidential
draft at the convention.
   But at a town meeting in Thomaston, Ga., he said, ``I haven't
even thought about that. I guarantee you I haven't spent 10 seconds
thinking about somebody drafting me.''
</TEXT>
