<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Lawyers     04-08 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Lawyers,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Form International Body Against Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers from 12 nations, including the
United States and Soviet Union, announced the formation Friday of a
group that will work to outlaw nuclear weapons and offer help in
disarmament programs.
   The new organization brought American, European, East bloc and
Asian jurists' associations together under one umbrella to
coordinate activities against nuclear warfare.
   Soviet, U.S. and Swedish attorneys were elected co-chairmen of
the International Lawyers Association against Nuclear Arms, or
ILANA.
   The group mirrored the International Physicians for the
Prevention of Nuclear War, which linked Soviet and U.S. doctors in
a campaign that earned them the 1985 Nobel Peace Prize.
   The jurists, ending a two-day conference, said anyone
contributing to the nuclear arms race could be held accountable in
the same way that Nazi officers were convicted of crimes against
humanity by the Nuremberg war crimes tribunal.
   Alexander Sucharev, head of the Association of Soviet Lawyers
and a former justice minister of the Russian republic, said the
ultimate goal ``is to outlaw nuclear arms ... possibly through
changes in the constitutions of our countries.''
   Sucharev, a co-chairman, said the organization also could offer
to help monitor the verification of arms control agreements.
   Speaking through a translator, he said his participation in the
founding conference reflected ``new thinking'' in Moscow.
   U.S. co-chairman Peter Weiss said the organization may help
defend arrested anti-nuclear activists and could sponsor cases at
the World Court in The Hague.
   It also could launch multinational research projects into the
legal aspects of the U.S. space defense program called ``Star
Wars'' and the possible interpretations of arms control treaties,
he said.
   The group believes that nuclear weapons violate international
laws banning the threat of indiscriminate force and the use of
weapons against non-military targets, said Weiss, a New York
attorney who also heads the Lawyers Committee on Nuclear Policy.
   ``It is ironic that the two most powerful countries in the world
rely for their security on an illegal institution, namely nuclear
weapons,'' said Weiss.
   Asked if he agreed that nuclear weapons in the Soviet arsenal
also were illegal, Sucharev said, ``the reality is that nuclear
weapons exist,'' and said that they should be outlawed.
   Co-chairman Stig Gustafsson, a member of the Swedish Parliament,
said the association will be financed by donations from its member
organizations and by contributions.
</TEXT>
