<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Namibia-Botha     04-08 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia-Botha,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African President in Namibia For Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ President P.W. Botha of South
Africa came to Windhoek with senior members of his Cabinet on
Thursday for talks with leaders of the territorial government, many
of whom are demanding abolition of all apartheid-style legislation.
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu, a prominent foe of apartheid, and other
southern African Anglican bishops also are here for a weeklong
visit that includes church services in the densely populated far
north of the territory, commonly known as Namibia.
   It is Botha's first official visit to Windhoek since June 1985,
when the unelected, multiriacial government was installed to
provide limited self-rule over the territory.
   In the ensuing three years, the so-called ``transitional
government'' failed to win international recognition, and the
United Nations continued to call for independence elections that
would include the South-West African People's Organization
guerrilla movement.
   The United Nations has designated SWAPO the ``sole and authentic
representative of the Namibian people,'' and most observers feel it
would win a U.N.-supervised election.
   During the past three years, four of the six parties in the
territorial government have grown increasingly adamant in demanding
a total break from apartheid _ South Africa's system of separate
political, social and educational structures for different racial
groups.
   Moses Katjiuonga, chairman of the eight-man transitional
Cabinet, said in an interview Thursday he and possibly other
members would quit the government if Botha rejected their proposal
for a constitution stripped of all references to race and ethnic
groups.
   He said that even if the independence question remained
unsettled for years, Namibians could promote reconciliation and
unity if they were allowed to implement the proposals for a bill of
rights and non-racial elections for regional and local governments.
   Botha must decide whether to bow at least partially to these
demands or side with those who want to retain ``group rights'' _
the phrase used in South Africa to justify racially segregated
structures.
   Group rights in Namibia are backed by the Rehoboth Basters, a
conservative mixed-race party, and by the all-white National Party
of South-West Africa, an offshoot of South Africa's governing
National Party.
   Namibian politicians say Botha is mindful of how developments
here would be viewed in South Africa, where his government is
trying to convince right-wing whites of its steadfast commitment to
group rights.
   About 88 percent of Namibia's 1.3 million people are black, 6
percent white and 6 percent mixed-race. A major source of friction
is that whites are by far the wealthiest group and are allowed to
administer their own tax system to fund all-white schools and
hospitals.
   Botha's chief representative in Namibia, Administrator-General
Louis Pienaar, said Thursday that the Pretoria government would be
willing to negotiate major changes in the tax disbursement system
and would accept for the first time the concept of regional,
non-ethnic elections. But he indicated Botha would insist on
maintaining special protections for racial minorities.
   Katjiuonga, of the transitional Cabinet, said Thursday that
SWAPO would lose some of its appeal if apartheid were eliminated
and might be induced to join negotiations on a post-independence
government.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I, defying U.N.
calls for independence. Botha says his government will not consider
the U.N. proposals as long as Cuban troops remain in neighboring
Angola aiding the Marxist government against South African-backed
rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
