<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarBomb 1stLd-Writethru a0794 04-08 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Car Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0794,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed When Car Bomb Explodes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: NEW throughout to UPDATE with witnesses telling police
another motorist put something inside car just before blast, quotes
on damage, other details. No pickup. ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN-TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb that witnesses said may have
been placed in a parked car by a passing motorist exploded
Thursday, killing a man and scattering debris over a two-block
area, police said.
   The car was engulfed in flames when firefighters arrived, said
Lt. F.D. Tacker of the Fort Worth Fire Department. The victim was
trapped inside.
   The bomb exploded shortly before 2:30 p.m., shooting flames high
into the air and scattering parts of the car over about a one-block
area.
   ``It's charred black, the roof is gone and all the doors are
blown open on it and there are no tires on it _ they've all burned
off,'' said Fire Department spokesman R.C. Knight.
   The identity of the victim was not immediately known.
   ``A couple of witnesses said another car pulled up and someone
placed some type of bomb device in the car,'' said Homicide Sgt.
Paul Kratz. ``At this point, we don't know what type of bomb it
was. Obviously it was a pretty spectacular explosion.''
   Witnesses said the victim had parked his car and walked across
the street to a barbecue stand, before returning to the vehicle.
   ``One of the medical officers told one of our people that the
guy had gotten out of his car to get a glass of iced tea and when
he got back in it exploded,'' said Fire Marshal Don Peacock.
   Investigators were trying to gather pieces of the bomb, Peacock
said.
   The car was rented on Feb. 25, Kratz said. Investigators know
the name of the person who rented the car but have not been able to
determine whether he was the victim because at least three people
had driven the car, Kratz said.
</TEXT>
