<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Meese-LatinAmerica     04-08 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Latin America,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Says Colombia Will Try To Resume Drug Extraditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco agreed on
Thursday to try to resume extraditing Colombian drug traffickers to
the United States, said U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese.
   Extraditions were suspended last year after Colombia's supreme
court, ruling on a technicality, said a 1979 extradition treaty was
unconstitutional.
   Meese and the director of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration, John Lawn, met with Barco and Colombia's minister
of justice, Enrique Mutra Low.
   Meese spoke at a news conference at the military terminal at
Bogota's El Dorado international airport Thursday before he and
Lawn left for Ecuador.
   Meese and Lawn have also visited the Dominican Republic and will
travel to Peru and Bolivia as part of a review of what Latin
American countries are doing to stop drug smuggling into the United
States.
   Extraditions are a key element of the fight against drug
smuggling, Meese said.
   The Colombian president agreed that both countries must work to
overcome the legal problems blocking further extraditions, Meese
said at the news conference.
   In response to questions, Meese rejected the idea of an
international police force to fight drugs, the suggestion that
drugs should be legalized and the possibility of U.S. troops being
sent to Colombia to fight drug traffickers.
   The United States contributes $14 million a year to Colombia for
fighting drugs.
   Colombians, often criticized in the United States for not doing
enough to fight cocaine trafficking, have pointed out that it is
Colombians who are suffering the most deaths in the war on drugs.
   Drug traffickers have killed a justice minister, an attorney
general, several judges, two newspaper editors and scores of
policemen and soldiers in the last four years.
   Drug traffickers have threatened to kill members of Colombia's
Council of State, the Bogota daily El Tiempo said Thursday.
   Last month, the Council of State decreed provisionally that
arrest orders be lifted for Pablo Escobar Gaviria, a Colombian that
U.S. narcotics agents call the world's biggest cocaine trafficker.
   The Council of State has not made its final decision on whether
or not to seek Escobar's arrest. Escobar is not charged with any
crimes in Colombia.
   The United States has asked Colombia to extradite Escobar.
   Colombia has not extradited any alleged drug traffickers to the
United States since February 1987 because the Colombian Supreme
Court last year ruled a 1979 extradition treaty invalid on a
technicality.
   Later Thursday, Meese flew to Ecuador. His plane was prevented
from landing in Quito due to heavy rain, but he detoured to
Guayaquil where he was to spend the night before traveling to
Quito, the capital, U.S. Embassy officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
