<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewDinosaur 1stLd-Writethru a0819 04-08 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Dinosaur, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0819,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Identify Previously Unknown Species</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT spelling of pygmy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skull of a prehistoric animal has been
identified as part of a previously unknown species of compact,
meat-eating dinosaur, scientists announced Thursday.
   The skull was misidentified after its discovery in 1942 in
eastern Montana by an expedition from the Cleveland Museum of
Natural History, officials said. It was in storage in the museum's
basement when it was noticed by a visiting paleontologist last year.
   The museum said the skull is from a previously unknown member of
the Tyrannosaurus rex family of dinosaurs, a ferocious meat-eating
animal that roamed the earth some 60 million years ago.
   Because of its relatively small size, the new dinosaur has been
named Nanotyrannus or ``pygmy tyrant'' by the scientists who
identified it. The Cleveland skull is believed to be the only such
specimen of the Nanotyrannus, although teeth have been found in
Montana and South Dakota.
   ``This animal is so different from any other meat-eater that it
merits its own branch of the tyrannosaur family tree,'' said Robert
T. Bakker, adjunct curator of paleontology at the University of
Colorado in Boulder.
   Bakker grew suspicious of the skull's initial identification as
a Gorgosaurus, a primitive and very common meat-eater, during a
visit to the Cleveland museum last spring. He worked with two other
scientists in determining its identity and their discovery was
disclosed in a paleontology publication this month.
   The Nanotyrannus resembled the giant Tyrannosaurus rex but was
only about one-third as large and one-tenth as heavy, the
scientists said. Bakker said the Nanotyrannus probably weighed less
than 1,000 pounds, stood about 10 feet tall, walked on its hind
legs and measured about 17 feet from nose to tail.
   Bakker compared the skull, which is about 22 inches long and 10
inches high, to the size of a brown bear's head.
   He said the Nanotyrannus had the same level of advancement in
anatomical features as the Tyrannosaurus rex, including eye sockets
that faced forward instead of sideways, a wider skull base and a
neck joint that bent downwards.
   The Nanotyrannus head was discovered during a museum field trip
to a farm in Carter County, Montana. The expedition yielded other
dinosaur skeletons in the museum's collection but no other parts of
the Nanotyrannus.
   ``It's very rare to find just the head, very rare. And I hope
the rest of it is out there,'' Bakker said after a news conference
to announce the discovery.
   Michael E. Williams, curator of vertebrate paleontology at the
museum, said there are no plans to excavate the site again.
   Bakker blamed the 40-year misidentification on a lack of
scientists.
   ``There are never enough scientists to study dinosaurs, or
crocodiles or beetles or whatever kind of critter you're talking
about,'' he said.
   The third scientist involved in the discovery with Bakker and
Williams was Philip Currie, assistant direector of the Tyrrell
Museum of Paleontology in Alberta, Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnpublishedAuction     04-08 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unpublished Auction,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maine Author Auctions Life's Work for $965</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Rosenberg isn't dead, and he obviously
isn't famous. But that didn't stop the Maine author from putting
his unpublished manuscripts up for sale Thursday, entering a market
that usually belongs to the prominent or the deceased.
   Rosenberg was not expecting to pull in the $605,000 that Franz
Kafka's love letters brought at auction _ in fact, bidding on his
works began at $2.75. Instead, he was hopeful of attracting a
publisher for his latest novel, ``Run Red Riding Hood Run.''
   So after 10 models in hooded sweatshirts simultaneously read
excerpts from his book to about 50 people in the penthouse of the
New York Hilton, Rosenberg watched as his literary properties,
including two other unpublished novels, were sold for a total of
$965.
   Rosenberg even auctioned off his collection of 30 rejection
notices from publishers for $65. Also on the block were his
dog-eared dictionary, which went for $40, various photos and
letters, and cassette tapes of his dictated notes.
   ``I'm thrilled,'' Rosenberg said after the sale. ``We did good.''
   ``I read PR releases before I read comic books,'' said
Rosenberg, 34, who freely admits the auction was nothing more than
a Barnumesque stunt aimed at getting him attention.
   ``Run Red Riding Hood Run'' has a little bit of everything:
``There's murder, there's suspense, there's black comedy,''
Rosenberg said. But, as was the case with his books on the second
Claus von Bulow trial and on his experiences at the Boston Herald,
there's no publisher.
   Rosenberg says his publicity efforts have cost him about $15,000
_ ``and it could get worse.''
</TEXT>
