<DOCNO> AP880408-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pulitzer-Complaint     04-08 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pulitzer-Complaint,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prize Winners Not Required To Break New Ground, Board Secretary
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pulitzer Prize board will look into a
complaint that an award was granted for reporting that broke no new
ground, but there is no such requirement for winners, the board
secretary said Thursday.
   A Washington magazine, the National Journal, asserted that
Philadelphia Inquirer reporter Tom Weiner's reporting on a secret
Pentagon budget was built on an earlier story in the Journal by
David C. Morrison and broke no new ground. Weiner won the Pulitzer
Prize for national reporting last week.
   The description of the prize does not require that the winner
break new ground, board secretary Robert Christopher said. The
reporter must only represent ``a distinguished example of reporting
on national affairs,'' Christopher said.
   Meanwhile, Harper's magazine publisher John R. MacArthur on
Thursday also criticized the award, noting that one of Weiner's
stories was accompanied by an annotated document similar to a
feature Morrison did for the January 1987 issue of Harper's.
   ``Certainly, David Morrison did a lot of work and a lot of very
brilliant work on this story,'' said MacArthur, who called The
Associated Press to make his complaint.
   ``It doesn't seem quite right that the Inquirer gets a Pulitzer
Prize unless originality has nothing to do with prize giving these
days,'' he said.
   He said he did not plan to write the Pulitzer board, although he
endorsed the Journal's complaint.
   Christopher said that only he and the board chairman, David
Laventhol, had seen the complaint.
   Laventhol, president of Times Mirror Co., which owns the
National Journal, a 5,000-circulation weekly, did not respond
immediately to a telephoned request for comment.
   Christopher said board members would discuss the complaint once
they had read it, probably next week.
   The Inquirer's deputy managing editor, Jim Naughton, maintained
that ``The series and Tim's work generally has broken new ground,
whatever that means.''
   ``I know it had a reaction,'' Naughton said. ``I know it caused
Congress to re-examine the situation and to ask for more
information from the Pentagon. I guess I would call that breaking
ground.''
   Weiner said he interviewed more than 100 people around the
country and was ``knee-deep in this before I saw David's work.''
</TEXT>
