<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Argentina     04-08 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Argentina,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidents Promise `No Nuclear Race,' Move Toward Joint Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidents Jose Sarney of Brazil and
Raul Alfonsin of Argentina signed accords on Thursday aimed at
further propelling their nations, the largest in South America,
toward becoming a joint economic force.
   They said their venture also ends speculation of a Latin
``nuclear race.''
   Alfonsin, in Brazil on a three-day visit, and Sarney signed
three agreements eliminating tariffs on cars, automotive parts and
more than 130 food products.
   The two neighbors began work in 1985 on a wide-ranging plan to
unify their economies and create a South American Common Market.
   Their project has been slowed by their struggling economies and
huge foreign debts, but progress has been evident.
   With the signing of nearly 25 agreements in all, trade between
Argentina and Brazil jumped from $900 million in 1985 to $1.5
billion in 1987.
   In addition, hundreds of students and professionals from both
countries now exchange information and work together at long-term
joint projects in aviation, transportation, scientific technology
and agriculture.
   For years, Spanish-speaking Argentina, with a population
exceeding 31 million, and Portuguese-speaking Brazil, with more
than 143 million people, were archrivals. They put aside
differences to become stronger economically.
   Sarney in 1985 became Brazil's first civilian leader after 21
years of military rule.
   Alfonsin became president of Argentina in December 1983, the
nation's first elected civilian leader following nearly eight years
of military juntas.
   Sarney said Thursday, ``We are taking new steps in the fruitful
and promising path of integration. We are widening our capability
to compete in the world. We have never had such an excellent
relationship.''
   Alfonsin arrived in the capital city of Brasilia on Wednesday.
It is the seventh time in three years the two presidents have met.
   During this trip, Uruguay was also officially incorporated in
the economic integration after a quick trip by President Julio
Maria Sanguinetti. He met with the other two presidents Wednesday.
   Uruguay has taken part in most of the talks between Brazil and
Argentina and it was expected to join the economic group,
especially since the three countries share a border.
   The nuclear issue has been a touchy subject in the integration
effort. Both Brazil and Argentina in the past two years were
reported to have developed the technology to enrich uranium, a key
step in building a bomb. But both countries say their nuclear
programs are for peaceful ends.
   On Friday, Sarney will take Alfonsin to Brazil's nuclear
experiment center of Aramar, outside of Sao Paulo in the southeast.
Last year, Sarney visited Argentina's nuclear installations.
   ``We are ending any suspicions that nuclear development in
Brazil and Argentina is not linked to peaceful purposes,'' said
Alfonsin.
   Added Sarney, ``A year ago it was hard to imagine that a
Brazilian president would visit a nuclear plant in Argentina.''
   Foreign Ministry officials said details were worked out during
this visit for a future nuclear accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0202 </DOCNO>
