<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RapeOrdeal     04-08 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape Ordeal,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Who Waited for Key to Apartment at Scene of Rape Is
Dismissed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran police officer was dismissed
Thursday after a city board found he broke department rules by
waiting nearly 30 minutes for a key while a 12-year-old girl was
being raped inside an apartment.
   James Horka was charged with breaking 10 department rules
stemming from the Dec. 21 incident.
   The Police and Fire Commission found him in violation of five
rules, but dismissed the most serious charge, failing to request
assistance at the scene.
   Horka said he expected to be cleared of wrongdoing and
reinstated after an appeal.
   ``I still think I did the right thing,'' he said. ``No one got
killed.''
   The disciplinary hearings were begun shortly after the Dec. 20
incident, in which Horka and two other officers responded to a call
of home invasion.
   They waited outside almost 30 minutes with the girl's frantic
mother for the landlord to bring a key, rather than breaking in to
rescue the girl.
   A supervisor told him to push the apartment door in if
necessary, Horka testified, but he did not interpret that as an
order. He maintained that he did not break into the apartment upon
arriving because he feared the assailant might harm the girl and
her 10-year-old brother.
   Four officers later broke down the door and arrested the
assailant, police said.
   The two officers who accompanied Horka also have been scheduled
for disciplinary hearings.
   Horka's attorney, Thomas Tyrrell, said immediately after the
decision was announced that he would seek an administrative review
of the decision from the Cook County circuit courts.
   A two-thirds majority was required on each violation. Board
member Guy Eveland found Horka in violation of eight of the 10
rules cited; Chairman Edward Fitzgerald, five; board member Leroy
McGinnis, one.
   The five violations were conduct unbecoming to an officer,
unsatisfactory performance, improper filing of a report, abuse of
command and violating departmental rules.
   Horka, a decorated Vietnam veteran and 14-year veteran of the
force, remained on active duty during the weeks-long hearing.
Tyrrell said he would ask the courts for reinstatement to the force
and any pay lost due to any suspension or dismissal.
</TEXT>
