<HEAD>Three Boys Injured As 9-Year-Old Crashes Van in Chase on I-95</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A van in which three boys apparently were
trying to drive to Florida crashed into a guardrail on an
interstate highway with a 9-year-old at the wheel as police gave
chase, authorities said.
   The boy was critically injured, and his 14-year-old brother and
a 13-year-old friend, all from suburban Trenton, N.J., also were
hurt in the accident about 5 a.m. just outside Baltimore.
   Earlier, Maryland State Police received a call that a van was
being driven erratically on the southbound lanes of the Delaware
Turnpike, just across the Maryland line.
   The van got past guards at a toll plaza and was seen by Maryland
State Trooper Eric Harbold speeding on I-95. Harbold tried to
signal the van to stop, but it accelerated to speeds of up to 100
mph, police said.
   The driver then lost control, and the van veered across the
median strip, slamming into a guardrail and overturning on the
northbound lanes about three miles from White Marsh, police said.
   The boys were taken by ambulance to Johns Hopkins Hospital in
Baltimore. The driver was in critical but stable condition and his
brother was lasping in and out of consciousness, police said. The
13-year-old was not seriously hurt.
   The van belonged to the parents of the 13-year-old, said police
spokesman Chuck Jackson.
   Investigators said they believed the boys were heading to
Florida without permission.
   No names were released.
