<DATELINE>ELON MOREH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli girl's death in
a clash with Arabs was a watershed in four months of violence,
radicalizing Jewish settlers. Many fear it presages a more savage
conflict in the occupied lands.
   The killing of 15-year-old Tirza Porat in the village of Beita
on Wednesday shocked the nation, but the general feeling was that
it had been a matter of time until Jews living in these disputed
hills became victims of the Arab rebellion.
   Although it was uncertain Friday whether Tirza was killed by
Palestinians or a stray shot from an Israeli's rifle, many settlers
blamed their government _accusing it of creating an atmosphere of
leniency toward Arabs that made the confrontation possible.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decline of oil wealth and easy credit has
sapped the energy of the Middle East arms-buying spree of the early
1980s, contributing to a $16 billion-a-year drop in worldwide arms
imports, the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency said Friday.
   ``As late as 1984, the trend in arms imports by developing
nations was sharply up in almost all years, fueled by ambitious
force improvement programs, financed, in most cases by rising oil
prices and easy credit,'' agency's annual study of global arms
sales said.
   The oil glut and the Third World's debt problems have forced a
decline in arms buying. Besides, many of the countries who bought
all those weapons in the early 1980s don't need any more now, the
report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
