<1ST_LINE>a i PM-SriLanka-India Adv15   04-08 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka-India, Adv 15,0856</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs April 15 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>India's Peacekeeping Mission in Sri Lanka Proving Difficult</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India sent its soldiers to this small
island nation with a declaration of noble intentions: to end a
murderous ethnic war, supervise a peace accord, then get out.
   That was eight months ago.
   The killings have not stopped, the biggest Tamil rebel group
quickly reneged on the Indian-arranged peace accord and the Indian
peacekeeping force of 3,000 soldiers has swelled to more than
50,000.
   Tamil rebels, seeking autonomy or independence for their ethnic
minority on the island once known as Ceylon, are still massacring
civilians from the Sinhalese majority and recently started turning
their guns, axes and arson torches on the previously unthreatened
Moslem minority.
   In addition, as direct or indirect results of the accord, Tamils
are killing fellow Tamils, Sinhalese are killing fellow Sinhalese,
and some young Moslems are taking up arms against Tamils.
   ``There appears to be a strange paradox here: the intensity of
the violence being directly proportional to the increase in the
number of Indian troops,'' the independent newspaper The Island
said in a recent editorial.
   ``It is time that every citizen of this country told the Indians
that if they cannot do their jobs fast enough they got to get out
and leave our problems to us.''
   But defenders of the peace accord say it still offers the best,
if not the only, hope for ending ethnic mayhem on a beautiful
island that was building a booming tourist industry until 1983.
That was the year militant Tamils, chafing under economic and
political domination by the Sinhalese, exploded their cause into a
guerrilla war that has now claimed more than 8,000 lives.
   ``We couldn't have done anything different,'' said Gamini
Dissanayake, Sri Lanka's minister of land development and a key
negotiator of the accord.
   For the first time, he said, the accord specifically and
publicly provided ``a solid understanding'' that the
Sinhalese-dominated government would share power with the Tamils, a
concept that he said was ``just an abstraction in the past.''
   The accord guarantees some autonomy to the Tamils, provided the
rebels surrender their arms.
   However, the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people, fear the accord makes too many concessions to the
Tamils, who account for 18 percent of the population.
   An underground organization of ultranationalist Sinhalese has
assassinated at least 150 people who supported the accord or were
prominent members of President Junius R. Jayewardene's United
National Party.
   The largest Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, are engaged in internecine warfare with smaller Tamil
guerrilla groups that support the peace accord.
   Moslems, who comprise about 7 percent of Sri Lanka's population,
became targets of Tamil rebels trying to dominate the Eastern
Province, where the population is about equally divided among
Tamils, Sinhalese and Moslems.
   Both the Tamils and the Sinhalese are descendents of people who
migrated from India centuries ago, but most Tamils are Hindus, most
Sinhalese are Buddhists, and they speak different languages. The
Moslems trace their religion and ancestry to Arab seafarers.
   Apart from the continuing violence, there is also a feeling that
time is running out to enforce the peace accord.
   Under Sri Lanka's constitution, the 82-year-old Jayewardene has
just 10 months left in office and cannot run again, unless he
pushes through an amendment or a new interpretation of his tenure.
   ``He, President Jayewardene, is about the only man who can put
an end to the situation,'' said National Security Minister Lalith
Athulathmudali.
   Jayewardene's own Cabinet is divided over the implementation of
the accord and the Indian military presence. Although the
ministers' public remarks tend to be fairly circumspect, their
views are well-known _ and can be measured by the bodyguards around
them.
   A dozen men guard the corridor leading to the office used by
Dissanayake, point man in the efforts at reconciliation and
therefore a top target for assassination by extremists in his own
Sinhalese community. The more hawkish Athulathmudali has only a
single guard in sight at his official residence.
   J.N. Dixit, the Indian high commissioner, or ambassador, who
once moved freely around Colombo with a single bodyguard, now has
what he calls ``my rather embarrassing contingent of five gunmen.''
   Dixit, a career diplomat, maintained that India did not take on
more than it could handle in Sri Lanka.
   He said Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's government in New Delhi
considered various things that might go wrong with the accord,
including the Tamil rebels' refusal to surrender arms.
   Apart from its regional role as South Asia's geographic and
military giant, India was drawn into Sri Lanka by pressure from its
own politically powerful Tamil minority of 60 million.
   By the Indian government's account, about 400 Indian soldiers
have died in Sri Lanka since the still-unfinished Oct. 10 offensive
to disarm the Tamil Tigers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs April 15</NOTE>
