<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:ArtIsland Adv15   04-08 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Art Island, Adv 15,0785</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, April 15 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Art Island Is Cultural Oasis in West Germany's Industry Belt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLZHEIM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Europe's most talked about
new art museums is a pastoral island that boasts Rembrandts, Roman
ruins and a resident sculptor who fires cannon salutes to Mother
Nature.
   Hombroich Island is a quiet cultural oasis in the heart of West
Germany's most heavily industrialized area.
   ``Art and nature come together at Hombroich,'' says Karl-Heinz
Mueller, a wealthy businessman who owns the Erft River island,
about nine miles west of Duesseldorf.
   ``Hombroich is timeless. It doesn't really have a purpose
because it is not static. Nature constantly changes, as will the
collection,'' says Mueller, a 51-year-old university dropout and
admirer of Eastern philosophy.
   Hombroich is the home of Mueller's private collection of
Rembrandt etchings, Paul Cezanne watercolors, sculptures by
Constantin Brancusi and Alberto Giacometti, Lovis Corinth
portraits, African masks, ancient Cambodian idols and prehistoric
pottery.
   The island has also been the site of open-air concerts by such
world-famous classical musicians as violinist Pinchas Zukerman and
pianist Svyatoslav Richter.
   Mueller's property is also an archaelogical treasure.
   Experts say the ruins of two Roman villas lie beneath the soil,
and there is also evidence of one of the earliest Stone Age
settlements in nNorthern Europe.
   The exhibition buildings are reached by labyrinthine paths that
lead visitors past shrubs and trees transplanted from such far-away
places as Japan and Iran. Hombroich's resident waterfowl float near
a foot bridge spanning the river.
   Ruminating on the links between art and nature is a favored
preoccupation of Mueller, and has led him to adopt some
unconventional art principles.
   He rejects the conventional practice of installing
climate-control systems as a means of preserving his valuable
collection.
   ``The pictures must have a chance to have their own lives, just
like us humans,'' Mueller said in a telephone interview.
   ``What would be better for a human being _ to live in an
air-conditioned room for 1,000 years, or to live normally? Besides,
paintings can live hundreds of years without climate control.''
   Mueller also shuns the normal museum practice of hanging plaques
near artworks to identify their creator and titles. He says signs
would be a distraction.
   Like Hombroich's lush vegetation, works of art also sprout, grow
and bloom on Mueller's 42 acres of Erft River property.
   Sculptor Anatol Herzfeld works nearly every day inside a shed on
the banks of the Erft, producing wooden and metal objects that are
scattered about the island and blend with the landscape.
   He periodically fires grass and flower seeds from his
hand-built, scrap-metal cannon in what he calls a symbolic salute
to nature.
   Since the island first opened in May 1987, tens of thousands of
people have visited, including artists, musicians and intellectuals
who Mueller says are enchanted as much by the serene setting as by
the art collection.
   Visitors pay about $9 to visit the island, but Mueller says
profit is not his primary motive.
   A speculator in industrial real estate, he purchased the Erft
River property in 1982 as a home for his expanding art collection.
He chose Hombroich Island after a long search.
   ``You look for years for the right property to do something
special, and suddenly you find it. It was the law of chance,'' says
Mueller, who refuses to say how much the property cost.
   Mueller hired noted German sculptor Irwin Heerich to design
Hombroich's cubist art pavilions.
   Gotthard Graubner, a prominent West German painter whose work is
also among the Hombroich collection, advises Mueller on his art
purchases.
   Another important partner for Mueller is Bernhard Korte, a
landscape gardener who helped transform Hombroich from a jungle of
wild undergrowth.
   Mueller went into business for himself in 1958, after quitting
university because ``formal studying makes me nervous.''
   ``I started out with zero money,'' he says. ``It took 10 years
until I was able to buy my first art piece. I bought what I liked.
You buy and buy and buy, and suddenly you have a lot of paintings.''
   Mueller says his purchase of Hombroich Island means that his art
collection will be evolving in new directions which he himself
can't yet imagine.
   ``At first I had a collection. It grew. Now I have an island,
where everything has its own importance _ the collection, nature
and the buildings,'' he says.
   ``You do your work, and it changes with what you feel is right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri April 15</NOTE>
