<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-TheAttic Adv11   04-08 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-The Attic, Adv 11,0866</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, April 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Hiding of Anne Frank' Based on Different Side of Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miep Gies, the woman who helped hide the Frank
family from the Nazis, says it was a long time before she could
bring herself to read ``The Diary of Anne Frank,'' even though it
was she who saved it.
   ``Mr. Frank always said to me, `Miep, read it, read it,' and I
said, `No, I can't,' because I was in fear of what I'd read,'' said
Mrs. Gies in halting English. ``But after the second edition, I
finally read it, but only when I'm alone.
   ``Then there grow up something. It was (as) if Anna come into
me. I heard her cry. She was with me. She was here, in here,'' she
said, touching her heart, her eyes welling up with tears. ``For I'm
so very, very happy.''
   Mrs. Gies is the author of her own book, ``Anne Frank
Remembered,'' written with Alison Leslie Gold. It is the basis of
the TV movie ``The Attic: The Hiding of Anne Frank,'' airing next
Sunday on CBS.
   In a tender scene in the movie, young Jan Gies suggests to Miep
that marriage will keep her from being deported to her native
Austria from German-occupied Holland.
   ``All we need do is find a handsome, intelligent, charming
gentleman of Dutch birth, sound of mind and body, financially
solvent with a fairly promising future in his chosen profession,
offering you comfort and security in your twilight years,'' says
Jan, played by Huub Stapel.
   Mrs. Gies, 79, was joined by her 82-year-old husband at a recent
news conference. They agreed that the scene, as well as the rest of
the movie, was quite accurate.
   They were joined by Mary Steenburgen, who portrays Mrs. Gies.
The movie also stars Paul Scofield in a rare television appearance
playing Otto Frank. Mrs. Gies, an employee of Frank, helped hide
his family and four other people in the attic above their offices
for more than two years, until the group was discovered by the
Nazis.
   Anne died in a concentration camp, but her father survived and
later published the diary Anne kept while in hiding. It became one
of the most powerful anti-war statements ever written. It was Mrs.
Gies who preserved Anne's diary and gave it to Otto Frank after the
war.
   Mrs. Gies said she never had any desire to write a book, because
she felt nothing could be more eloquent than the diary. But she was
convinced by Gold that a history should be written of what it was
like in Amsterdam outside the attic during that time.
   ``You must understand,'' Mrs. Gies said, ``it was very painful
for us, but after many difficult _ we gave her the information for
that reason.''
   Lisa Jacobs plays the bright, mischievous Anne, for whom
imprisonment in the attic was especially difficult. Mrs. Gies
fondly recalled Anne as a ``very charming child, lively, but very
curious.''
   ``She always ask us and ask us what happen outside. ... After a
while my husband tell me, you must not tell her all the terrible
things, because it is terrible enough to be in hiding. But she
always ask in a different way until she get the answer she want,
and I lost.''
   Mrs. Gies praised Jacobs' portrayal _ ``She did it very good.''
Steenburgen, she said, played her ``the way I looked to myself: No
panic in a difficult situation. She was right. She was me.''
   The movie is from director John Erman and screenwriter William
Hanley, who teamed on one of the best TV movies of last season,
``When the Time Comes.'' Erman also directed ``Who Will Love My
Children?'' and ``An Early Frost.'' Hanley's credits include the
screenplay ``Something About Amelia.''
   Rather than focusing on life in the attic, the movie portrays
the courage of Dutch citizens who defied the Nazis. Mrs. Gies
insisted there was nothing especially heroic about what she did.
   ``We only did our human duty _ help people who need help. But
there were heroes,'' she said, ``the eight people in hiding.
   ``I can say out of my heart I am so happy that I could give the
diary to Mr. Frank, and Mr. Frank could give the diary to the
world. That was good.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   WHITHER PAULEY? _ With Jane Pauley out for the week that ended
April 1, NBC's ``Today'' show dropped to a virtual tie with ABC's
``Good Morning America'' after a 19-week winning streak. Both shows
had a rating of 4.6, a percentage of total homes with televisions.
``Today'' had a 20 share to GMA's 19 _ that's the percentage of the
audience actually watching TV. Maria Shriver substituted for Pauley
that week. Bryant Gumbel is off this week, and Phil Donahue is
substituting. ``CBS This Morning'' struggles along in third place.
Last week it had a 2.3 rating and a 10 share.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, April 11</NOTE>
