<1ST_LINE>s i BC-VanishingVenetians Adv17-2Takes   04-08 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Vanishing Venetians, Adv 17-2 Takes,0874</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Venetians Abandon City to Tourists and the Rich</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the world's most enchanting cities
was founded 15 centuries ago by frightened citizens who sought
refuge among its 118 islets in the Gulf of Venice from the
southward invasion of Lombards.
   Now their 20th-century descendents are fleeing in the other
direction, heading back north to the Italian mainland and
abandoning their lagoon city in the northern Adriatic Sea to hordes
of tourists and real estate speculators.
   Venice has become too expensive for its natives and those still
left say it is losing its soul.
   As Venetians flee, the city is trying desperately to save itself
from high tides, floods, polluted canals, erosion and decay.
   After spending hundreds of millions of dollars provided by
special national legislation, planners have come up with plans _
after 20 years of striving _ for movable dikes and sophisticated
sewers to stop the lagoon's green-black waters from doing further
damage.
   The initiative to do something took root after a disastrous
flood in 1966 and the cry of ``Save Venice'' went up. Art lovers
from around the world pitched in to rescue palaces, churches and
paintings from the annual high tides.
   But no one came up with a ``save the Venetians'' campaign and
most descendents of one of the world's most glorious republics
don't live in palaces on the Grand Canal.
   They can put up with stench from garbage and refuse in the
canals, which also serve as sewers, and the winter floods _ even
the summer floods of tourists.
   It is the lack of affordable housing that's forcing Venice's
proud, sea-loving natives to the Italian mainland.
   Alarmed by the loss of regular customers, the city's bakers
organized a conference this winter to discuss the exodus.
   A report prepared by a provincial agency informed the bakers
that in 1951 Venice had 175,000 people, the most ever in modern
times. Last year, the number was down to 83,000 and about one-fifth
of those are older than 60.
   The report predicted by the year 2015 Venice could have only
20,000 permanent residents.
   ``If we go ahead at this rate, they'll be zero,'' said Giuliano
Zanon, a Venetian who wrote the report.
   Butcher shops, grocery stores, carpenters and plumbers have been
closing along the city's narrow, zigzagging streets. Popping up
everywhere _ sometimes four, five or six to a street _ are shops
selling nothing but Carnival masks _ in gold, ceramic, wood,
face-sized and pocket-sized _ as souvenirs of the Mardi Gras
festivities that pack the city with outsiders every winter.
   The mask shops have become a symbol for Venetians who say the
loss of the city's natives is robbing Venice of something just as
precious as its classic paintings and its mosaic-studded Byzantine
basilica ceilings.
   ``Venice's soul is emptying out. It's becoming a Disneyland, a
spiritually poor one,'' said Gianluigi Casini, an architect who has
helped restore canal-side palaces dating back to the 7th-century
beginning of rule by the doges.
   ``When I was a boy, all the kids would be playing in the
piazzas. Now there are few kids,'' said Casini, who at 34 is one of
a dwindling number of young Venetians.
   ``Only old people stay, those who can't go away. There are so
many empty houses. ... (Yet) most of my friends have gone ... for
lack of houses.''
   He lives with his parents in Santa Croce, one of Venice's six
historic districts.
   Some of Casini's friends, married or pursuing professions, moved
to Mestre, on the other side of the 2.5-mile causeway going out of
Venice.
   Mestre, which had about 50,000 people when Casini was born, now
serves as a bedroom for a few thousand people who commute to Venice
to work as hotel maids, souvenir sellers and waiters. Its
population now is about 250,000, triple that of Venice's historic
center.
   Casini is thinking about moving.
   ``I'd like to stay, but it's just not possible.''
   Casini, who supplements his architect's earning by teaching art
history in a Mestre high school, explained that he can't afford
Venice's rents, which are the lire equivalent of $675 to $975 a
month for a two-room apartment.
   By law, apartments should rent for far less under the city's
rent-control program. But as elsewhere in Italy, landlords prefer
to keep apartments vacant hoping for a foreigner or an Italian rich
enough to pay illegal high rents.
   A nighttime ride down the Grand Canal turns up many darkened
apartments. Some belong to foreigners or the rich who come from
Milan, 165 miles away, for vacations or weekends.
   Many other houses are in no shape to live in. Waters lapping at
the front door and sea breezes drifting by the balcony may inspire
poetry, but flooding and salty air constantly erode foundations and
beams.
   Restoration, especially of historic buildings, is more costly in
Venice, chiefly because supplies must come by barge or by porters
who handle small loads on carts in carless Venice.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
