<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-VanishingVenetians Adv17-1stAdd   04-08 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Vanishing Venetians, Adv 17-1st Add,0533</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>VENICE: carless Venice.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In the last few years, however, some young Venetians have taken
advantage of government-subsidized mortgages to buy properties, and
the city has bought many buildings to rent out.
   ``But the city can't buy all the houses,'' Mayor Casellati said.
   Not all Venetians are planning to leave.
   Gianfranco Tagliapietra, who runs a camera shop, said his
teen-age daughter is looking forward to making money in the tourist
business when she's old enough.
   Because of the exodus of Venetians, skilled laborers must be
brought in from the mainland.
   ``To restore a house you have to sell a house'' is a Venetian
byword.
   At the same time, the easy spending of tourists drives up prices
for goods in stores.
   For example, natives complain that a pair of shoes that sell for
50,000 lire ($42) in Mestre are twice that in Venice. Fruit and
vegetables generally cost about 30 percent more in Venice than in
the pricier neighborhoods of Rome.
   ``It's the middle class that's going away,'' said Mayor Antonio
Casellati.
   ``If someone comes back, it's the rich.''
   Disappearing with the exodus is the Venice of old, when
everybody knew everybody else, Casellati added.
   ``In the old days, a doge would live next to a poor person;
Venice's classes were all mixed together. All this is being lost.''
   Even some of Venice's gondoliers live in Mestre.
   Zanon, who wrote the report on the declining population, said
exodus that is siphoning off people has an ironic twist: it began
because the city was too crowded.
   ``If the city had a plan, they could have done something,'' he
said. ``But they didn't do anything.''
   After the 1966 flood, tourism took off, perhaps inspired by the
worry that Venice some day might be swamped for good by the tides.
   By the 1970s, real estate speculators started to move in,
betting that the tourism boom would last. It became fashionable for
big name companies, like Fiat, to restore palaces for headquarters,
banquets or exhibitions.
   ``We Venetians are at our limits to transmit culture; we are
outnumbered by tourists,'' Zanon said. ``My daughter doesn't even
speak Venetian,'' a dialect more lilting than a gondolier's song.
   ``The sadness about Venice,'' he added, ``is not the pollution''
_ or decay. ``It's the politicians who don't do anything.''
   The mayor said he'd like to see a law that would force
real-estate buyers to live in what they bought or rent their
properties for several years only to Venetians. But he acknowledges
that might be impossible in a free-market society.
   In the last few years, however, some young Venetians have taken
advantage of government-subsidized mortgages to buy properties, and
the city has bought many buildings to rent out.
   ``But the city can't buy all the houses,'' Mayor Casellati said.
   Not all Venetians are planning to leave.
   Gianfranco Tagliapietra, who runs a camera shop, said his
teen-age daughter is looking forward to making money in the tourist
business when she's old enough.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
