<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-08 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0570</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than four years of courtroom battles,
the bitter feud between Texaco Inc. and Pennzoil Co. ended quietly
with a series of bank transactions that put $3 billion in a
Pennzoil account.
   The wire transfers to Texas Commerce Bank-Houston began at 10:03
a.m. CDT Thursday. Ten minutes, four transactions and $3 billion
later, the transfer was complete.
   Texaco agreed to pay Pennzoil $3 billion to end the litigation
stemming from its acquisition of Getty Oil and allow the White
Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant to emerge from bankruptcy protection.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of the New York Stock Exchange
approved a proposal to boost the capital requirements for the
specialist firms it relies on to maintain orderly conditions for
trading specific stocks.
   The proposal, which now goes to the Securities and Exchange
Commission for approval, is one of a series of steps the exchange
has taken since the October stock market crash to stengthen the
financial market.
   Under the suggested changes approved Thursday, a specialist firm
must show it can meet, with its own liquid assets, a minimum
capital requirement of $1 million or be able to buy 15,000 shares
of each common stock in which it makes a market, whichever is
greater.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers who have pinched pennies in recent months loosened
their purse strings in March, giving many of the nation's largest
general retailers a strong month. But Wall Street analysts, noting
that sales lagged at other stores, warned Thursday that shoppers
may return to their more cautious ways.
   Storeowners and analysts attributed the better-than-expected
results to the early Easter holiday, which gave consumers an
incentive to get their spring shopping done.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Working indoors may be hazardous to your health
after all, suggests a study that says modern, energy efficient
buildings may significantly increase the risk of communicable
respiratory infections.
   The study examined the incidence of influenza and other
respiratory illnesses among about 400,000 trainees at four Army
training centers in the southeast and south-central United States
from October 1982 to September 1986. But the researchers said the
findings may apply to office buildings and other structures
designed for maximum energy efficiency.
   The study was published in Friday's edition of the Journal of
the American Medical Association.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors led by Britain's Brian C. Beazer
extended their $1.7-billion hostile bid for Koppers Co. until April
15, when a federal court ruling is due on whether the offer
violates securities laws.
   Beazer said Thursday he was shocked that Koppers board of
directors has not yet given shareholders any advice on the
$60-a-share offer, which has been on the table for two weeks.
   The board declared as inadequate Beazer's previous offers of
$45-a-share and $56-a-share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Chrysler Corp.'s 49 United
Auto Workers union locals gave bargainers approval to seek a
contract mirroring job-protecting pacts with the nation's two
largest automakers when they begin talks with Chrysler April 18.
   ``We will take the pattern agreement and as closely as possible
fit those provisions (to) the Chrysler agreement,'' UAW Vice
President Marc Stepp, who heads the union's Chrysler department,
said after the two-day meeting closed Thursday afternoon.
</TEXT>
