<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0458</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters union and the trucking industry
have reworked a tentative contract to shift some wage gains to
pension and other fringe benefit increases and unfreeze wages for
part-time ``casual'' workers, officials said.
   As presented Thursday to representatives from 277 Teamster
locals meeting in Chicago, the new National Master Freight
Agreement would provide annual 35-cents-an-hour wage gains this
year and again in 1989 and 1990 to some 200,000 workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal budget director James C. Miller III
pushed the idea of turning over the Postal Service to private
companies, as about 100 picketing postal workers accused him of
trying to destroy the U.S. mail.
   New Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, appearing at the same
meeting Thursday, opposed the privatization idea and called for
greater discretion for the service to manage its finances and set
rates. Picketers said they had no dispute with Frank.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An employee for the Merrill Lynch financial
services company who was about to be fired walked into the firm's
office and fatally shot his boss, officer manager George Cook,
according to police.
   Cook was pronounced dead Thursday at Massachusetts General
Hospital.
   Witnesses said the suspect, Lonnie Gilchrist, was wrestled to
the floor by other employees after firing several shots in the
office. He was arrested and charged with homicide, police said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners continue to own just under 1
percent of U.S. agricultural land, slightly more than the level of
a year ago, the Agriculture Department reported.
   The department's Economic Research Service said Thursday its
1987 year-end review of reports under the Agricultural Foreign
Investment Disclosure Act found 12.5 million acres of agricultural
land in foreign hands, 202,000 acres more than reported in 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barclays PLC, a major British bank, said it would
raise about $1.72 billion to expand business by offering its
stockholders the opportunity to buy new shares.
   But a spokeswoman in New York denied rumors Thursday that the
bank was raising money to persue a friendly acquisition of Irving
Bank Corp., a New York bank holding company resisting a hostile
takeover from rival Bank of New York Co.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices worked their way higher in an erratic session
Thursday, getting a bit more mileage out of Wednesday's strong
rally. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had gained
64.16 points Wednesday, edged up another 0.50 to 2,062.17.
   The dollar and bond prices finished lower. Gold rose in value.
   Oil futures prices put on a late rally and broke past $17 a
barrel.
</TEXT>
