<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retailers Note Healthy March Sales, Stocks Climb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the nation's major retailers have notched healthy sales
gains in March, while the stock market wavered amid a mid-week
advance.
   The early Easter holiday helped the March retail sales reported
by major retailers, experts said Thursday.
   But although sales were strong for many, including F.W.
Woolworth Co. with a 29 percent jump over March 1987, there were
some exceptions. The nation's largest retailer, Sears, Roebuck and
Co. reported its sales rose just 1.5 percent during the month.
   Analysts said the stores with lackluster sales suffered from
general consumer caution.
   ``The shift in the Easter calendar should have helped in many
cases to lift sales, but we're still in a very sluggish
environment,'' said Thomas Tashjian, an analyst with the investment
firm Seidler Amdec Securities Inc. in Los Angeles.
   Consumers have spent cautiously since early last year, and
analysts predict they will remain tight-fisted for at least the
first part of 1988.
   In the financial markets on Thursday, stock prices managed to
move higher in an erratic session and add to Wednesday's strong
gain.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had gained 64.16
points Wednesday, edged up 0.50 to 2,062.17. Over the past three
days, the Dow Jones average has gained 81.47 points.
   New signs of stability in the dollar have boosted stock prices
around the world. The Tokyo stock market climbed Thursday to new
highs, having recovered all the ground it lost in last year's crash.
   But the U.S. bond market slipped. Prices of long-term government
bonds declined slightly, pushing their yields up to the 8.75
percent range.
   Oil prices climbed steadily, piercing the $17-a-barrel level in
advance of an important meeting this weekend of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</TEXT>
