<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     04-08 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise Above $17 a Barrel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have edged back above the
$17-a-barrel level in moderate trading, recouping losses recorded
earlier in the week.
   Analysts and traders said the market appeared calm Thursday
ahead of an OPEC committee meeting scheduled to begin this weekend
in Vienna, Austria, even though there have been reports of trader
nervousness.
   Contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, rose 25 cents per barrel to $17.06.
   Among refined products, wholesale heating oil for May delivery
rose 0.39 cent a gallon to 45.73 cents, and wholesale unleaded
gasoline for May rose 0.40 cent a gallon to 48.82 cents.
Longer-term contracts also rose.
   ``We had a very steady and constructive market that continued up
all day,'' said Bob Baker, senior energy analyst at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``The fundamentals look good _ demand keeps edging up, and OPEC
is not overproducing,'' he said.
   Traders and analysts said the session's buyers included refiners
who stepped up their purchases as prices inched above the
$17-a-barrel level.
   ``They saw that the market was getting too high, too quickly, so
they speeded up their purchases,'' noted Madison Galbraith, a
trader at Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   In addition, a large money management firm in Chicago reportedly
purchased 3,000 May contracts for crude, a move that was believed
to have absorbed much of the selling in the market.
   The upcoming OPEC meeting has not stirred much nervousness among
traders. Most believe the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries' pricing committee will not take much constructive action
at the April 9 meeting.
   Some market participants had hoped the 13-nation cartel would
act aggressively to stabilize prices and enforce production limits
to curb excessive supplies. Baker said the group likely would only
``issue a bland statement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
