<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BlindSpots     04-08 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blind Spots,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Product Electronically Illuminates Driver's Blind Spot</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Minnesota entrepreneur hopes a computerized
sonar device is the answer for illuminating the rearward blind
spots that plague drivers of bulky trucks and recreational vehicles.
   The blind-spot scanner, which will which cost $400 to $550
depending on the size of the vehicle using it, signals the driver
when a vehicle slips into the ``black hole'' by the back wheels of
a tractor-trailer or other big truck, out of sight of the rear-view
mirror.
   Marketing the ``Vehicle Blind Spot Alert'' is Bill Bartodziej of
Edina, an insurance salesman whose work made him aware of a need
for such a device.
   Many of his clients are truckers who repeatedly have told him of
problems stemming from cars that move into their blind spot, one of
the most common causes of accidents, said Bartodziej, 47.
   When a truck attempts to turn or change lanes with a car in the
blind spot, the results can be fatal for those in the unseen
vehicle and expensive for the trucker's insurer.
   The blind-spot detector employs sensors are attached to both
sides of the vehicle and wired to a small computer on a metal box
fitted below the dash. Two small red lights placed on top of the
windshield indicate whether another vehicle is in the blind spot _
the left light blinks on when a car slips into the left blind spot,
and vice-versa.
   The device also beeps when the turning signal is turned on and a
vehicle is in the blind spot.
   ``It's made me a better driver,'' Bartodziej said of the
demonstration model he's used in his van for several months. ``It's
made me more alert that there are people around me.''
   Motor carriers will be the first big target market for the newly
formed Freeway Technology Inc., based in Edina and headed by
Bartodziej's wife. He also hopes to sell the device to owners of
cumbersome campers and to companies that rent moving trucks.
   With the patent application still pending, Bartodziej made his
first sales at the end of March and put field representatives to
work in Minnesota, Wisconsin and Illinois. He plans to embark on a
national sales effort by August, he says.
   The detector was developed by David Ziembicki of Indian Valley
Manufacturing of Telfore, Pa. Bartodziej, who knew Ziembicki from a
business contact, urged him to tackle the blind spot with some
technology he was developing in work on an unrelated product.
   Bartodziej says all test drivers who have tried it would rather
drive with the detector than without it. And one insurance company
he deals with has indicated an interest in offering lower rates for
trucks equipped with the detector, he says.
   ``We don't endorse any product, but we certainly endorse the
concept,'' said Carol Bufton, president of the Minnesota Safety
Council.
   Bufton said her organization still recommends that drivers
attempt to turn and look for cars that may be in their blind spot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   04-08 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Mixed in March as Sluggish Spending Trend Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An early Easter helped lure consumers into stores in March,
giving many of the nation's largest general retailers a respite
from their sluggish sales of the past year.
   But experts don't believe shoppers are on a long-term spending
spree.
   Retailers and analysts attributed the strong March sales
increases at some stores to a quirk in the calendar: with Easter
falling earlier in April than usual, consumers did their spring
shopping in March. That made comparisons with March 1987 look
better.
   ``They're not as good as they appear,'' Jeffrey B. Edelman, a
retailing analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said of the
March figures.
   Among the retailers reporting strong sales was F.W. Woolworth
Co., which registered a 29 percent increase over March 1987 sales.
   At the other end of the spectrum, the nation's largest retailer,
Sears, Roebuck and Co., reported its sales rose just 1.5 percent.
   The lackluster sales resulted from consumers' general caution,
said Thomas Tashjian, an analyst with the investment firm Seidler
Amdec Securities Inc. in Los Angeles.
   ``The shift in the Easter calendar should have helped in many
cases to lift sales, but we're still in a very sluggish
environment,'' Tashjian said.
   Consumers have spent cautiously since early last year, and
analysts predict they will remain tight-fisted for at least the
first part of 1988.
   The rate of spending is crucial to a retailer's bottom line, but
economists watch it for signals of the nation's economic health.
Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the gross national
product.
   Apparel retailers continued to have problems because of
consumers' continuing disenchantment with the stores' latest lines,
said Karen Sack, an analyst with Standard & Poor's Corp.
   Sears was among the stores having problems with their fashion
lines, Drexel's Edelman said. The retailer said its sales for the
first nine weeks of the fiscal year rose 1.9 percent over the same
period a year earlier.
   K mart Corp. said its sales rose 8.6 percent last month, and 5.5
percent so far this year. Its comparable store sales _ those from
stores open at least a year _ rose 5.5 percent last month, and 2.6
percent for the year to date.
   Rapidly-expanding Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its sales rose 36
percent in March and 34 percent so far this year. Wal-Mart's
comparable store sales rose 15 percent last month and 14 percent
for the first two months of fiscal 1988.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. posted a 10.2 percent sales increase last
month, and a 5.7 percent year-to-date gain. Its comparable store
sales were up 9.3 percent last month and 4.9 percent so far this
year.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said its sales were up 28.8 percent last
month and 23.4 percent so far this year. Comparable store sales
rose 10.5 percent in March and 5.4 percent for the first nine weeks.
   May Department Stores Co. said its sales rose 12.1 percent in
March and 6.5 percent so far this year. May's comparable store
sales rose 7.9 percent last month and 2.6 percent year-to-date.
   Montgomery Ward & Co. said its March sales were up 10 percent
and its year-to-date sales rose 4.3 percent. Comparable store sales
rose 7.7 percent in March and 1.9 percent for the first nine weeks.
   Woolworth said its year-to-date sales were up 20.9 percent.
   Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc. said its sales fell 0.4 percent
in March and 2.4 percent for the nine-week period.
   Results reported Thursday were for department and apparel stores
and general merchandisers. They do not include sales by automakers
or supermarkets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
