<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Chronology     04-08 1108</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Chronology,1153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Key Days in the Texaco-Pennzoil Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texaco-Pennzoil Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the important dates in the battle between Texaco Inc.
and Pennzoil Co. over Getty Oil Co.:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1983</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 28 _ Pennzoil Co. launches a bid of $100 a share for about
20 percent of the stock of Getty, a company viewed as vulnerable
because of feuding among principal shareholders.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1984</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 1 _ Pennzoil Chairman J. Hugh Liedtke and Gordon P. Getty,
sole trustee for the holders of about 40 percent of Getty stock,
discuss a plan under which Pennzoil would acquire three-sevenths of
Getty Oil.
   Jan. 2 _ Representatives of Getty Oil contact Texaco and other
large oil companies to invite competing bids.
   Jan. 3 _ Getty's board, faced with a threat of removal by Gordon
Getty, approves merger negotiations with Pennzoil at a minimum
price of $112 a share.
   Jan. 4 _ Getty Oil and Pennzoil issue identical press releases
announcing an agreement in principle ``subject to a definitive
merger agreement.'' Getty Oil's investment bankers advise Texaco
that anyone is still free to bid.
   Jan. 6 _ Texaco reaches agreement to acquire Getty for $125 a
share. The bid later is raised to $128, for a total of about $10.1
billion.
   Feb. 8 _ Pennzoil sues Texaco in Houston, alleging Texaco
wrongfully interfered in its deal with Getty. It asks for $7.53
billion in actual damages and $7.53 billion in punitive damages.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1985</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   July 9 _ The trial of Pennzoil's suit begins in Houston, with
Judge Anthony Farris presiding.
   Oct. 22 _ Farris steps down because of illness, and Judge
Solomon Casseb Jr. takes over the trial.
   Nov. 19 _ The jury returns a verdict in favor of Pennzoil,
awarding it $7.53 billion in compensatory damages and $3 billion in
punitive damages.
   Dec. 10 _ Casseb enters the judgment for the full amount of the
verdict, plus $600 million in interest, for a total of $11.1
billion. Under Texas law, Texaco faces putting up a bond equal to
the judgment while it appeals the case.
   Dec. 17 _ Texaco obtains a temporary order from U.S. District
Judge Charles Brieant in White Plains, N.Y., barring Pennzoil from
enforcing the Texas court order while Texaco appeals.
   Dec. 20 _ Brieant suspends proceedings while the two companies
try to negotiate a settlement.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1986</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 7 _ Pennzoil stock shoots up 30 percent on rumors it is
near a settlement with Texaco, but Pennzoil announces at the end of
the day its board of directors has rejected a merger offer from
Texaco.
   Jan. 9 _ Brieant resumes proceedings on Texaco's request for an
injunction. In Houston, Texaco asks for a new trial and seeks the
removal of Casseb from the case.
   Jan. 10 _ Brieant grants an injunction against Pennzoil and
rules Texaco has to put up only $1 billion for a bond while it
appeals the case in the Texas courts.
   Feb. 20 _ A federal appeals court in New York upholds Brieant's
ruling.
   March 7 _ Texaco posts the bond with the district court clerk in
Houston to initiate its appeal, pledging $1 billion of stock in its
Canadian subsidiary.
   June 23 _ The U.S. Supreme Court agrees to review the appeals
court decision.
   July 31 _ The Texas Court of Appeals hears arguments in Texaco's
appeal of the damage judgment.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1987</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 12 _ The U.S. Supreme Court hears arguments on Pennzoil's
request to overturn the New York appellate decision.
   Feb. 12 _ The Texas Court of Appeals upholds the $7.53 billion
award in actual damages, but throws out two-thirds of the $3
billion in punitive damages awarded by the Houston jury.
   April 6 _ The U.S. Supreme Court rules unanimously that Brieant
should not have gotten involved in the issue of Texaco's bond
before the Texas courts reviewed the matter. Texaco says it will
appeal the bond issue to the Texas courts immediately, but warns an
unfavorable ruling will force it into bankruptcy court
reorganization.
   April 7 _ The Texas Court of Appeals puts the bond requirement
on hold pending a hearing scheduled for April 13.
   April 12 _ Texaco announces it has filed a petition seeking
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy code.
   April 23 _ Bankruptcy Judge Howard Schwartzberg of White Plains,
N.Y., permits Texaco to resume its appeal of the case, which had
been on hold since the Chapter 11 petition.
   Nov. 2 _ The Texas Supreme Court refuses to hear Texaco's
appeal, letting stand the judgment against Texaco, now worth $10.3
billion. Texaco says it will take its case to the U.S. Supreme
Court.
   Dec. 2 _ The bankruptcy court gives Texaco 40 more days in which
it will have the exclusive right to file its own financial
reorganization plan. But Schwartzberg says he will vacate the order
if Pennzoil and Texaco's creditors agree on a settlement plan to be
voted on by shareholders.
   Dec. 7 _ The judge clarifies his ruling, saying the Texaco
shareholders committee must approve any settlement proposal before
it goes to all the shareholders for a vote.
   Dec. 11 _ Pennzoil announces it has agreed with the shareholders
committee on a reorganization plan that would pay Pennzoil $3
billion to settle the damage claim.
   Dec. 19 _ Texaco announces an agreement with the shareholder and
creditor committees and Pennzoil on a reorganization plan. The plan
calls for a $3 billion payment to Pennzoil, the settlement of all
litigation between the two companies, and the reinstatement of
Texaco's outstanding indebtedness, with full payment of principal
and interest to creditors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1988</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 15 _ Texaco agrees with the shareholders committee to ease
its anti-takeover defenses but not to drop them completely as
sought by financier Carl Icahn, who controls the largest block of
Texaco stock.
   Jan. 22 _ The bankruptcy judge rules that only Texaco's
reorganization propoal will be submitted to shareholders for a vote.
   March 22 _ Dissident shareholders drop their opposition to the
plan, despite their criticism of its provision for freeing officers
and advisers of Texaco, Pennzoil, Getty Oil, the Sarah Getty Trust
and the J. Paul Getty Museum from any liability arising from the
Texaco-Pennzoil battle. The company announces that 96 percent of
the shares voted by Texaco stockholders supported the plan, far
above the two-thirds margin required by federal law.
   March 23 _ After a day-and-a-half hearing, the bankruptcy judge
approves the plan, clearing the way for Texaco to emerge from this
protection by mid-April.
   April 7 _ Texaco's Chapter 11 protection ends. The company pays
$3 billion to Pennzoil and initiates another $2.6 billion in
payments to its other creditors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Economy Bjt   04-08 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Economy, Bjt,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Made Hondas Coming To Japan, Sign Of New Direction In Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of thriving on a booming export trade,
it might seem odd for Honda Motor Co. Ltd. to celebrate the first
arrival here of U.S.-built Honda automobiles.
   But for the company and the domestic economy, today's
celebration over the shipload of 540 Hondas built in Marysville,
Ohio, marked more than a simple welcoming party.
   For Honda, the shipment signaled maturity for a company that in
two decades has transformed itself from a respected motorcycle
maker into a worldwide maker of attractive cars.
   In a broader sense, the imported Hondas reflected ongoing
changes in the surprisingly robust Japanese economy, which is being
fuled more by domestic demand than because of exports, its
longstanding source of growth.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange has surged back from last October's
worldwide crash. On Thursday the Nikkei Stock Average surpassed its
previous high, which was set on Oct. 14. The New York and London
exchange indexes are still about 10 percent below pre-crash levels.
   Japan's gross national product grew at a vibrant rate estimated
at 7 percent to 8 percent in the last quarter of fiscal 1987-88,
which ended March 31. Official figures aren't yet published. Most
analysts expect it to expand at over 4 percent in the new fiscal
year.
   The Japanese consumer _ the same Japanese whose propensity to
save is legendary _ is changing. The car that Honda is importing is
the Accord coupe, a type of car that hasn't been much favored by
Japanese buyers, who traditionally have gone for four-door family
sedans.
   But in recent years, as the strong yen has greatly increased the
wealth of some Japanese, sportier cars have been selling better,
and the Honda Accord coupe is aimed at that increasing market.
   Still, why not make it in Japan?
   Honda spokesman Bret Anderson explained: ``This particular car,
the coupe, is completely designed and set up by American Honda,
with American R&D (research and development) and engineering. So we
don't have facilities in Japan to build it. It was built for the
U.S. market. We see the car as an American car.''
   The company saw the growing demand in Japan and ``thought that
it probably would sell,'' he said. The company predicts sales in
1988 of the American-made coupe at 4,000, and hopes sales will grow
to 50,000 in 1991.
   The Japanese domestic car market is the second biggest in the
world after the United States, where Japan has an export quota of
2.3 million cars a year.
   Oddly, Honda sells more cars in the United States, about 740,000
last year, than in Japan, about 365,000. Importing the Accord coupe
is part of the company's drive to increase its domestic market
share.
   The U.S. price for the Accord coupe is about $15,000; its price
in Japan hasn't been announced.
   The Japanese economy has spurted ahead on a combination of the
high yen and some pump-priming undertaken by the Japanese
government last spring when it looked as if 1987 might be a
recession year.
   On Thursday, the Japanese parliament enacted another mildly
expansionary budget of 56.7 trillion yen ($453.6 billion), up 4.8
percent from the earlier year.
   The new budget includes a big increase in public works spending,
up 19.7 percent at 7.3 trillion yen ($58.4 billion), to keep
domestic demand high.
   A strong factor fueling growth last year was private-sector
housing investment, which leaped 21.7 percent, according to Fuji
Bank economists. They predicted in early April that the economy
would expand at a 4.1 percent rate in fiscal 1988-89, inflation
would be only 0.9 percent, and the dollar would average 122 yen,
close to its recent level of 123-125 yen.
   A projection by the respected Okasan Research Institute
predicted 4.5 percent growth. The Okasan and Fuji projections
agreed that private housing would stall after its hot performance
in the previous year, but that personal spending and corporate
capital investment would continue to fuel growth.
   The Okasan think tank said domestic demand would push the
economy up 5.6 percent while external demand _ exports _ would
shrink and reduce the economy's growth by 1.1 percent.
   Okasan expected the trade surplus to drop from $93.3 billion in
the past fiscal year to $87.7 billion, and the dollar to average
124 yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LuckyStores     04-08 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucky Stores,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lucky Stores Rejects Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc. has spurned American
Stores Co.'s offer for a $1.74 billion buyout and says it may
undergo a major restructuring or sell the company elsewhere.
   Lucky said Thursday its directors unanimously had rejected
American Stores' unsolicited $45 a share tender offer as
``inadequate'' and not in the best interests of the company or its
stockholders.
   The board also rebuffed the offer by American Stores, a Salt
Lake City-based grocery and drugstore chain, to increase its bid to
$50 a share in a negotiated acquisition.
   In addition, Dublin-based Lucky adopted a stock purchase rights
defense plan aimed at making a hostile takeover prohibitively
expensive.
   The rejection of American Stores' surprise tender offer for
Lucky's 38.6 million outstanding shares came 17 months after Lucky
blocked a hostile takeover attempt by New York investor Asher
Edelman.
   A combination of the two companies would create the nation's
biggest supermarket chain.
   Mike Holt, American Stores vice president for investor public
relations, said his company had no comment on the announcement.
   Lucky's stock closed at $52.50 per share on the New York Stock
Exchange Thursday, up $3.75 from Wednesday's close.
   In addition to rejecting American Stores' bid, Lucky's board
also authorized company management and advisers to consider
alternatives to an American Stores buyout to boost its stock price.
   Alternatives could include a possible reorganization to focus on
Lucky's California operations, a leveraged recapitalization with
possible distributions to stockholders by a dividend or share
repurchase, and a negotiated sale of the company to a third party.
   ``We are confident that pursuit of one of these alternatives
will provide our best opportunity to achieve greater value for our
stockholders,'' stated John M. Lillie, Lucky's chairman and chief
executive officer.
   The board also adopted a warrant dividend plan and has declared
a dividend under the plan of one common stock purchase right for
each share of outstanding common stock, payable to stockholders of
record on April 8. The plan would act to dilute Lucky's common
stock in the event of a hostile takeover, making such a move
prohibitively expensive.
   The company stated the plan was aimed at preventing unsolicited
attempts to acquire a controlling stake in Lucky Stores through a
tender offer or on the open market ``at prices determined by the
board to be inadequate.''
   A merger of American Stores, with 1,700 outlets in 40 states,
and Lucky would have make Lucky the nation's largest supermarket
chain, surpassing No. 1 Kroger Co. Lucky has 480 outlets, 340
within the state.
   American Stores had indicated it would convert its struggling
240 Alpha Beta outlets in California to Lucky stores.
   American Stores last year posted $14.3 billion in annual sales,
while Lucky had $6.9 billion in sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Earns-Safeway     04-08 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Safeway,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge Supermarket Chain Reports Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Safeway Stores Inc. says it suffered a
$487.7 million loss last year, largely due to interest expenses
from its 1986 leveraged buyout and to income tax law changes.
   The privately-held supermarket chain, the nation's
second-largest after Cincinnati-based Kroger Co., had posted a
$14.3 million loss in 1986. Safeway also said its revenue fell to
$18.3 billion last year from $20.3 billion the previous year.
   However, Safeway's operating profit rose to $448.3 million from
$422.9 million the previous year, Safeway said.
   Last year's loss was blamed on $576.4 million in interest
expense, largely stemming from the leveraged buyout, and a $409.4
million bookkeeping charge resulting from the new tax law, the
company said.
   Safeway believes its interest expenses have peaked and will
decline over the next few years, said the company's controller,
David Domeier.
   Domeier said the company trimmed its long-term debt by 32
percent to $3.1 billion in 1987 and is one to two years ahead of
schedule in paying off its debt.
   The drop in revenue was attributed to the sale of several
divisions, including the 105-store Liquor Barn chain and markets in
Britain and four states, to raise capital and help pay off the debt.
   During the same period, sales for U.S. stores grew 5 percent,
Domeier said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
