<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-08 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar traded lower against all major
foreign currencies except the Swiss franc and Canadian dollar in
Europe early today. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market is waiting for a
meeting of finance ministers of the seven major industrialized
countries in Washington next week.
   Most said they expect the Group of Seven _ the United States,
Britain, Japan, West Germany, France, Italy and Canada _ to
reaffirm their wish to keep the dollar stable around its current
levels.
   European traders said interest was likely to focus on the
British pound again today, following intervention by the West
German and British central banks Thursday to stop sterling's rise.
   ``Sterling is very healthy at the moment but that old fear of
central bank intervention should keep the market from pushing it up
too fast,'' said one trader with a major Italian commercial bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.52 yen to a closing 125.18. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 125.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.6725 West German marks, down from 1.6810; 1.3825
Swiss francs, up from 1.3817; 5.6740 French francs, down from
5.7022; 1.8855 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8865; 1,241.20 Italian
lire, down from 1,246.50; and 1.2475 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2448.
   In London, it cost $1.8775 to buy one British pound today, more
expensive for buyers than late Thursday's $1.867.
   Gold prices were higher in London than late Thursday's $447.75 a
troy ounce. The gold metal opened at a bid price of $449.40 an
ounce but at midmorning today the city's five major bullion dealers
had fixed a recommended price of $448.60.
   One dealer said that after hitting a low of about $445 Thursday,
gold has found some support at its current levels. Other bullion
dealers said attention will be focused on the dollar, and that a
major move in the U.S. currency could send gold moving.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $448.65, up from $448 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.06 to close at a bid $450.72.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.42 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $6.40.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
