<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene     04-08 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,0860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Offers Extensive Data On China Agriculture, Population</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China in recent years has been losing its
rural people, despite an overall growth in the country's
population, according to a new statistical report by the
Agriculture Department.
   In 1982, when China reported a population of more than 1.01
billion, a record 803.9 million, or 79 percent, lived in rural
areas. By 1985 the total population was more than 1.04 billion, but
rural residents were down to 662.9 million people, or 63 percent.
   Population figures and many others are included in a new edition
of ``Agricultural Statistics of the People's Republic of China,
1949-86,'' by Frederick W. Crook and others of the department's
Economic Research Service.
   The new version, which was distributed Thursday, expands greatly
an earlier statistical report on China's agriculture issued in
1984, which was the USDA's first since the communists took charge
in 1949.
   Although not likely to make this spring's best-seller lists, the
158-page report is expected to be in great demand from China
watchers and U.S. agricultural traders interested in that
potentially huge Asian market. The first edition in 1984 was 71
pages long.
   The report relies on ``the important, although still incomplete,
agricultural data that China's State Statistical Bureau reported
during 1949-85, with some updates through 1986,' the authors said.
   Some 126 national and provincial tables of figures are included,
along with an introduction, explanatory notes, references and
suggested readings.
   Various sections include agricultural production; ``inputs''
such as farm machinery, fertilizer and labor; exports and imports;
and consumption and procurement.
   The provincial tables include China's population by region and
province; agricultural areas by crops; hog slaughter; horse and
camel year-end inventory; milk production for cows and goats; and
consumption by peasants.
   Officials said the report may be ordered from: Superintendent of
Documents, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C. 20402,
or telephone (202) 783-3238.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fierce competition for the world's soybean
market has sprung up as demand increases for the high-protein,
oil-rich crop that once was dominated almost entirely by the United
States.
   Soybeans have the potential to supplement diets of low-income
people in the Third World, where it will be important to gain
consumer acceptance for soybeans and soy-fortified foods, Gary
Vocke, an Agriculture Department analyst, said Thursday in a new
report.
   ``A historical view shows that U.S. dominance of world soybean
trade, founded on U.S. research and development in the 1940s and
1950s, declined in the 1980s as South American countries, spurred
by high prices, developed large-scale production and processing
facilities,'' he said.
   Brazil and Argentina have been the main U.S. competitors in the
international soybean market.
   Vocke, an agriculture and trade analyst in the department's
Economic Research Service, added: ``Their success, mainly in
temperate areas, has not been duplicated in tropical areas
elsewhere in the Third World.''
   The major factors behind the increased demand for soybeans in
the Third World, he said, are rising incomes and population growth.
As families have more to spend, their demand increases for meat and
other food products such as margarine and cooking oil.
   `` Fierce export competition with the South Americans for these
markets, as well as the developed country market, will likely
continue,'' Vocke said. ``The expansion of large-scale soybean
production in South America will continue as long as soybean prices
are high enough for Brazilian farmers to profitably open new lands
for soybeans.''
   Further encouragement would be in the Brazilian government's
willingness to develop the rural transportation system connecting
the new lands to ocean ports, he said.
   ``If the price of soybeans is high relative to other crops,
farmers in Brazil, Argentina and elsewhere will find it profitable
to switch even more of their existing cropland to soybeans,'' Vocke
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners continue to own just under 1
percent of U.S. agricultural land, slightly more than the level of
a year ago, according to an Agriculture Department report.
   The department's Economic Research Service said Thursday its
1987 year-end review of reports under the Agricultural Foreign
Investment Disclosure Act found 12.5 million acres of agricultural
land in foreign hands, 202,000 acres more than reported in 1986.
   Of the land owned by foreign interests, 50 percent was forest
land, 17 percent cropland, 28 percent pasture and other
agricultural land, and 5 percent used for non-agricultural purposes
or unreported.
   Corporations held 80 percent of the foreign-owned land, with the
balance held by individuals, partnerships, institutions and other
entities.
   As in the past, much of the ownership is concentrated in the
United Kingdom, Canada, West Germany, the Netherlands Antilles and
Switzerland. Those countries combined to account for 69 percent of
the foreign-held acreage, the agency said.
   Maine continued to have the heaviest concentration of foreign
ownership, with holdings of almost 1.79 million acres, mostly
timberland, or more than 14 percent of the total.
   ``Ninety-three percent of the foreign-owned acreage will remain
in agricultural production, according to foreign owners,'' the
report said.
</TEXT>
