<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     04-08 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Higher On Interest Rate Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose Friday when British commercial
banks heeded a Bank of England signal to cut their base lending
rate.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index rose 12.6
points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,773.6 at midday.
   Volume was light at 259.3 million shares at midday compared with
261.9 million shares at the same time Thursday.
   The commercial banks announced a cut in their base lending rate
by half a percentage point to 8 percent, the lowest level in more
than a decade.
   The banks cut the benchmark rate, effective Monday, after the
central bank reduced its own money market rate by 0.375 percnet to
8 percent, apparently to stem the British pound's advance.
   ``That's what we want, some more good news like that,'' said one
dealer, referring to the reduced interest rates. ``It should be
just the tonic the market needs'' to take it higher.
   The dealer said the market had been sluggish all morning, held
back in part by major new share issues by Tate and Lyle PLC to help
finance a tender offer for Staley Continental Inc. of the United
States and a huge issue announced by Barclays Bank PLC on Thursday.
   Other dealers were more wary of the benefits to equities from
the interest rate cuts, saying the lower rates revive fears of
inflationary pressures on Britain's economy.
   One dealer also noted that the pound failed to show marked
reaction shortly after the rate cut was announced, dampening the
positive sentiment in the equity market.
</TEXT>
