<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Staley-TateandLyle     04-08 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Staley-Tate and Lyle,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tate and Lyle Launches Tender Offer For Staley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tate and Lyle PLC, a major British sugar refiner
and distributor, announced today a $1.33 billion cash tender offer
for Staley Continental Inc., the second largest refiner of corn
sweeteners in the United States.
   Tate and Lyle, which already owns nearly 5 percent of Staley's
stock, said it was offering $32 a share for the rest of its 30.4
million outstanding shares.
   Staley stock closed at $30.12{ a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Wednesday.
   Staley has proposed that Tate and Lyle build on its stake
acquired in November and become a more substantial minority
shareholder, Tate and Lyle said. But Tate and Lyle said it decided
to launch the tender offer instead.
   The acquisition would give Tate and Lyle its first interest in
the U.S. corn sweetener market. Tate and Lyle said it would become
the only supplier of all three types of sugar _ corn, beet and cane
_ in the United States.
   ``We are confident that, as part of Tate and Lyle's North
American division, the performance and competitive position of
Staley's corn activities will be significantly enhanced,'' Tate and
Lyle Chairman Neil Shaw said.
   Tate and Lyle said it began legal action in the United States to
overturn takeover defenses established by Staley, including a
benefit package for its senior management.
   Tate and Lyle said the offer will be partly funded by the sale
of new shares to its existing shareholders, cash resources and a
bank loan.
   Tate and Lyle said it intends to sell Staley's food distribution
business, which Staley acquired in 1984 for $396 million, and that
it was prepared to consider any offers immediately.
   The acquisition and stock issue must be approved by Tate and
Lyle's shareholders, who are to meet on May 3.
   Staley's principal corn product is high fructose corn syrup,
known as HFCS. The largest refiner of corn sweeteners in the United
States is Archer-Daniels-Midland Co., also based in Decatur.
</TEXT>
