<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     04-08 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0287</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today, continuing
its rally over the past three sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 81.57 points over
the last three trading days, rose 2.32 to 2,064.49 by 10 a.m. today
on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in the early tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 553 up, 406 down and
476 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.81 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The market has benefited lately from signs that the dollar has
steadied in foreign-exchange, reducing fears that the Federal
Reserve might soon tighten credit.
   In the credit markets today, prices of long-term government
bonds showed some moderate gains, putting their yields in the 8.75
percent range.
   Brokers also say investors are looking for generally strong
corporate earnings reports for the first quarter over the next few
weeks.
   With all that, however, many analysts remain skeptical about the
market's chances to launch a sustained rally toward last year's
highs.
   General Electric, which reported higher first-quarter earnings
on Thursday, rose { to 41} in active trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .25 to 150.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .02 at 299.36.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average edged up 0.50 to
2,062.17.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 975 up, 535 down and 480 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 177.84 million shares, against 181.76 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
