<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-InterestRates 3rdLd-Writethru   04-08 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Interest Rates, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Banks Cut Key Lending Rate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 3rd graf that rate is at its lowest level since
1978 sted 1977.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's major commercial banks, heeding a signal
from the Bank of England, announced Friday a cut in their base
lending rate by half a percentage point to 8 percent, the lowest
level in more than a decade.
   Midland Bank PLC, National Westminster Bank PLC, Barclays Bank
PLC and Lloyds Bank PLC cut the benchmark rate, effective Monday,
after the central bank reduced its own money market rate by 0.375
percent to 8 percent, apparently to stem the British pound's
advance.
   The base rate cut brought the rate to its lowest level since it
stood at 7.5 percent in April, 1978, the banks said.
   The banks last cut the rate, by half a point, on March 17.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government has been concerned
about the strength of the pound against the West German mark since
early March. The pound has been buoyed by Britain's relatively high
interest rates, which make pound-denominated investments more
attractive, stimulating demand for the currency.
   A stronger pound could hurt Britain's exports and corporate
profits.
   However, there have been concerns that rate cuts would spur
inflation, which is running at a modest 3.3 percent.
   Mrs. Thatcher repeatedly has said that reining in inflation is
her top economic priority.
   Better commercial borrowers generally obtain loans at 1
percentage point above the base rate.
</TEXT>
