<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAW-Chrysler     04-08 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-Chrysler,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bargainers OK'd To Go For Ford-GM Pattern, Some Kenosha Workers
Admitted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers bargainers have
received their marching orders: win for Chrysler Corp. employees
the same pay, benefits and job protections enjoyed by their
counterparts at the top two automakers.
   The UAW's Chrysler council wrapped up a two-day strategy session
here Thursday and voted to seek a return to labor parity between
the No. 3 automaker and its larger rivals, General Motors Corp. and
Ford Motor Co.
   Since 1979, the union's Chrysler contract has expired at
different times than the Ford and GM pacts because the Chrysler
contract was reopened several times for company-saving concessions.
   But the UAW will insist on a two-year contract with Chrysler so
all three pacts will expire together in 1990, adding to workers'
bargaining power at a time when they will need it most because of
the growing number of Japanese-owned factories building cars in the
United States.
   ``There might be a wiggle here or there that will be different
but the principles will be the same,'' UAW Vice President Marc
Stepp said. ``We are ready to do battle for justice, economically
and socially, with the Chrysler Corporation.''
   Chrysler's UAW contract expires Sept. 14. Talks normally would
begin in mid-July but the UAW and Chrysler agreed to start early
after Chrysler's attempt to sell its Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary
ignited angry UAW opposition and left behind a bitter residue.
   The bargaining is set to begin April 18 in Detroit.
   ``We will take the pattern agreement and as closely as possible
fits those provisions (to) the Chrysler agreement,'' Stepp said.
   The Chrysler council represents 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off
workers, members of 49 UAW locals.
   The council also voted nearly unanimously to accept some former
American Motors Corp. workers into their fold under a compromise
that ended days of potentially divisive debate.
   Chrysler bought AMC last August and announced last fall it will
close a 5,500-worker assembly plant in Kenosha, Wis., leaving 1,000
workers at a Kenosha engine plant and a Milwaukee parts
distribution center to either bargain with Chrysler on their own or
come under the national contract.
   The soon-to-be-laid-off assembly plant workers will be covered
under a separate plant closing agreement and will not join the
union's Chrysler council.
   Local leaders who did not want to admit the 1,000 Kenosha
workers said they feared the former AMC workers, whose seniority
averages 18-20 years, would take jobs that otherwise might go to
laid-off Chrysler workers.
   Under the compromise, the Kenosha workers, unlike other Chrysler
workers, will not be able to take their seniority with them if
their plant closes or use their seniority to take openings in other
plants ahead of workers already on layoff.
   ``We weren't looking for that anyway. We were looking to be
covered under the same wages, hours and working conditions that all
other Chrysler workers get,'' said Rudy Kuzel, chairman of Local 72
at Kenosha.
   ``We know that Chrysler wants to close four plants in the
Detroit area and it would be presumptuous of us to expect to move
into other plants with our seniority,'' Kuzel said.
   Local 72 President Ed Steagall called the approval a miracle
because of heated behind-the-scenes wrangling over the issue since
before delegates began arriving Tuesday.
   The union's elected 10-member rank-and-file bargaining committee
will have to negotiate both the demands package and the inclusion
of the Kenosha workers with Chrysler in the talks.
   Last fall, the UAW won contracts with Ford and GM that forbade
layoffs for any reason except slow sales, banned plant closings not
announced before negotiations and limited the top two automakers'
ability to shift work to outside suppliers or to their own plants
in other countries, including Canada and Mexico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Saudi-OPEC     04-08 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Saudi-OPEC,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Monarch Calls for Cooperation by All Oil Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd has called for
``solidarity'' among members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to bolster the target price of $18 a barrel,
the official Saudi Press Agency reported.
   ``If this is achieved, then there will be immense benefits and
the prices of oil will always be on the increase,'' he told college
students Thursday night while on inspection tour of the al-Qasseem
region some 200 miles north of here.
   The Saudi monarch attributed the instability of oil prices to
attempts by ``some'' to sell at discount prices, and expressed hope
that adherence will be strict to production and price rulings laid
down by the 13-nation OPEC.
   He affirmed that the kingdom ``has never at any time violated
any agreement related to oil,'' thus adding yet another official
denial to ongoing reports that Saudi Arabia was also violating OPEC
prices and selling at a discount because of the weak market.
   Fahd did not name any of the member states of the OPEC cartel
that he accused of cheating on the rulings laid by OPEC for more
than a year and designed to strengthen oil prices around an 18
dollars for benchmark crude.
   At Saudi Arabia's request, the five-member OPEC pricing
committee is meeting in Vienna on Saturday to consider ways and
means of firming up the world market's flagging prices.
   Fahd's call for ``solidarity'' among OPEC member states was
apparently aimed at pre-empting outbursts of inter-OPEC criticism
to help the Vienna gathering formulate the proper recommendations.
   On Thursday, Iranian oil minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh accused
Saudi Arabia of trying to destabilize the oil market by not
agreeing to have the Vienna meeting held at an earlier date.
   He said that Saudi Arabia blocked a call three months ago by
Iran to have the pricing committee convene. Committee members are
oil ministers of Saudi Arabia, Mexico, Venezuela, Nigeria and
Algeria.
   Saudi Oil Minister Hisham Nazer will be in Vienna after calling
on two major non-OPEC oil producers _ Mexico and Britain _ seeking
their cooperation in helping stabilize the market by restraining
their output.
   Saudi Arabia is the leading member of the cartel and alone
possesses at least one-fifth of the world's proven oil reserves.
Fahd stressed this point in his address saying that the kingdom
``now is one of the major countries with reserves in the ground
that can suffice it for 200 years according to the estimates of
world experts.''
</TEXT>
