<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Trader-Jail     04-08 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trader-Jail,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Broker Gets Jail For $1 Million Defrauding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former trader who pleaded guilty to commodities
fraud in the $1 million-plus defrauding of his employer has been
sentenced to three years in prison.
   U.S. District Judge James Alesia ordered Jeffrey Donnelly on
Thursday to surrender June 1 to begin serving the sentence.
   Donnelly is a former trader for CRT Services Inc., a member firm
of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. He pleaded guilty to two counts
of commodities fraud on Feb. 17.
   According to a plea agreement, Donnelly admitted defrauding CRT
of more than $1 million by diverting money from profitable trade in
Standard & Poor's stock index futures to four accounts from January
1984 through July 1986.
   The diversion was carried out through a scheme involving secret
and illegal agreements with four CRT customers, the plea agreement
said. Donnelly received 35 percent of the profits, while the four
customers got the remaining 65 percent, according to the agreement.
   Donnelly was among 10 brokers, traders and others who worked at
the Chicago Board of Trade and the Merc, and were charged with
wrongdoing in indictments and criminal complaints filed by U.S.
Attorney Anton Valukas in January.
   Donnelly was the first to be sentenced.
</TEXT>
