<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-Oil     04-08 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Oil,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabia, Mexico Agree to Work for Oil Price Stability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico and Saudi Arabia have agreed to create
a bilateral consultative mechanism to seek price stability on the
world petroleum market.
   The new mechanism was established ``to strive for the stability
of the international petroleum market and the improvement of
hydrocarbon prices,'' according to a statement released Thursday,
following a meeting between Saudi oil minister Hisham Nazer and
President Miguel de la Madrid.
   Department of Energy, Mines and Parastatal Industries Secretary
Fernando Hiriart also attended the talks.
   Nazer observed during the meeting that both oil-producing
countries ``probably will remain in the world hydrocarbons market
long after other exporting countries leave,'' according to the
agency statement.
   Mexico is not a member of the Organization of Oil Exporting
Countries but closely monitors its price and production guidelines.
It was the world's fourth largest oil producer in 1985 but since
has slipped to sixth place after the Soviet Union, the United
States, Saudi Arabia, Iran and China.
   Hiriart and Nazer agreed ``that the stability of the
international petroleum market and improvemnt of hydrocarbon prices
only can be brought about with the cooperation of all producing
countries, members and non-members of OPEC,'' the statement said.
   Energy officials of both governments will meet periodically to
evaluate the market situation, the statement added.
   On Monday, Mexico's state oil monopoly Pemex announced that it
had lowered the price of its light Isthmus crude by $1.62 a barrel
to Japanese customers in March.
   Pemex revealed in a statement that the price of its light oil
was $13.86 a barrel in March, down from $15.48 a barrel in February.
   The price for its heavy Maya crude fell from $12.83 to $11.20,
the monopoly.
   Japan buys 180,000 barrels a day of crude, accounting for 11
percent of Mexico's total exports in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
