<DOCNO> AP880408-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GM-FuelEconomy     04-08 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Fuel Economy,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Calls Wants Scaled Back Fuel Efficiency Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp., which helped persuade the
government to reduce its car fuel economy regulations for each of
the last three model years, has again called for the repeal or
reduction of the rules.
   The No. 1 automaker said in a statement Thursday the Corporate
Average Fuel Economy Standards are ``a disadvantage for full-line
manufacturers'' that should be repealed or amended.
   Without some action, GM said it could be ``subject to civil
penalties in the hundreds of millions of dollars'' and may be
forced to ``close plants or severely restrict product offerings to
remain in compliance.''
   GM and other automakers were successful in efforts to win
reduced CAFE standars in 1986, 1987 and 1988. The government had
set a fleetwide goal of 27.5 miles per gallon for 1988 models, but
agreed to lower it to 26 mpg.
   GM anticipates compliance with the reduced level in 1988, but
the standard is scheduled to return to 27.5 mpg in 1989 model year.
   The company has said it might fail to meet CAFE regulations in
1989 if gasoline prices remain stable or continue falling. Stable
gas prices have made the less fuel-efficient six- and
eight-cylinder cars more attractive to consumers.
   Companies are allowed to borrow credits from past and future
years in which they have exceeded or expect to exceed the standard
as a way to reduce current non-compliance.
   GM is asking the government to reduce retroactively the 1985
model year standard to 26 mpg from 27.5 mpg, which would give the
company credit to offset any 1989 shortfalls. Other auto companies
are doing the same.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
