<DOCNO> AP880408-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NYSE-Specialists 1stLd-Writethru   04-08 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYSE-Specialists, 1st Ld-Writethru,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Boosts Capital Requirements for Specialists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 3rd graf pvs, The Securities ...
with comment on the requirements. Picks up 4th graf, The exchange
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Specialist firms that control the rights to
trade specific issues on the New York Stock Exchange will have to
meet tough new capital requirements under the Big Board's latest
post-crash proposal.
   The capital plan, approved Thursday by the NYSE board, is the
latest in a series of steps taken to strengthen the market in the
wake of Wall Street's October crash.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission now must consider the
plan.
   Perrin Long, who follows the securities industry industry for
Lipper Analytical Securities Corp., said the new proposal appears
mainly designed to bolster confidence in the marketplace. He said
it may help keep trading orderly, but would not prevent another
severe decline.
   Richard Torrenzano, a spokesman for the NYSE, confirmed that
``the vast majority of the specialists can meet'' the proposed new
requirements today.
   Long said the new requirements could lead to more consolidation
among specialists.
   The exchange currently has 54 specialist firms, which control
the rights to market the stocks of the 1,650-plus companies listed
on the exchange. Specialists are required to keep order in the
market by setting opening prices and covering trades when there are
not enough buyers or sellers.
   The specialist system came under scrutiny in the days following
the Oct. 19 crash because of reports that some specialists failed
to fulfill their roles during the market turmoil. Some specialist
firms merged with bigger firms or had to give up their roles
because of shattering financial damage suffered in the crash.
   Since the crash, five stock specialists have agreed voluntarily
to give up their roles as market makers on the exchange.
   Under the proposed changes, a specialist firm must show it can
meet, with its own liquid assets, a minimum capital requirement of
$1 million or be able to buy 15,000 shares of each common stock in
which it makes a market, whichever is greater.
   The rules currently require minimum capital of $100,000 or the
ability to buy 5,000 shares in each stock in which the specialist
makes a market.
   John J. Phelan Jr., chairman and chief executive of the
exchange, said one question asked repeatedly since the crash has
been, ``Would the condition of the market during the week of Oct.
19 have been better than it was if specialists had more capital?''
   ``The simple answer was `no,' and the Brady Commission agreed
with that conclusion,'' Phelan said, referring to the presidential
commission that investigated the causes of the crash.
   But Phelan said the crash and subsequent volatility of the stock
market served to ``underscore the need for strengthening the
specialist system'' and he said the proposed changes were ``an
appropriate interim step to be taken now to bolster confidence'' in
it.
   He said other measures concerning the adequacy of the
specialists' capital requirements are under review.
   Among other post-crash steps the exchange has announced
previously was a curb on computerized program trading, which takes
effect when the Dow Jones industrial average moves 50 points in
either direction from the previous day's close in one session.
   That curb was activated for the first time on Wednesday when the
Dow's rise surpassed 50 points in the last hour of trading. The Dow
finished with a gain of 64.16 points for the day.
   The exchange has also announced it has begun taking steps to
improve its ability to handle heavy trading volumes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MexicoInflation     04-08 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico Inflation,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>March Consumer Prices Growth Slowest Since November 1985</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 5.1 percent during
March, the lowest monthly figure since November 1985, the central
Bank of Mexico announced.
   It said late Thursday that inflation recorded for the first
three months of the year reached 31.5 percent, compared to 23.6
percent in the same period of 1987.
   Inflation last year soared to a record 159.2 percent annual
figure. The government put into effect controls on wages and prices
for goods and services it regulates in March, the second phase of a
so-called Economic Solidarity Pact intended to brake hyperinflation
and reduce it to 1 to 2 percent monthly by the end of the year.
   Under the program, the value of the peso _ 2,280 to the dollar _
and the minimum daily wage of 8,000 pesos, or about $3.50, will
remain steady through the end of May.
</TEXT>
