<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OfficeShooting     04-08 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Office Shooting,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fired Broker Arraigned On Charges Of Killing Boss At Merrill Lynch</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: versions running on general news wires</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with arraignment. Picks up in 4th
graf, `George Cook ...'
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fired Merrill Lynch broker accused of fatally
shooting his former boss, who was chased from his office and
pistol-whipped in front of about 60 company workers, was ordered
held on $500,000 bail today.
   Lonnie Gilchrist, 41, of Boston, did not offer a plea at his
arraignment in Boston Municipal Court. Judge Peter Donovan ordered
his case continued until April 19, said court clerk Russell Long.
   Gilchrist had complained of racial discrimination, but was fired
because of ``poor performance,'' a newspaper quoted sources as
saying.
   George Cook, 56, a senior vice president and 31-year Merrill
Lynch employee, was meeting with Gilchrist when he was shot
Thursday, said Patrick Murphy, national director of security for
Merrill Lynch
   Cook then fled into the main office and Gilchrist chased him for
about 30 feet, beating him on the head with the .22 caliber pistol
until Cook collapsed, witnesses said. At that point, Murphy said,
``Mr. Gilchrist pumped more shots into him while he was on the
floor.''
   Cook was hit in the chest, back, arm and side with four of a
total of nine bullets fired, Murphy said.
   After Cook collapsed in the 36th-floor downtown office, three
workers wrestled Gilchrist to the floor.
   ``I don't know what went on between them,'' said Merrill Lynch
vice president Paul Knouse of the meeting between Cook and
Gilchrist. ``George wasn't able to say much. I think he was already
in shock ... ''
   Gilchrist, a graduate of the University of Massachusetts in
Boston and the Wharton School of Business at the University of
Pennsylvania, had worked for the company for less than two years
and was fired Wednesday for inefficient performance.
   Merrill Lynch spokesman Fred Yager declined to be more specific
about the reasons behind the firing. He said he did not know
whether Gilchrist's meeting with Cook had been scheduled.
   An unnamed associate was quoted by The Boston Globe as saying
Gilchrist went through eight jobs in 11 years before joining
Merrill Lynch in June 1986. He was told repeatedly that he would
have to ``start performing'' there or lose his job, the associate
said.
   ``Lonnie was doing very poorly,'' said an unidentified friend
who told the Globe he talked to Gilchrist by telephone Wednesday
night, and that Gilchrist gave no indication that he had been
fired. ``He was bright but he couldn't communicate or sell. He
couldn't bring in the revenue but George Cook was trying to help
him along.''
   The newspaper said Gilchrist made only $17,051 in commissions in
his first year, less than 20 percent of the average $100,000 in
commissions a first-year broker makes, according to a Merrill Lynch
official in New York. Since October, Gilchrist had received $6,491
in commissions, the newspaper said.
   The Globe quoted unnamed sources as saying Gilchrist was heard
to complain that his bosses' growing criticism of his weak sales
volume at Merrill Lynch was racially motivated. ``Lonnie was taking
this as racial, but it was just poor performance,'' one source said.
   Gilchrist, who lived with his mother, filed a racial
discrimination complaint with the Massachusetts Commission Against
Discrimination three years ago, claiming Northrop Corp. of Norwood
refused to give him a job because he was black. Northrop said it
didn't hire Gilchrist because he asked for too much money. The
commission dismissed the complaint on grounds of insufficient
evidence.
   A Merrill Lynch office manager in Florida was killed and another
broker wounded after last October's stock market plunge by a
customer who had been told he owed $138,000. The investor, who then
killed himself, had seen his stock holdings drop $2.5 million in
value after the Oct. 19 market collapse.
</TEXT>
