<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Construction     04-08 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Construction,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Questions Japan-U.S. Public Works Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Commission Friday asked Japan to clarify the terms of an accord
with the United States opening Japanese public works projects to
U.S. firms.
   ``If it turned out that this agreement would be yet another
bilateral deal between these two countries to the exclusion of
others, that would be very damaging,'' EEC External Relations
Commissioner Willy De Clercq said Friday.
   The EEC has criticized past efforts by the United States to open
Japanese markets through preferential bilateral accords.
   Last month the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade said parts
of a U.S.-Japanese accord on trade in semiconductors violated its
international rules of commerce.
   The public works deal was signed Tuesday in Washington.
   ``We take this affair very seriously, not only because of the
amount of potential trade involved but also because we feel that
bilateral deals are hurting the spirit of free trade,'' De Clercq
said in a statement.
   He said he would raise the issue at a meeting in Vancouver next
week of trade officials from the United States, Japan, Canada and
the EEC.
   The public works accord signed by U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter and Japan's Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Ichiro
Ozawa, was termed a declaration of intent rather than a formal
bilateral agreement.
   U.S. officials said it was intended to provide market access to
Japan for U.S. engineering and construction firms and for U.S.
suppliers of a wide range of equipment for projects financed
directly or indirectly with Japanese government funds.
   De Clercq said he has not yet seen the text of the accord but
sought ``an immediate, official declaration by the Japanese
government clarifying the situation.''
   ``There is a need for a binding commitment sufficiently specific
to reassure the (EEC) and its industry that the latter will be able
to bid for work under these major projects on an equal and
non-discriminatory basis with regard to both Japanese and third
country competitors,'' he said.
</TEXT>
