<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Stocks Bjt   04-08 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Stocks, Bjt,0920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fueled By Strong Economic Performance, Tokyo Stock Market Recoups
Losses</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than six months after the global market
collapse, Japanese stock prices have surged above pre-crash levels,
thanks to market resilience and renewed confidence in the country's
healthy economy.
   ``People have realized the Tokyo market has certain strengths,''
said Simon Smithson at the Kleinwort Benson investment firm.
   The main index of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the world's largest
in terms of money invested, fell 15 percent last October in the
session after the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell a
record 508 points, or 23 percent.
   On Thursday, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues
finished making up all its lost ground as it surpassed its
pre-crash level and reached its highest level in history, 26,769.22.
   On Friday, the Nikkei index slipped less than 0.1 percent,
losing 20.33 points to close at 26,748.89.
   The Dow Jones index, meanwhile, still languishes more than 8
percent below its level of the day before the crash and 24 percent
below its peak of last August. Other world stock exchanges are also
below pre-crash levels.
   Julian Jones of the Vickers da Costa investment firm said the
Tokyo market had been pushed by factors ``intrinsic and unique to
Japan'' which had more to do with underlying domestic economic
factors that could not be applied internationally.
   ``They were Japanese reasons,'' he said.
   Some of them are low interest rates, high corporate profits,
strong economic growth estimated at a 7 percent annual rate in the
last quarter of 1987 and inflation so low that consumer prices in
February were 0.7 percent below a year earlier.
   Also, investors are reassured by controls on price movements of
stocks, which they believe protect the market against a crash,
Smithson said.
   Still, some Japanese officials worry that the Tokyo Stock
Exchange is bouncing back too fast. Satoshi Sumita, governor of the
Bank of Japan, said Thursday that stock prices have risen too
rapidly in relation to economic growth.
   Many investment strategists remain optimistic. Hisamichi Sawa,
chief strategist at the Prudential Bache investment firm, said the
Tokyo stock market is sensitive to corporate earnings, and the
Nikkei's rise was powered by substantial improvements in company
profits.
   ``The domestic sector is now growing by more than 6 percent,''
Sawa said. Other analysts agree, and say the economy's overall
growth _ compensating for a decline in exports _ will be 4 to 4.5
percent this year.
   Sawa attributed the market's resilience to a ``substantial level
of liquidity and low interest rates.'' The prime lending rate in
Japan is 5.5 percent.
   ``Investor sentiment is very optimistic,'' Sawa said. ``Money is
flowing into the market from bond investments and savings
accounts.''
   Traders also agreed that a stable foreign exchange rate is
contributing strongly to the Nikkei's continuing bullish
performance. The U.S. dollar fluctuated mainly in a narrow range of
125 to 128 yen last month.
   ``People realized the dollar was not headed for 120 yen as
quickly as they originally thought,'' said Clap Ham, director of
research at Jardine Fleming.
   ``Removal of this fear has pushed the market up,'' he added.
   Many analysts said the country's system of government control
over daily market movements also played a substantial role in
fueling the rise.
   ``There is no doubt about it,'' said Ham. Investors are bound to
feel comfortable with ``a market secured in government
intervention.''
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange determines daily price-change limits
for stocks from their previous day's closing level. At the bottom
end, shares closing at less than 100 yen (79 cents) are allowed to
move a maximum of 30 yen (24 cents) up or down, while at the top,
those closing above 10,000 yen ($79), are given a maximum
fluctuation of 2,000 yen ($16).
   Trading offers outside the stock's allowed range are not
accepted, meaning shares with quick price changes sometimes are not
traded for much of a session.
   Traders say the restrictions greatly inhibited the flow of money
out of the market at the time of the crash, thereby limiting the
overall decline.
   ``The limits had a positive calming influence on the stock
market,'' said Smithson of Kleinwort Benson. The ``close
relationship between the administration and institutions'' had an
``important role and slowed the rate of fall.''
   Jardine Fleming's Ham described the government as ``a guardian
angel'' who will do whatever is needed to keep the market from
falling.
   He added that numerous American investors have recently come
into the Tokyo market, lured by the perceived benefits of the
Japanese system.
   But while some analysts are predicting the Nikkei index will
continue up _possibly nearing the 30,000 mark by the end of summer
_ they stopped short of saying Tokyo, already the world's largest
market in terms of total value of shares, will replace New York and
London in dictating future market trends.
   Sawa said the U.S. stock market will continue to wield a strong
influence over Tokyo activity. ``Assuming New York does not drop
significantly or remains at its present level, the Tokyo market
will move up,'' he said.
   He predicted prices will be bolstered by a new buying mood among
the ``many financial institutions, including insurance firms and
trust banks, who missed the bus because the market went up''
quicker than they expected.
</TEXT>
