<2ND_LINE>BC-L-P Redwood Settlement,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louisiana-Pacific Gets Final Redwood National Park Payment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana-Pacific Corp. has received $440
million from the federal government as final payment for 26,544
acres of timberland taken in the 1978 expansion of California's
Redwood National Park.
   With previous payments, the wood-products manufacturer has
received $665 million in principal and interest for the timberland.
   ``After 10 years of discussion and court debate, it's a pleasure
to finally have these funds in the bank so we can put the money to
use on behalf of our employees and stockholders,'' said Harry A.
Merlo, L-P president and chairman on Friday.
   About $100 million of the settlement will be used to pay back
taxes on the land, and $170 million will repay long-term debts that
carried provisions for repayment after a settlement was received.
   Portions of the remaining money will be used to repay other
debts and to fund several capital projects, such as the Inner-Seal
panel plant under construction near Athens, Ga., and the $70
million upgrading of the company's pulp mill in Samoa, Calif.
   L-P has 128 plants and mills throughout the United States.
</TEXT>
