<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NewsweekCuts     04-08 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Newsweek Cuts,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newsweek to End Campus, Health Editions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newsweek magazine has decided to end its special
editions, Newsweek on Campus and Newsweek on Health, both of which
have been losing money.
   The decision was disclosed to the magazines' staffs on Thursday,
said Diana Pearson, communications director of Newsweek, a
subsidiary of Washington Post Co. No editorial staffers will lose
their jobs but six advertising salespeople for the publications
will be let go, she said.
   The publications' revenue came solely from advertising.
   Newsweek on Health, a quarterly that prints 500,000 copies and
mails them to doctors' and dentists' offices, will bow out after
the spring issue.
   Newsweek on Campus will have two more editions, in May and
September. Its 1.3 million copies are inserted into school
newspapers at more than 200 colleges and universities and also are
mailed to students who subscribe to Newsweek.
   To cope with a 20 percent rise in printing and postage costs,
Newsweek also will raise its basic subscription rate by about 10
percent. The weekly's circulation is 94 percent by subscription and
6 percent at the $2 cover price at newsstands.
   Newsweek's current circulation is a record 3,198,000, Pearson
said.
</TEXT>
