<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted some spotty gains today,
struggling to extend its rally of the past three sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 81.57 points over
the last three trading days, rose 6.46 to 2,068.63 by 2 p.m. today
on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 792 up, 625 down and
498 unchanged.
   The market has benefited lately from signs that the dollar has
steadied in foreign-exchange, reducing fears that the Federal
Reserve might soon tighten credit.
   In the credit markets today, prices of long-term government
bonds showed some moderate gains, putting their yields in the 8.75
percent range.
   Brokers also say investors are looking for generally strong
corporate earnings reports for the first quarter over the next few
weeks.
   With all that, however, many analysts remain skeptical about the
market's chances to launch a sustained rally toward last year's
highs.
   Staley Continental led the active list and jumped 5} to 37\.
Tate & Lyle PLC of Great Britain announced a $32-a-share offer for
the company's stock.
   Archer Daniels Midland, another company in the corn-processing
business, rose ~ to 22].
   Quantum Corp. fell 1 to 10\ in the over-the-counter market. The
company said it would have a loss for the quarter and fiscal year
ended March 31 arising from a one-time charge related to a
changeover in its disk drive production facilities.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .55 to 150.83. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .06 at 299.32.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 104 million shares with two
hours to go.
