<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OSHA-Testing     04-08 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA-Testing,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testing Firm Wins 14-Year Battle With Federal Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Baltimore-based electrical testing company
has won a 14-year battle with the U.S. Occupational Safety and
Health Administration and broken two other companies' hold on the
U.S. market for product testing.
   MET Laboratories Inc. tried for more than a decade to get the
federal agency to set standards for the national accreditation of
product testing firms, and change a regulation that specifically
listed two laboratories and thus kept others out.
   After settling two lawsuits brought in federal district court by
MET, OSHA on Tuesday will publish standards for accreditation in
the Federal Register .
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' said Leonard Frier, MET's
founder and president.
   The existing, and soon to be defunct, regulation says that
testing shall be done by a nationally-recognized company, such as
Underwriters Laboratories, Inc. and Factory Mutual Engineering Corp.
   Frier said that for many years Underwriters Laboratories, Inc.
has had a virtual monopoly on the sort of electrical testing his
company does. That firm, established by the insurance industry in
1890, was not a party to any of the legal actions.
   ``The only thing they're guilty of,'' Frier said, ``is running a
great public relations effort.''
   Frier's objections in correspondence and the lawsuits has been
to the specific reference to UL, which tests more than 12,500
products, including consumer electrical appliances, and Boston-area
FM, which primarily tests fire safety products.
   He said OSHA's regulation kept companies like his from
certifying the safety of products that OSHA itself will recognize
as proper for the workplace, said Frier.
   UL, which has headquarters in North Brook, Ill., and additional
laboratories in New York, California and North Carolina, had no
comment Thursday on OSHA's setting a time for the publication of
new standards.
   Founded by insurance companies, UL now is an independent,
not-for-profit corporation.
   Norwood, Mass.-based FM also had no comment Friday.
   The Baltimore businessman first requested that OSHA set
standards for accrediting testing firms in March 1974. His firm,
which depends on field testing rather than new-product testing for
its revenues, was growing and for several years he did not press
the matter with OSHA.
   Then in May 1982 Frier brought suit against the Secretary of
Labor, who has ultimate responsibility for OSHA. Before the suit
came to trial, OSHA settled the legal action by agreeing to
re-write an existing reference to accreditation by March 1984.
   Although OSHA agreed that it would change its regulation, it did
not and last June MET went back to federal court, charging that
OSHA had breached the settlement. In December, a federal judge
directed OSHA to comply with the settlement and set a time limit
for publication of standards.
   Joseph E. Pipkin, the Towson resident who heads OSHA's office of
electrical and electronics safety standards, said Thursday that
part of the long delay was due to ``the number of reviews that are
necessary for something like this.''
   He said there was agreement at OSHA ``several years ago'' that
its regulation ``kept other companies out, but for various reasons
the changes just never moved forward.''
   MET also has a branch in Burlington, N.J., in suburban
Philadelphia. It has 125 employees and annual revenues of about
$3.5 million.
</TEXT>
