<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BankError     04-08 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bank Error,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$80 Million Grocery Leaves Couple Overdrawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No matter how many prime ribs or steaks
Carol Armstrong placed in her shopping cart, her husband knew the
grocery trip did not cost what his bank account indicated _ $80
million.
   ``I was a little surprised. I knew it was a mistake,'' said
Richard Armstrong, 41, on Friday.
   An innocent shopping trip March 23 to a local supermarket cost
$121.78, but a bank error added another $80 million to the
purchase, making it perhaps the most expensive grocery trip in
history.
   Mrs. Armstrong had paid for the groceries with an automated
teller card from Wells Fargo Bank.
   Armstrong, an electronics technician for the Bay Area Rapid
Transit District, said he realized something was wrong several days
later when he couldn't withdraw money from their account.
   He tried unsuccessfully several times to withdraw money. Then,
somewhat perplexed, he called up his balance.
   ``This huge number with a minus sign comes spilling out,''
Armstrong said. Since the automated teller only goes up to $1
million, the machine showed his account overdrawn for that amount.
   Despite this shock, Armstrong wanted to purchase some flags and
went to a flag store. ``I said `I think I'm a million dollars
short, so can I write a check?''' Since the owner knew him,
Armstrong was allowed to write a check.
   He then called his bank's 24-hour hotline to notify them of the
mistake. The bank, he said, insisted the Armstrongs had mistakenly
written a check for $80 million. He noted, however, that
$80,000,121.78 had been deducted from their account.
   Armstrong finally deduced that the bank's mistake stemmed from
the $121.78 check for the grocery trip. Still, Armstrong was left
without money last weekend.
   ``I was penniless. I had to rob my kid's piggy banks,'' he said.
   Wells Fargo corrected the Armstrongs' bank balance on Tuesday. A
bank spokeswoman said it was a clerical error.
   Armstrong said that even though he realized it was a mistake, it
was hard to be without money on Easter weekend for his family,
including his two children.
   ``It's pretty tough to convice people, `Hey I'm $80 million
dollars short, can you lend me a hundred dollars,''' he said.
</TEXT>
