<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EasternTraffic     04-08 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Eastern Traffic,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Reports 20 Percent Drop In Passenger Miles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines announced that the number of
paying passenger miles it flew in March and its passenger volume
dropped 20 percent from the same month a year earlier.
   Eastern said Friday that it flew 2.82 billion revenue passenger
miles in March, down from 3.53 billion in March 1987.
   A revenue passenger mile, or RPM, represents one paying
passenger flown one mile and is used to determine an airline's
capacity.
   Passenger volume for March also fell 20 percent, to 3.51 million
passengers from 4.39 million a year earlier, Eastern reported.
   ``The figures are very misleading,'' said Eastern spokeswoman
Paula Musto. ``Last year our passenger volume was artificially high
because we were in the midst of our MaxSaver (deep disount) fares.
We had fares as low as $79 to New York City (from Miami) _ that
really increased our discretionary travelers.''
   She also said Eastern had more seats available a year ago.
   The airline's capacity declined 13.1 percent in March, to 4.50
billion available seat miles from 5.18 billion a year earlier.
   Last month, U.S. District Judge John Pratt in Washington
declared Eastern in contempt of court for trying to sell its
profitable Northeast shuttle to giant Texas Air Corp., Eastern's
parent.
   Eastern's management remains embroiled in negotiations with its
machinists union, which is fighting $490 million in proposed job
cuts at the airline.
   Ms. Musto said these problems had nothing to do with the
declining traffic figures.
</TEXT>
