<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HotelAuction     04-08 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Auction,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auction Of Fort Lauderdale Motels Falls Flat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many developers nibbled, but few
bit at beachfront hotels for sale at an auction designed to breathe
new life into a stretch of sand and surf battered by slumping
tourism and broken spring breaks.
   Only two of 11 properties sold at the private auction Thursday
night that was marked by bids thousands of dollars below what hotel
owners were seeking.
   ``These bidders don't realize they're buying Fort Lauderdale
Beach, not the backwoods of Maine,'' said Ed Wrobleski, a
Massachusetts factory worker who had sold his home and invested his
life savings last year to buy a hotel for $650,000.
   His property fetched a top bid of just $350,000.
   ``I'm not going to give my property away,'' Wrobleski said.
``We'll just hang in there and do the best we can.''
   Tourism officials and real estate analysts had viewed the
auction as a test of private interest in redeveloping the city's
beachfront strip.
   The city of Fort Lauderdale is planning a $13.8 million beach
revitalization as it tries to turn the beach from a spring break
haven into an area of luxury resorts. That plan hinges on private
development.
   ``If it busts, the negative connotation will be that the
potential to upgrade the property just isn't there,'' said Thomas
Powers, executive vice president of Goodkin Research Corp. in Fort
Lauderdale.
   The auction at the Bahia Mar Resort and Yachting Center drew
about 30 registered bidders and some 600 spectators.
   An 81-unit beachfront property sold for $2.1 million and an
18-unit motel sold for $542,000.
   Owners of the 11 properties agreed to the auction because the
decline of spring break has brought declining profits. They say
city officials in the past few years have restricted the students'
activities so much they have chosen to travel to other vacation
spots.
   ``I've worked hard, but after a while you get burned out on
beating your head against the wall,'' said Roger Handevidt, one
motel owner. ``I've tried to attract people down here and to
increase tourism in the area only to be shot down by the city.''
   Each property owner contributed $3,000 to an international
marketing campaign for the auction, to which co-organizer Fisher
Auction Co. Inc. added about $10,000.
   ``When you're talking about all-cash deals, it's difficult,''
said Lamar Fisher, senior vice president of the auction company.
``But we're hoping to negotiate several more deals in the next few
days.''
</TEXT>
