<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-SpringerFeud     04-08 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Springer Feud,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Springer Power Struggle Heats Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Cartel Office dealt a
serious blow to three shareholders' joint attempt to gain majority
control of Axel Springer Verlag, West Germany's largest publishing
company.
   Franz and Frieder Burda, who have their own printing operations,
and media entrepreneur Leo Kirch pooled their Springer shares last
month in an effort to forge a majority.
   But the Cartel Office said Friday that their combined shares had
fallen short of that goal.
   ``At the moment the pool has not had much of an effect. Leo
Kirch is still a long way even from 25 percent (of the shares),''
said Hartwig Wangemann, a spokesman for the Cartel Office.
   Meanwhile, a spokesman for Springer employees said workers would
fight attempts by Kirch and the Burdas to gain control of the
company.
   The spokesman, Rolf Juergensen, said employees are worried that
Kirch would lead the company into extensive involvement with
electronic media, which could mean a loss of jobs for Springer's
print workers.
   The highly successful Springer empire includes the Bild tabloid
with a daily circulation of about 5 million and dozens of other
mass-circulation publications.
   Springer Chairman Peter Tamm urged that ``for the benefit of the
company, all participants (in the power struggle) reach a rational
solution as soon as possible.''
   Addressing a meeting of Springer employee representatives, Tamm
also said any solution should give top consideration to ``security
for workers ... and to a stable leadership.''
   Executives of the publishing house have been squabbling ever
since the death of company founder Axel Springer in 1985.
   Under a complicated formula, Springer's heirs and executors were
given control of 27.1 percent of the company shares, the Burda
brothers 25.9 percent and Kirch 10 percent. The rest were sold to
the public.
   Kirch had maintained that he gained support from the owners of
another 16 percent of Springer stock, which would give him and the
Burdas a combined majority.
   Friede Springer, the widow of the founder, has been fighting the
attempts by the Burdas and Kirch to gain majority control.
   Kirch is involved in film distribution and production and other
media areas. The Burda brothers own printing plants in West Germany.
</TEXT>
