<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Banks     04-08 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Banks,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Chicago Reports Increased Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   First Chicago Corp., the nation's 10th largest bank holding
company, said Friday that its first-quarter profit more than
doubled from a year ago even though it raised its loan-loss
reserves to cover troubled Third World debt.
   Net income for the three months ended March 31 totaled $141.5
million, or $2.38 per share, compared with earnings of $63.9
million, or $1.06 a share, in 1987.
   Chairman Barry F. Sullivan said improvement was made across the
board during the period.
   ``Our performance this quarter was outstanding in all aspects of
the consumer and middle-market banks _ the superregional segment of
First Chicago _ as well as in the global corporate bank,'' he said
in a statement.
   Net interest income rose 14 percent, to $315.3 million from
$277.9 million last year, while interest expense totaled $615.92
million, up from $515.92 million.
   First Chicago said it increased its provision for loan losses to
$100 million from $75 million, half of which went to cover shaky
foreign debt.
   ``We are continuing to see improvements in credit quality ...
and we are continuing to maintian one of the strongest reserve
positions for troubled-country debtors among our peers,'' Sullivan
noted.
   Quarterly non-interest income totaled $249.0 million, compared
with $173.1 million last year. Non-interest expense rose to $311.5
million form $265.4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
