<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Grolier-Hachette     04-08 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grolier-Hachette,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hachette Says It Would Sell Grolier's Childcraft Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French publisher Hachette S.A. said Friday it
has agreed to sell Grolier Inc.'s Childcraft Education Corp., which
markets educational toys by direct mail, if its $444 million
takeover bid for Grolier is successful.
   Grolier, meanwhile, said its board would meet on Monday to
consider Hachette's latest offer, president Andrew J. Reinhart said.
   On Wall Street, Grolier was unchanged at $26.37{ a share on the
New York Stock Exchange, or $2.37{ a share more than Hachette's
latest offer.
   Hachette said Walt Disney Co., the entertainment giant based in
Los Angeles, has tenatively agreed to buy the Childcraft unit for
$52 million, provided that Hachette's current tender offer for
Grolier is successful.
   Hachette, based in Paris, has offered $24 a share for the 18.5
million shares of Grolier's common stock that it does not already
control. The tender offer is scheduled to expire April 14. Hachette
and affiliates already own about 957,000 shares of Grolier stock.
   Grolier, which publishes encyclopedias and is based in Danbury,
Conn., has taken no position on the sweetened offer, but had
rejected as inadequate Hachette's March 13 offer of $21 a share.
   The company said at that time that it would pursue talks with
other interested parties to negotiate a sale for a satisfactory
price.
   Hachette boosted its tender offer to $24 a share on March 31.
   Grolier acquired Childcraft in 1986, and it made a profit on
sales of $51 million in 1987, said Reinhart, who is also chief
operating officer.
</TEXT>
