<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hunts-Banks     04-08 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunts-Banks,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hunts, Banks Near Settlement of Dispute Involving $1.5 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dallas Hunt brothers and the 23 foreign and
domestic banks they are battling are nearing settlement in their
dispute over $1.5 billion in loans, attorneys said.
   Both sides have asked a federal bankruptcy judge to suspend
reorganization hearings on the Hunts' Placid Oil Co. until the
negotiations are complete, attorneys said.
   ``Negotiations are at the stage where the major parties have
come to what I call a handshake deal,'' Placid attorney Henry W.
Simon said Thursday. ``That deal is not in writing, and the
handshake is not now binding, but it does represent at least a
conclusion of an intensive series of all the Placid-related
issues.''
   Neither Simon nor First RepublicBank Corp. attorney Paul Wickes
_ key negotiators for the case _ would discuss the substance of the
negotiations. But the settlement would have to include what to do
about $200 million in penalty interest, attorney fees and costs the
banks claim against Placid.
   Nelson Bunker Hunt, William Herbert Hunt and Lamar Hunt filed
suit in federal court nearly two years ago against the 23 banks,
alleging they were fraudulently squeezing the Hunts into accepting
increasingly difficult loan terms for a $1.5 billion debt.
   A countersuit was filed by the banks, demanding immediate
payment on what the banks contended were legitimate loans in
default.
   Six weeks later, the banks posted for foreclosure key Hunt
assets securing the defaulted loans. The Hunts protected themselves
by placing Placid and William Herbert's personal trust under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code. They later did the same
with the other brothers' trusts.
   Both sides have since been warring in federal and bankruptcy
courts, maneuvering for a possible death blow or at least some kind
of legal advantage.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Harold Abramson in January allowed the
banks a $7.8 million first lien against revenues from the Hunts'
Green Canyon drilling project in the Gulf of Mexico.
   The lien represented money Placid had spent on Green Canyon in
violation of a court order. When the Hunts experienced cost
overruns _ including the loss of nine miles of pipe being towed to
the site _ the project's outside investors declined to cover the
loss.
   The outside investors, Dallas Mavericks owner Don Carter and
Oklahoma media giant Ed Gaylord, said they would commit more money
only if the bankruptcy judge put those funds ahead of the banks'
prior lien.
   The banks' desire to close Green Canyon, and Abramson's balking
at considering the need for additional money an emergency,
``brought Placid to the table,'' one bank attorney said.
   Without Green Canyon, Placid's reorganization plan would be
untenable and, by default, Abramson would have accepted the bank
plan calling for the outright sale of Placid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0265 </DOCNO>
