<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USAToday 1stLd-Writethru   04-08 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USA Today, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0129,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gannett President Predicts 1988 Loss for USA Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS last graf to CORRECT figures for Gannett non-daily
newspapers and TV stations; also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USA Today will probably lose money in 1988,
following a profitable quarter at the end of 1987, John J. Curley,
Gannett Co. Inc. president and chief executive officer says.
   Curley, speaking to reporters Thursday after a meeting with
securities analysts, attributed the projected loss to expected
increases in the cost of newsprint. Newspaper executives expect
newsprint costs in 1988 to be 18 percent to 20 percent higher than
last year.
   The national daily, founded by Gannett on Sept. 15, 1982,
reported its first quarterly profit in the three months of 1987.
   USA Today has a circulation of 1.6 million. It is one of 90
daily newspapers, 35 non-daily newspapers and a newspaper magazine
published by Gannett. The company also operates 10 television
stations, 16 radio stations, a news service and an outdoor
advertising company.
</TEXT>
