<DOCNO> AP880408-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     04-08 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0194</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market extended its rally of the past
three sessions today with a strong advance that carried the Dow
Jones industrial average to a new high since the October crash.
   The market has benefited lately from signs that the dollar has
steadied in foreign-exchange, reducing fears that the Federal
Reserve might soon tighten credit.
   In the credit markets today, prices of long-term government
bonds rose more than $5 for each $1,000 in face value, putting
their yields in the 8.7-8.75 percent range.
   Analysts said traders were anticipating the possibility of
favorable news next week on the dollar and international trade. It
could come, they say, from a meeting of the so-called Group of
Seven industrialized nations in Washington, or from the Commerce
Department's monthly report on the U.S. trade balance for February.
   Advance estimates call for the trade data to show continuing
improvement from the record levels it reached last fall.
   Brokers also say investors are looking for generally strong
corporate earnings reports for the first quarter over the next few
weeks.
</TEXT>
