<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1705EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-08 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Predece BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Friday while the
British pound held its ground despite an apparent attempt by the
Bank of England to stem its rise by slashing interest rates.
   Gold prices were higher. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold was bid at $449 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up 15 cents an
ounce from $448.85 late Thursday.
   Trading in the dollar remained hemmed in a narrow range before a
meeting next week in Washington, D.C., of the Group of Seven major
industrialized democracies.
   Dealers said they expect the finance ministers of the United
States, Britain, Japan, West Germany, France, Italy and Canada to
reaffirm their wish to keep the dollar stable.
   ``The central banks are very happy about what they've done over
the past few months. They've taken a lot of the speculative
character out of the market _which is bad for the traders, of
course,'' said Peter Wild, first vice president of Switzerland's
Bank Julius Baer & Co. in New York.
   The foreign exchange market was taken by surprise when the Bank
of England engineered a half-point cut in the commercial banks'
base lending rate to 8 percent at midday in London.
   But the rate cut ``appears to have gotten the same reaction as
yesterday's intervention,'' said Ken de la Salle, a senior manager
at National Westminster Bank PLC's foreign exchange department in
London.
   The Bank of England intervened Thursday to stem sterling's rise,
also with minimal results.
   Other traders pointed out that British interest rates are still
higher than in other countries. That makes pound-denominated
investments more attactive and boosts demand for the currency.
   In London, the pound was quoted at $1.8755 compared with late
Thursday's $1.8670. Later in New York the pound finished the day at
$1.8757, unchanged from late Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 0.52 yen to a closing 125.18 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at a higher rate of 125.50 yen. At the end of the
trading day in New York, the dollar finished at 125.68, down from
125.72 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.6742 West German marks, down from 1.6776;
1.3842 Swiss francs, down from 1.3864; 1.2469 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.2483; 5.6775 French francs, down from 5.6885; and
1,241.13 Italian lire, down from 1,243.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.6725 West German marks, down from 1.6810; 1.3825 Swiss
francs, down from 1.3897; 5.6715 French francs, down from 5.7022;
1.8790 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8865; 1,241.75 Italian lire,
down from 1,246.50; and 1.2478 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2448.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $451.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $447.75. In Zurich, gold was rose to
a bid $449.50 an ounce compared with $448 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.06 to close at a bid $450.72
an ounce.
   At the end of the trading day in New York, gold bullion for
current delivery was bid at $451.60 a troy ounce late in the day,
up from $450.80 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to a late bid price of
$6.48 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $6.40. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to a late bid of
$6.410 from $6.407 late Thursday.
