<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MicrosoftSuit     04-08 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Microsoft Suit,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Microsoft Countersues Apple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp., answering Apple Computer Inc.'s
copyright lawsuit, has filed a suit seeking unspecified damages
from Apple for alleged breach of contract, slander and interfering
with Microsoft's relationships with its customers.
   Microsoft also asked for punitive damages against Apple plus
payment of attorney fees in its suit, which was filed Thursday in
U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California in San
Jose.
   The Microsoft action was in response to a March 17 suit filed in
the same court against it and Hewlett-Packard Corp. by Apple, which
charged them with infringing upon copyright audio and visual
display technology for Macintosh personal computers.
   Apple's civil suit said software products made by
Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft make use of Macintosh technology
without permission.
   Microsoft's counterclaims and answer asked that Apple's suit be
dismissed. It also sought damages against the Cupertino, Calif.,
computer maker for breach of contract between the two companies,
for interference with Microsoft's contractual relations with other
companies, for harming Microsoft's ``prospective business
advantage,'' for slander of Microsoft's title to its Windows 2.03
software product and for violations of California unfair business
and practices laws.
   Apple spokesmen failed to return phone calls Friday seeking
comment on the lawsuit.
   Apple's suit had said Microsoft's Windows 2.03, a graphics
program used with Hewlett-Packard software, are ``illegal copies of
the Macintosh audio-visual works and exceed the limited license
rights Apple previously granted to Microsoft.''
   The suit asked that Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard be prevented
from copying, selling or marketing Hewlett-Packard's New Wave
software and Windows 2.03. Apple also sought unspecified damages.
   Windows operates with IBM and compatible computers using
Microsoft's MS-DOS operating system. New Wave provides an
audio-visual display upon which applications software can be run.
   In its countersuit, Microsoft said Windows 2.03 doesn't infringe
on any Apple copyright or patent and that Microsoft didn't
contribute to any alleged copyright infringement by Hewlett-Packard.
   The software company also asked the court to require Apple to
live up to a 1985 settlement agreement concerning the use of the
visual displays in question.
</TEXT>
