<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Staley-Tate 2ndLd-Writethru   04-08 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Staley-Tate, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tate & Lyle Launches $1.33 Billion Tender Offer For Staley</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, But there ... with 5 new grafs to provide
closing stock prices and comments from Tate news conference in
Illinois. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``Tate & Lyle said ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tate & Lyle PLC, a major British sugar refiner and
distributor, announced Friday a $1.33 billion cash tender offer for
Staley Continental Inc., the second largest refiner of corn
sweeteners in the United States.
   Tate & Lyle, which already owns nearly 5 percent of Staley's
stock, said it was offering $32 a share for all the remaining
common stock.
   Staley Continental, which is based in Rolling Meadows, Ill.,
will have no comment on any aspect of the offer until its lawyers
examine the proposal, said spokesman David Satterfield.
   But there was speculation the bidding may go higher. Staley
climbed $5.87{ a share to $37.37{ in active trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Lynton Wilson, North American managing director for Tate & Lyle,
said at a Springfield, Ill., news conference that the $32 price was
fair.
   ``We prepared to launch our bid at a time when the price for
Staley shares was in the low 20s,'' Wilson said. ``I don't know
what may happen to the price on the market but we believe the $32
is a full and fair offer for the shares of the company.''
   Wilson said Tate & Lyle's interest in the company ``is a
fundamental interest in the business,'' not a passing financial
interest.
   ``We're not financial entrepreneurs or corporate raiders,'' he
said. ``We're manufacturing people involved in the processing
businesses not only here in North America but in other countries as
well.''
   Tate & Lyle said Staley had previously proposed that Tate
increase its stake acquired in November and become a more
substantial minority shareholder.
   But Tate & Lyle said it decided to launch the tender offer
instead.
   The acquisition would give Tate & Lyle its first interest in the
U.S. corn sweetener market. Tate & Lyle said it would become the
only supplier of all three types of sugar _ corn, beet and cane _
in the United States.
   ``We are confident that, as part of Tate & Lyle's North American
division, the performance and competitive position of Staley's corn
activities will be significantly enhanced,'' said Tate & Lyle
Chairman Neil Shaw.
   The tender offer represents a 78 percent premium to Staley's
share price of $18 a share before the Tate & Lyle stake was
announced.
   Staley's stock price was boosted in March by speculation that a
foreign concern would launch a bid for the company.
   Staley Continental is a holding company formed in early 1985 for
the A.E. Staley Manufacturing Co., a leading corn processor, and
CFS Continental Inc., a food service supplier acquired in late 1984.
   Tate & Lyle said Staley is the second largest refiner of corn
sweeteners in the United States behind Archer-Daniels-Midland Co.,
based in Decatur, Ill.
   Staley's principal corn product is high fructose corn syrup,
known as HFCS. The company has around 25 percent of the $1 billion
a year U.S. market for HFCS sales, Tate & Lyle said.
   In a letter to Staley released in New York, Tate's Shaw said
Staley had moved away from its core business of corn processing in
recent years, scaled back corn sweetener operations and expanded
into foodservice distribution.
   ``In our view it is time to return Staley to basics,'' Shaw
wrote.
   Tate & Lyle said it intends to sell Staley's food distribution
business, which Staley acquired in 1984 for $396 million, and that
it was prepared to consider any offers immediately.
   The proceeds of that sale would be used to reduce Tate & Lyle's
debt incurred by the acquisition, it said.
   Tate & Lyle also said it planned, after the merger, to move the
company's headquarters to Decatur, where its corn wet milling
operations have been based for years.
   Tate & Lyle said it began legal action in the United States to
overturn takeover defenses established by Staley, including a
benefit package for its senior management.
   Tate & Lyle said the offer will be partly funded by the sale of
new shares to its existing shareholders, cash resources and a bank
loan.
   The acquisition and stock issue must be approved by Tate &
Lyle's shareholders, who are to meet on May 3. The tender offer is
scheduled to expire May 5 unless extended.
   Staley earned $57.3 million on revenue of $3.4 billion in the
year ended in September.
   Tate and Lyle had a pre-tax profit of 92 million pounds, or
about $173 million, on revenue of 1.7 billion pounds, or $3.2
billion, in the same time period.
</TEXT>
