<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IBMPatents 1stLd-Writethru   04-08 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM Patents, 1st Ld-Writethru,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Higher Ceilings On Patent License Fees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf, Under the ..., to UPDATE with
lawyer, analyst calling fees reasonable; picks up 10th graf, Many
companies .....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp., moving to
earn more money on its intellectual property, said Friday it will
raise the ceiling on its patent license fees to 5 percent from the
current 1 percent.
   The decision is likely to put pressure on the profit margins of
companies that require licenses to make products compatible with
those of IBM, the world's largest computer company.
   IBM holds 9,000 U.S. patents and more than 23,000 counterpart
patents around the world. The decision does not affect existing
license agreements.
   IBM's announcement came just weeks before the expected
announcement of computers compatible with IBM's year-old Personal
System-2 personal computer.
   ``They certainly intend to cash in on their development effort''
on the Personal System-2, said Jack W. Wilson, an analyst for
Dataquest Inc. in San Jose, Calif.
   IBM also said it was reaffirming its long-standing practice of
making its patents generally available for licensing to others
under reasonable terms and conditions.
   Some companies refuse to license some of their patents or
license them selectively, to particular companies, IBM spokesman
John Mihalec noted. He said IBM makes its patents generally
available ``because it's good for the industry.''
   Under the new rates, licensees will pay a maximum of 1 percent
of sales revenue on a product using a single IBM patent. They will
pay up to 5 percent of sales revenue on products using multiple
patents, depending on the number of patents used and the extent of
their use.
   Under the old rates, which were last changed 10 years ago, the
maximum royalty was 1 percent regardless of the number of patents
used.
   License fees of 3 to 5 percent are fairly common in industry,
said David Carnevale, director of the microcomputer service of
InfoCorp, a consulting and research company based in Cupertino,
Calif.
   ``I would say that's in the ballpark,'' agreed Richard L.
Bernacchi, an intellectual-property attorney in Los Angeles. He
said patents have become more valuable since the federal court
system has become more consistent in enforcing them.
   Many companies have cross-licensing agreements with IBM that
allow the companies to use each other's patents without fees for
specified periods. In other cases, the agreements provide for free
use of certain patents and require payment for use of others.
   ``Any licensee can look at the license they have from IBM and
figure out what they're covered for,'' Mihalec said.
   Tandy Corp., one of the companies rumored to be preparing to
announce a Personal System-2 computer, has a long-standing
cross-licensing agreement with IBM, according to Ed Juge, director
of market planning.
   Amdahl Corp., which makes big mainframe computers that run the
same software as IBM's mainframes, also has a cross-licensing
agreement with IBM, which expires at the end of 1991, spokesman
Bill Stewart said.
   ``It will have no current effect on us,'' Stewart said.
   IBM noted that a patent license is not a license to copy
products that use the covered patent. It is not a transfer of the
technology or trade secrets that went into developing a product and
it does not allow a licensee to infringe other forms of
intellectual property rights such as copyrights.
   IBM has said it has applied for both patents and copyrights on
Micro Channel Architecture, the internal data pathway that is a
critical part of its new Personal System-2.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DiscountRealEstate     04-08 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Discount Real Estate,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discount Real Estate Broker Closing Doors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate company that tried to be a
maverick by selling homes for fees well below the prevailing rate
is going out of business eight months after opening.
   Barclay & Stubbs is being forced to close its doors mainly
because it could not attract top agents, Elizabeth F. Kinzly, the
company's president, said Thursday.
   The real estate agency was offering to sell houses for a 3{
percent commission, sharply below the going rate of 6 percent.
Buyers were also being offered a 1 percent bonus for purchasing a
home listed by Barclay & Stubbs.
   Agents for the company were offered a salary instead of the
standard commission _ a factor that others in the real estate
business had predicted would hinder Barclay & Stubbs' recruitment
efforts.
   Kinzly said she believed agents were reluctant to join the
company because of fear of something new and concern about how they
would be viewed by others in the business.
   If Barclay represented both the buyer and the seller, the agency
would net only a 2{ percent commission. Other brokerages were
offered a 2 percent shared commission, so Barclay's net commission
could be as little as half a percent.
   Although real estate commissions are negotiable, most are 6
percent, shared equally between the listing and selling brokers.
   The company had sold four or five houses, and had deposits on
another six, Kinzly said, adding that many of the sales had been on
a shared-commission basis.
   A few dozen homeowners had listed their houses with the agency,
and ``things were picking up a lot,'' said Kinzly.
   She said she disagreed with Chairman Benjamin Morris' decision
to quit now. Kinzly said she would have liked to see the company
remain in business at least through the spring house-selling season.
   ``That could have made it go,'' she said.
   The company had been at the center of a controversy in the real
estate community after it sued four area brokers in February,
charging unfair trade practices and conspiracy to restrain trade.
   The other brokers had offered Barclay a lower shared commission
than that offered to other agencies.
   Last month, a judge granted a motion by two of the defendants to
have the case referred to the Greater New Haven Board of Realtors
for arbitration. One of the other companies reached a settlement
with Barclay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-08 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cattle Futures Advance Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle futures advanced sharply Friday on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, reflecting expectations of improved beef demand.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures moved higher, energy
futures declined and precious metals were slightly higher.
   Livestock traders got clipped earlier in the week with limit
declines in some cattle deliveries.
   ``Now we've gone a long way to return a little optimism to the
market,'' said Philip Stanley, an analyst in Chicago with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc.
   There seemed to be a general belief that cash cattle prices will
improve next week along with wholesale beef, he said.
   ``The expectations are for improved demand throughout the beef
trade,'' said Stanley. ``There should be a return of retail
interest in beef and the packers will have to buy live animals
because they've done little of it in recent days.''
   Hog and pork belly futures also did well, in part because of
spillover support from the cattle pit, Stanley said.
   ``Also, a lot of traders are expecting a seasonal bottom in hog
prices,'' he said.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to 1.47 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in April at 74.77 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .10 cent lower to .58 cent higher with April at 80.10
cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent lower to .70 cent higher
with April at 45.37 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .70
cent to 1.15 cents higher with May at 54.47 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices advanced on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   Soybeans set contracts high early in the session, then in a wild
finish slumped to the day's lows before reaching new highs again.
   Large speculative buying, led by C&D Commodities Inc., accounted
for much of the activity, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``It was a day of wild gyrations,'' he said. ``There were some
big sellers, too, but I think this market does not want to go
down.''
   The market is expecting a government report coming out Monday to
show a further drawdown in soybean stocks, said Lespinasse.
   ``This would give a very low stocks-to-usage ratio,'' he said.
``So if any problems develop with the weather later this spring or
summer, this market could explode to the upside.''
   Wheat and corn futures also were higher, partly in response to
the performance in the bean pit. Wheat also got help from export
activity.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 4{ cents higher with the May contract
at $3.16} a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 cents higher with May at
$2.09 a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 3{ cents higher with May at
$1.66} a bushel; and soybeans were 5 cents to 8 cents higher with
May at $6.78 a bushel.
   Energy futures took a dip, heading into the weekend meeting of
the OPEC pricing committee.
   ``Up to this morning there was some speculation that there might
be a surprise'' coming out of the meeting that would send prices
higher, said Michael Rothman, senior oil analyst in New York with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   A change of feeling came on remarks by OPEC President Rilwanu
Lukman, who indicated the pricing committee would meet only one
day, said Rothman.
   The implication is that the session would be a perfunctory one,
with no recommendation for a special OPEC meeting or for production
cuts.
   ``Those anticipations were put to rest today by Lukman's
remarks,'' said Rothman.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 18 cents to 20 cents lower with the May contract
at $16.88 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent to .57 cent lower with
May at 45.46 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to
.45 cent lower with May at 48.77 cents a gallon.
   Stock index futures at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange advanced
with the June contract for the Standard & Poor's 500 index settling
at 269.90, up 2.30 points. The underlying spot index was up 3.27 at
269.43.
   Precious metals futures advanced slightly on the Commodity
Exchange in New York.
   Gold was 70 cents to $1 higher with the June contract at $453.70
a troy ounce; and silver was .3 cent to .4 cent higher with May at
$6.438 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
