<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HughesAircraft     04-08 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hughes Aircraft,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hughes to Buy Flight-Simulator Firm for $283 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hughes Aircraft Co., a unit of General Motors
Corp., said Thursday it has agreed to buy Rediffusion Similation,
one of the world's largest suppliers of flight simulators, for $283
million.
   Rediffusion, which is based in Crawley, England, and has
operations in Arlington, Texas, is owned by BET Ltd., a
conglomerate headquartered in London.
   Rediffusion manufactures 40 percent of the military flight
simulators in the Untied Kingdom and 35 percent of the simulators
for training pilots of U.S. and other foreign airlines.
   Hughes is one of the world's leading suppliers of
high-technology electronics for military, scientific and commercial
use.
   Acquisition of Rediffusion will expand Hughes' existing
operations in the pilot-training field. Hughes currently builds a
weapons tactics trainer for the F-A18 jet and the mission trainer
for the F-14A jet.
   Rediffusion, with a work force of 2,500 and annual sales of
about $260 million, will be operated as a subsidiary of Hughes.
   ``Hughes expects that simulators will be used increasingly by
military customers to train pilots and operators as defense budgets
flatten out,'' said Albert Wheelon, chairman and chief executive of
Hughes, adding that the acquisition will ``make Hughes a a major
factor in this field.''
   The current world market for military and civilian simulators is
$3 billion a year and that is expected to grow to $4 billion a year
by 1993.
   Hughes said it expects the use of simulators will be expanded
into non-aircraft areas, such as factory automation and machine
repair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
