<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 0620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TextileImports     04-08 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textile Imports,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Manufacturers Urge Legislation To Protect Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheaply-manufactured textiles from China
and other nations fueled a 17 percent increase in the textile trade
deficit in 1987 while taking away jobs from Americans, industry
representatives said Thursday.
   Members of the American Textile Manufacturers Institute, meeting
here through Saturday, said that unless federal legislation is
passed setting a 1 percent annual ceiling on import growth, textile
production in the United States could cease by the mid-1990s.
   Imported clothing now accounts for 54 percent of all garments
sold in the United States, according to institute figures.
   About 2.2 million people make their living in the nation's
textile industry, according to institute figures. This represents a
loss of about 350,000 jobs since 1980, including 10,000 jobs lost
in March alone, said Robert G. Laidlaw, president of the group. He
blamed the situation in part of the Reagan Administration's failure
to enforce import quotas.
   Laidlaw urged passage of the Textile and Apparel Trade Act,
which faces a vote in the Senate next month.
   The U.S. imposed an embargo against the Soviet Union last year
after the Soviet Union exported 12 million yards of fabric to the
U.S. instead of the 4 million yards provided under U.S. quotas, he
said. But Laidlaw added the embargo was lifted when Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev visited the U.S. He said a 1988 limit was set at
23.5 million yards.
   ``The government is happily giving away our industry, and people
are not going to re-invest if they don't have confidence,'' said
Laidlaw.
   The primary competition comes from government-subsidized
manufacturers in China, Taiwan, Korea, Hong Kong and other nations
producing textiles for as little as 20 cents an hour in wages.
   ``On an even field, the U.S. industry can compete with anyone,''
said Christopher Bonner, institute spokesman. ``But it can't
compete when governments subsidize exports made by low-wage earners
in deplorable conditions that would be illegal in the U.S. It's
crazy.''
   U.S. Department of Commerce figures show imports of textiles and
apparel in 1987 reached a record $29 billion, while exports totaled
$4 billion. The industry's $24.8 billion trade deficit for textiles
and apparel now equals 14.5 percent of the nation's overall trade
deficit, according to Laidlaw.
   ``If we look at the growth of the nation's overall trade deficit
from 1986 to 1987, one fourth of that diastrous growth has been at
the expense of the U.S. textile and apparel industry and its 2
million employees,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880408-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-QuakerState     04-08 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quaker State,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quaker State Gets Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by a New York-based
investment banking firm said Friday it is offering $695 million to
buy Quaker State Corp., the motor oil refining company.
   Ardshiel Inc. said it is offering $26.50 per share for the Oil
City-based company, which refines and sells Quaker State motor oil,
owns Quaker State Minit-Lube Inc. drive-in automobile lubrication
centers, and manufactures truck lighting systems and automobile
brake lights.
   Quaker State common stock closed at $22.62{ per share, up $1, in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading Friday before
Ardshiel's offer was made public.
   Ardshiel said it currently owns about 3.3 percent interest in
the company. It did not disclose the identities of other investors.
   Quaker State spokesman Ben Faulkner said the company had no
comment on the offer.
   Rumors have been circulating for weeks that an offer was in the
works, although it was expected to be about $30 per share or
higher, said Edward Farmer, a broker with Butcher & Singer in
Pittsburgh.
   Ardshiel said it might be willing to raise the offer. It said it
has enough money to fund the acquisition.
   Dennis McCormick, Ardshiel's senior managing director, said
Ardshiel wanted to continue Quaker State's core businesses.
   ``Surveys indicate that Quaker State Corp. is one of the 10
best-recognized consumer brand names and we believe the value of
that name recognition and Quaker State Corp.'s position have not
been fully developed,'' McCormick said.
   McCormick said Ardshiel would ``accelerate growth'' of the
company's Minit-Lube subsidiary based in Salt Lake City. Faulkner
said the subsidiary, the company's latest area of expansion, has
grown to 280 outlets in 20 states in the last few years.
   Quaker State, founded in 1931 from many small Pennsylvania
refiners and marketing companies, concentrates on the sale of
high-quality motor oil and petrolum byproducts.
   It has about 6,300 employees, including about 450 at its
headquarters and research centers in this Venango County oil center
of about 13,500 people. It also has refineries in Farmers Valley,
McKean County, and in Newell, W.Va.
   Its Truck Lite Inc. subsidiary, based in Jamestown, N.Y.,
manufactures vehicle lighting systems.
   Last year, Quaker State reported a net loss of about $48
million, or $1.82 per common share, on sales of about $848 million,
according to Faulkner.
   Ardshiel said it has been involved in more than a dozen
leveraged buyouts since 1977. In 1986, it was involved in the $1.6
billion leveraged buyout of National Car Rental System Inc. from
Household International Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
