<DOCNO> AP880408-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-88 2138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Disney-Burbank     04-08 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney-Burbank,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney Scraps Plan for $300 Million Burbank Entertainment Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unexpected move, the Walt Disney
Co. scrapped plans Friday for $300 million entertainment complex in
Burbank, and city officials indicated they were looking at other
alternatives including a proposal by Disney rival MCA Inc.
   In a two-page letter to the head of Burbank's redevelopment
agency, Robert Ovrom, Disney said the project wasn't justifiable
economically.
   Based on projected costs and attendance at the planned complex,
``the projected return on Disney's investment simply did not meet
corporate thresholds for an investment of this magnitude and
anticipated business risk,'' the company said.
   Disney spokesman Erwin Okun declined to elaborate on what that
profit threshold is.
   Last May, Disney entered into an agreement with Burbank to
negotiate exclusively to develop 40 acresof city-owned land
alongside the Golden State Freeway, about 15 miles northwest of
downtown Los Angeles.
   Since then, Disney said, the company has invested 22,000
man-hours and spent $2.5 million on planning studies, market
research and related economic analyses.
   The complex was envisioned as including movie backlot tours,
theaters, shopping areas, a hotel, a planetarium, rides and
nightclubs _ a different format that the company's Disneyland theme
park in Anaheim, about 30 miles away in neighboring Orange County.
   The complex was to be about two miles from Disney's crowded
studio and headquarters in Burbank.
   The exclusivity of the negotiating agreement was attacked by
rival entertainment conglomerate MCA Inc., the parent of Universal
Studios and operator of a successful studio backlot tour in nearby
Universal City.
   MCA claimed it had been unfairly barred from making a competing
proposal to develop the Burbank site and has filed suit to block
the Disney-Burbank agreement.
   Ovrom, Burbank's redevelopment chief, said in a three-page
memorandum to the mayor and city council that he felt ``a
tremendous amount of disappointment'' over Disney's decision.
   But he added, ``We are all big boys and big girls, and we know
going into this agreement that it was just a feasibility study ...
We, too, shall immediately shift gears.''
   Ovrom noted that MCA, in its lawsuit, had indicated it was
interested in making a proposal for developing the Burbank site.
   ``I am sure we all anxiously await to see what they will submit
now that Disney is no longer in the picture,'' Ovrom said in the
memorandum.
   MCA spokesman Harold Haas said the company had no comment on its
plans.
   Ovrom said he had no regrets about granting Disney the exclusive
agreement.
   ``The concept that (Disney chairman and chief executive) Michael
Eisner originally envisioned was very exciting and could have been
very special for Burbank,'' Ovrom said in the memo.
   ``Had we turned down Disney's offer to study these
possibilities, we would have gone to our graves always wondering
what might have been.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
